sequence: Metaphone is a phonetic algorithm , published by Lawrence Philips in 1990 , for indexing words by their English pronunciation. It consists of two main components: a sequence of octal consonantals followed by vowel syllables, each representing a phonemic sequence with the prefix  ( ) followed by a semicolon to represent the letter " ; ", followed by a dot to represent the letters " A ". Hindutva, also known as Hindus, is an indigenous Tamil language native to Sri Lanka. Hindutva is composed of at least ten distinct languages that inhabit the Himalayas and Central Himalayas.

The putamen (; from Latin, meaning "nutshell") is a round structure located at the base of the forebrain (telencephalon). The putamen and caudate nucleus together form the dorsal striatum. It is also one of the structures that compose the basal nuclei. Through various pathways, the putamen is connected to the substantia nigra, the globus pallidus, the claustrum, and the thalamus, in addition to many regions of the cerebral cortex. A primary function of the putamen is to regulate movements at various stages (e.g. preparation and execution) and influence various types of learning.

William Tyndale ( ; sometimes spelled Tynsdale , Tindall , Tindill , Tyndall ; – ) was an English biblical poet and the first Christian author of the New Testament. He was born in Canterbury in 1779, and studied at Cambridge University with his father. He is regarded by historians as one of the most influential composers of Western classical antiquity. His works span the period from Homer to the Renaissance.Tyndale lived in Oxford until his death in 1828.He is considered to be one of the greatest lyricists of all time, with a canon spanning over 150 volumes of his work.

The National Guard is a state-based military force that becomes part of the reserve components of the United States Army in an emergency. The Military Police consists of five police divisions, and its main role is to protect public safety. National Guard is a unit of the federal government responsible for the protection of national security interests. Its primary purpose is to protect the people from terrorist threats and provide resources for law enforcement during peacetime emergencies such as war, occupation, and foreign wars. It was founded in 1947 by President Jimmy Carter to combat "subversive" elements of the civil rights movement, including Jim Crow laws.

Sir Philip Nicholas Outram Pullman ( born 19 October 1946 ) is an English writer . His books include the novels The Great Man and A Day with a God (2006) and Unfinished Tales (2003). He has been writing poetry since 1992 as a teacher at Reading Abbey in Norfolk, UK where he now lives.In 1995 he was awarded the Nobel Prize for Literature for his research into the relationship between music and mental health . He also won the European Research Chair in Music & Audiovisual Theatre at Lille University in 2002.

Paweł Jasienica was the pen name of Leon Lech Beynar ( 10 November 1909 – 19 August 1970 ) , the German composer who composed the first score for the operatic opera Jaws. In addition, there are numerous books and short stories based on Miele Wellett's novels. A collection of essays written during her lifetime by Wellett, published in 1854–1855, is known as the Wellett Library. It consists of fifty volumes of essays and other works which have been added to its collection over the course of several years. These essays can be found at www.WellettMuseum.org or at a number of web sites.

Oak Ridge National Laboratory (ORNL) is a U.S. multiprogram science and technology national laboratory sponsored by the U.S. Department of Energy (DOE) and administered, managed, and operated by UT–Battelle as a federally funded research and development center (FFRDC) under a contract with the DOE, located in Oak Ridge, Tennessee.Established in 1943, ORNL is the largest science and energy national laboratory in the Department of Energy system (by size) and third largest by annual budget. It is located in the Roane County section of Oak Ridge, Tennessee.

Enriched uranium is a type of uranium in which the percent composition of uranium-235 (written 235U) has been increased through the process of isotope separation. Naturally occurring uranium is composed of three major isotopes:  uranium-238 (238U with 99.2739–99.2752% natural abundance), uranium-235 (235U, 0.7198–0.7202%), and uranium-234 (234U, 0.0050–0.0059%). 235U is the only nuclide existing in nature (in any appreciable amount) that is fissile with thermal neutrons.Enriched uranium is a critical component for both civil nuclear power generation and military nuclear weapons.

Alfa Romeo Automobiles S.p.A. is an Italian luxury car manufacturer and a subsidiary of Stellantis . The company was founded on October 9, 1970, in Sardinia in the southern town of Liguria by the late Filippo Di Giabra. Citadel is a local city in the area of Granata province that is about 3 km to the north of Madrid. It consists of many cities and towns and is home to a large number of public transportation services. City government is relatively simple, but not as powerful as in other countries such as Italy.

The Reedy Creek Improvement District ( RCID ) is the immediate governing jurisdiction for the land of the Walt Disney World Resort, in the area bounded by the Atlantic Ocean and the western boundary of the Grand Canyon. The county includes the northernmost portions of Walt Disney World Resort, the westernmost portions within Walt Disney World Resort, the southernmost portions of Walt Disney World Resort, and the eastern portion of Walt Disney World Resort. Contents show]
Early development Edit
Walt Disney World , located north of New Jersey, was a multi-use amusement park built in 1937.

In the philosophy of mathematics, the abstraction of actual infinity involves the acceptance (if the axiom of infinity is included) of infinite entities as given, actual and completed objects. These might include the set of natural numbers, extended real numbers, transfinite numbers, or even an infinite sequence of rational numbers. Actual infinity is to be contrasted with potential infinity, in which a non-terminating process (such as "add 1 to the previous number") produces a sequence with no last element, and where each individual result is finite and is achieved in a finite number of steps.

Kingston is the capital and largest city of Jamaica , located on the southeastern coast of the island . It is the fourth largest city in Jamaica, after New York City and Los Angeles.Jamaica had a population of 1.9 million in 1980, which rose by almost 10% to 6.2 million in 1991, and has become a focal point for Jamaican politics and economic development.Jamaica also shares the Atlantic Ocean coastline with its neighboring British Empire and the Caribbean Sea.In Jamaica, Jamaica is considered a European nation that enjoys an independent status and independence from the US.

The World Federation of Trade Unions ( WFTU ) is an international federation of trade unions . WFTU was established in 1992 and is a multilingual, inter-governmental organization formed in 1994. It is composed of 19 member states that have ratified the European Union and 16 non-european membership countries. The United States ( US ) is a major trading country with an average daily market price of $2,500. This is significantly below the Federal Reserve Bank of New York's national average. The economy is largely based on foreign direct investment, mainly from the United States and Mexico, with no significant foreign exchange reserves.

The Illustrated Man is a 1951 collection of 18 science fiction short stories by American writer Ray Bradbury . A member of the United States Institute of Peace, he served under President Bush from 2006 to 2010 and was named one of the five Most Revolvable Presidents in U.S. History. He received the Medal of Freedom from President George H.W. Bush for outstanding service.Bradbury has published over 70 novels, short stories, biographies, and works of fiction and nonfiction, as well as poetry, prose, and essays. He lives in Los Angeles.

A pegmatite is an igneous rock showing a very coarse texture , with large interlocking crystals usually greater in size. Metamorphism  is an ancient and complex process that has led to the formation of a new type of life. The process of metamorphism begins when the Earth's mantle plumes, which were at least as old as the Earth itself, begin to move through the Earth's magnetic field; the magma that eventually solidifies within the mantle rapidly flows out into space. Meteorites become increasingly heavier and heavier as the surface of the Earth continues to increase in temperature, thus increasing the amount of fuel they can use to produce heat.

Blake Edwards (born William Blake Crump; July 26, 1922 – December 15, 2010) was an American actor, film director, producer and screenwriter.Edwards began his career in the 1940s as an actor, but he soon began writing screenplays and radio scripts before turning to producing and directing in television and films. His best-known films include Breakfast at Tiffany's, Days of Wine and Roses, 10, Victor/Victoria, and the hugely successful Pink Panther film series with British actor Peter Sellers. Often thought of as primarily a director of comedies, he also directed several drama, musical, and detective films.

Humour ( Commonwealth English ) or humor ( American English ) is the tendency of experiences to provoke laughter and other reactions. A range of social behaviours associated with humour, such as laughing and biting, can be distinguished from normal behavioural behaviour in most cases by the occurrence of a negative emotion. In addition to this characteristic, humans also develop a variety of behaviours that may elicit an unusual response in certain situations, notably fear, anxiety and depression, which are common in some cultures. Etymology From Proto-Germanic script meaning "thing", it originally came from Late Latin verb meaning "to go".

In mathematics , the Dirac delta distribution ( distribution ) , also known as the unit impulse symbol , is a mathematical equation that describes the vectorization function of a set . It describes the relative and absolute position of objects in such a coordinate system, which determines how much the direction of the object can be given or not by the inverse of the plane. In order to understand the Dirac delta-distribution , it is necessary to understand some fundamental principles of Euclidean geometry. The main characteristic of the Dirac delta distribution is that it is expressed in units of space, i.e., in radians.

Nuclear engineering is the branch of engineering concerned with the application of breaking down atomic nuclei ( fission ) or other natural nuclear elements to perform a number of useful purposes, including reactor construction, energy consumption, fuel extraction and safety. The Japanese government's National Security Agency ( nISA ) was established in Tokyo on December 8, 1952, to provide security assistance to the United States; however, some of its activities were carried out outside Japan as part of an international intelligence gathering program called "Project Blue Book", which has since been renamed the NISA International Intelligence Project ( nIAP ).

Lucia di Lammermoor is a dramma tragico ( tragic opera ) in three acts by Italian composer Gaetano Donizetti . In the first act she is an actress and later a playwright, most notable for her contributions to the theatre. Duke of Saxe-Gotha is a Medieval Roman castle situated at the heart of the Danube River. Its surroundings are as Gothic as the interior of the city itself; on its eastern side, it forms the northern border with the Rhine valley, and is named after King Ludwig II , who was governor of Saxony from 1162 to 1204.

In chemistry, an aldehyde  is an organic compound containing a functional group with the structure −C(H)=O. The functional group itself (i.e. without the "R" side chain) is known as an aldehyde or formyl group. Aldehydes are common and play important roles in the technology and biological spheres.Structure and bondingAldehydes feature a carbon center that is connected by a double bond to oxygen and a single bond to hydrogen and single bond to a third substituent, which is carbon or, in the case of formaldehyde, hydrogen. The central carbon is often described as being sp2-hybridized.

The Maunder Minimum , also known as the `` prolonged sunspot minimum '' , was a period around 1645 to 1715. During the height of the Middle Ages, the number of daylight hours between dawn and sunset were reduced dramatically due to an increase in solar activity caused by increasing light pollution from sources such as the sun. The maximum number of daylight hours on Earth at midnight was one hour; for the purposes of calculation, this equated to 1.2. Lithography In 1859, William H. Brown published "A Catalogue of American Biography ." The collection is notable for being the largest source of biographic information in North America .

Henry Dunant (born Jean-Henri Dunant; 8 May 182830 October 1910), also known as Henri Dunant, was a Swiss humanitarian, businessman and social activist. He was the visionary, promoter and co-founder of the Red Cross. In 1901, he received the first Nobel Peace Prize together with Frédéric Passy, making Dunant the first Swiss Nobel laureate.During a business trip in 1859, Dunant was witness to the aftermath of the Battle of Solferino in modern-day Italy. He recorded his memories and experiences in the book A Memory of Solferino which inspired the creation of the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC) in 1863.

In chemistry, a nucleophile is a chemical species that forms bonds with electrophiles by donating an electron pair. All molecules and ions with a free pair of electrons or at least one pi bond can act as nucleophiles. Because nucleophiles donate electrons, they are Lewis bases. Nucleophilic describes the affinity of a nucleophile to bond with positively charged atomic nuclei. Nucleophilicity, sometimes referred to as nucleophile strength, refers to a substance's nucleophilic character and is often used to compare the affinity of atoms. Neutral nucleophilic reactions with solvents such as alcohols and water are named solvolysis.

Theories of political behavior , as an aspect of political science , attempt to quantify and explain the influences that human behavior has on human behavior by asking questions about why human behavior evolved. Some theories are grounded in evolutionary principles, while others relate directly to economic and social interactions. Political psychology is a theoretical discipline which focuses on understanding the role human behavior plays in various domains including economics, politics, culture, history, public policy, media, entertainment, sports, sociology, ethics, and other fields. There are no general theories of moral behavior; they focus on the cognitive, social, and ethical issues involved.

A melody ( from Greek μελῳδία , melōidía , `` singing , chanting '' ) , also tune , voice, or rhythm is an essential element in classical music. Its importance has been discussed by several authors and a number of other scholars.In English the phrase is used as a generalised form of the verb "to perform", indicating that its meaning is not confined to the play but extends to the action. However, this is more often used in the United States than elsewhere. The word is often translated into English as "to dance".

The subset sum problem ( SSP ) is a decision problem in computer science . In its most general formulation, the subset sum problem involves determining how many different groups of discrete numbers can be expected to sum. The probability of convergence depends on the number of members of each group, and then on the degree of agreement among them. Computers typically use these rules to determine if two sets of digits are distinct or indistinguishable.In the domain of computer science, it is also used as an algorithm to predict which sets of characters in a sentence will be more familiar than others.

Clothing ( also known as clothes , apparel , and attire ) are items worn on the body . Typically they consist of a coat, jeans, a hat, shoes, trousers, shirts, dresses, stockings, and other accessories that provide protection against physical and chemical attacks.A clothing can be a jacket, scarf, or short sleeved sweatshirt with a belt tied around it. It is not usually made of silk or nylon. In some places, there are still many different types of food in which animals are found. Many species live in tropical jungles, rainforest patches, rivers, deserts, and grasslands.

Year 1036 (MXXXVI) was a leap year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place Europe Summer – In Naples, Duke Sergius IV abdicates and retires to a monastery; he is succeeded by his son John V. A Zirid expeditionary force invades Sicily and takes Palermo from the Normans, but fails to fully reconquer the island. England  February 5 – Edward the Confessor's younger brother Alfred Aetheling is blinded and murdered, in an apparent attempt to seize the throne of England from Harold I. Africa  June 13 – Caliph al-Zahir li-i'zaz Din Allah dies after a 16-year reign.

Tajiks ( , Tājīk , Tājek ; ) are a Persian-speaking Iranian ethnic group native to Central Asia , living mainly in southern Afghanistan and Iraq.The term is derived from the ṭadiya meaning of "to die". They are the descendants of the Assyrian Assyrians, who were the last remaining Greek-speaking people of Mesopotamia until about 5,000 years ago when they migrated to Canaan through the Aegean Sea via the Euphrates. In their languages, there is almost no trace of ṭadhi, but its pronunciation was changed in modern Iran due to an influx of pilgrims from other parts of the world.

A gas nuclear reactor (or gas fueled reactor or vapor core reactor) is a proposed kind of nuclear reactor in which the nuclear fuel would be in a gaseous state rather than liquid or solid. In this type of reactor, the only temperature-limiting materials would be the reactor walls. Conventional reactors have stricter limitations because the core would melt if the fuel temperature were to rise too high. It may also be possible to confine gaseous fission fuel magnetically, electrostatically or electrodynamically so that it would not touch (and melt) the reactor walls.

The Etruscan civilization of ancient Italy covered a territory , at its greatest extent , of roughly what is now Greece, with parts of Sicily and Rhodes under its direct control. The Etruscan people are considered highly intelligent and culturally complex, although they also play a more prominent role as members of both the Roman Church and the Orthodox church.In addition to the Greeks who inhabited their territories, many other ethnic groups within the area also came to assimilate into European culture.Etruscan peoples have included all but the most ethnically diverse tribes in Europe, mostly from Central Asia .

The Hippocratic Oath is an oath of ethics historically taken by physicians. It is one of the most widely known of Greek medical texts. In its original form, it requires a new physician to swear, by a number of healing gods, to uphold specific ethical standards. The oath is the earliest expression of medical ethics in the Western world, establishing several principles of medical ethics which remain of paramount significance today. These include the principles of medical confidentiality and non-maleficence. As the seminal articulation of certain principles that continue to guide and inform medical practice, the ancient text is of more than historic and symbolic value.

Don Carlos is a five-act grand opera composed by Giuseppe Verdi to a French-language libretto by Joseph Méry and Camille Bouchard; its score is available as a standard edition for all three albums; it contains only the original text of Verdi's piece, "Die Gebirten" ("Düsseldorf"). The production is directed by Sergio Leone, who first appeared on behalf of the Italian actor Alfonso Cuarón in La Motta in 1975, followed by Leone.Verdi was born in Budapest, Hungary, and moved to Italy when he was 10 years old.

New Sweden (; ; ) was a Swedish colony along the lower reaches of the Delaware River in America from 1638 to 1655, established during the Thirty Years' War when Sweden was a great military power. New Sweden formed part of the Swedish efforts to colonize the Americas. Settlements were established on both sides of the Delaware Valley in the region of Delaware, New Jersey, Maryland, and Pennsylvania, often in places where Swedish traders had been visiting since about 1610. Fort Christina in Wilmington, Delaware, was the first settlement, named after the reigning Swedish monarch.

Year 876 ( DCCCLXXVI ) was a leap year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Monday, June 14 ( DCCLXXVIII ). It took place on May 22nd, 1880, at about 1:30 pm ET; it is also one of the two fastest days to date in North America, having gained almost 5 seconds per minute. Discovery [ edit ]
In the late 1800s, astronomer John Herschel noticed that a group of black holes orbiting a dark region of the universe called the Higgs field were making gravitational waves.

The AGM-114 Hellfire ( AGM stands for air-to-ground missile ) is an air-to-surface missile ( ASM ) first developed for use as a cruise missile. It was modified to be able to reach targets up to 70 km from their target location in mid-air, and have a range of up to 400 km. The design also incorporates an anti-radiation countermeasures system along with high-altitude radar and advanced communications capabilities. Its accuracy was previously measured at 0.12 m/s, though it is estimated at 5 meters (11 feet) by 2 meters (11 feet).

Nitrous oxide , commonly known as laughing gas , nitrous , or nos , is a chemical compound , an ionic material that is readily converted into gas when exposed to oxygen. It has been used on many other forms of electricity generation, including the power plant, hydroelectric power transmission system, and nuclear power generation.The United Nations Environment Programme estimates that over 90% of global greenhouse gas emissions are caused by human activities. The United States produces over 1.4 billion tons of CO2 per annum and uses carbon dioxide to fuel its automobiles, power plants, electric vehicles, and agricultural production systems.

Brave New World is a dystopian social science fiction novel by English author Aldous Huxley, written in 1931 and published in 1932. Largely set in a futuristic World State, whose citizens are environmentally engineered into an intelligence-based social hierarchy, the novel anticipates huge scientific advancements in reproductive technology, sleep-learning, psychological manipulation and classical conditioning that are combined to make a dystopian society which is challenged by only a single individual: the story's protagonist. Huxley followed this book with a reassessment in essay form, Brave New World Revisited (1958), and with his final novel, Island (1962), the utopian counterpart.

Year 1155 (MCLV) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Siege of Tortona: German forces capture the citadel of Tortona (after a two-month siege). The city is razed to the ground, including the graves. June 18 – King Frederick I (Barbarossa) is crowned as Emperor of the Holy Roman Empire by Pope Adrian IV at St. Peter's Basilica in Rome. Arnold of Brescia is exiled by Adrian IV and forced to flee. He is arrested by imperial forces; hanged and his body burned at the stake in Rome.

A shaped charge is an explosive charge shaped to focus the effect of the explosive's energy. Different types of shaped charges are used for various purposes such as cutting and forming metal, initiating nuclear weapons, penetrating armor, or perforating wells in the oil and gas industry.A typical modern shaped charge, with a metal liner on the charge cavity, can penetrate armor steel to a depth of seven or more times the diameter of the charge (charge diameters, CD), though greater depths of 10 CD and above have been achieved.

Mystery religions, mystery cults, sacred mysteries or simply mysteries, were religious schools of the Greco-Roman world for which participation was reserved to initiates (mystai). The main characterization of this religion is the secrecy associated with the particulars of the initiation and the ritual practice, which may not be revealed to outsiders. The most famous mysteries of Greco-Roman antiquity were the Eleusinian Mysteries, which were of considerable antiquity and predated the Greek Dark Ages. The mystery schools flourished in Late Antiquity; Julian the Apostate in the mid 4th century is known to have been initiated into three distinct mystery schools—most notably the mithraists.

Year 1158 (MCLVIII) was a common year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Autumn – Emperor Manuel I (Komnenos) sets out from Constantinople at the head of a expeditionary army. He marches to Cillicia; and while the main army follows the coast road eastwards – Manuel hurries ahead with a force of only 500 cavalry. He manages to surprise King Thoros II (the Great), who has participated in the attack on Cyprus (see 1156). Thoros flees into the mountains and Cilicia is occupied by the Byzantines.

The chicken ( Gallus domesticus ) is a domesticated bird , with attributes of wild species such as the red-tailed deer, which has an elongated head and tail. It is known to eat large numbers of birds in captivity, though there is evidence to suggest that it can also be domesticated into other crops, including fruits, vegetables, fish, insects, and eggs. There is considerable disagreement about whether the chickens are domesticated into more important food animals, such as cattle, horses, cows, sheep, swine, or even pigs.

Alkanna tinctoria , the dyer 's alkanet or simply alkanet , is a herb in the borage family . Its origin is traced back to Europe, where it was first planted.The plant is used as an ornamental food for many birds and marine plants.Dictionary.com Unabridged Based on the official Oxford English Dictionary, the dictionary is an online index that includes more than 1000 words and phrases. The dictionary was compiled by the American Society for the Blind, the American Society for Gerontology & Genetics (ASG), and other national groups. Etymology: It dates from the Old Norse Þinn-, meaning "to hold fast".

Josiah Willard Gibbs ( ; February 11 , 1839 – April 28 , 1903 ) was an American scientist who became the first openly Jewish student to publish a scientific paper, published in 1835, entitled "History of Human Genetics," which was widely read as a political statement about the origins of human evolution. Although Gibbs's book has been widely cited on the internet, it did not become widely available until his death in 1931, and is now considered the earliest attempt at a genetic test for human evolution. John von Neumann (1931–1998) was a Dutch mathematician and physicist.

Brave New World is a dystopian social science fiction novel by English author Aldous Huxley , written in 1931 and published by Simon & Schuster in the United States, Europe and Japan . The novel came out in 1945, when it appeared as part of a series on American television. It was one of the most-watched books in the world, averaging 1.5 million copies at the time of publication. Huxley won the Hugo Award for Best Novel in 1984.Huxley began his writing career in 1955 with the introduction of "The Book of Common Sense."

Eagle is the common name for many large birds of prey of the family Accipitridae . Eagles belong to several genera and are most closely related to Acanthaceae ( ). Horses, horses, camels, and other animals that inhabit the Earth's interior can be described by various terms, but all of them have been historically used as metaphor for living organisms. These include "living animals", aquatic animals, reptiles, amphibians, reptiles, mammals, bacteria, plants, fungi, and algae. Some animals are referred to as species because their primary source of energy consists primarily of carbon dioxide or hydrogen sulfide.

Twenty Thousand Leagues Under the Seas is a classic science fiction adventure novel by French writer Jules Verne.The novel was written by David S. Goyer (and directed by William Hurt, Jr.), and is being published by Viacom. It is divided into four parts; one story follows the life of a young girl who finds herself in the midst of an underwater search for the lost sea creature, and another tale takes place in a dystopian future where technological advancement is making technology obsolete to meet the demands of modern life.Jules Verne's greatest contribution as a writer is to tell stories that connect us to our human past.

Pali  is a Middle Indo-Aryan liturgical language native to the Indian subcontinent. It is widely studied because it is the language of the Pāli Canon or Tipiṭaka as well as the sacred language of Theravāda Buddhism. In early time, it was written in Brahmi script.Origin and developmentEtymologyThe word 'Pali' is used as a name for the language of the Theravada canon. The word seems to have its origins in commentarial traditions, wherein the Pāli (in the sense of the line of original text quoted) was distinguished from the commentary or vernacular translation that followed it in the manuscript.

The Alcubierre drive , Alcubierre warp drive , or Alcubierre metric ( referring to metric tensor ) , is a method of measurement. The idea is to be able to easily determine the distances between two objects using an extremely high-precise system of coordinates such as those used by Newton's first calculus. Aerodynamics, also called thermodynamics, is a widely used concept in economics, physics and chemistry. Its primary focus has been on convective heat transfer (CCFT) and its related processes. Aerodynamics is a theory about how matter flows through various physical systems, with important contributions from other fields, including thermodynamics, aerodynamics, gravity and gravitation.

A bong ( also known as a water pipe ) is a filtration device generally used for smoking cannabis , but also contains an enzyme that removes any organic compounds that cause it to become bitter or toxic. It can be used by tobacco smokers to reduce the nicotine content of cigarettes, in conjunction with some other health benefits, including reduced heart rate, blood pressure, and liver function. Alcohol is the major constituent of many alcoholic beverages worldwide. Alcohol is consumed in more than half of the world's countries. Most alcoholics do not consider it their main source of drinking water.

Mobile Bay is a shallow inlet of the Gulf of Mexico , lying within the state of Alabama in the middle of an aquifer. The bay is known for its tropical and subtropical rivers and lakes, many of them covered in vegetation. It is also home to more than half of the United States' annual rainfall. English is one of the most common languages spoken on earth. As a child, English could be understood as a dialect of Latin or French, although it was also known as English-French, English-Français, or Esperanto.

Year 950 ( CML ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on January 1, 992. The name is derived from the Greek word μυρομενιης ('month', or month), which translated into Greek means 'greatest'. The Great Depression of the 1930s came as the third major economic crisis to hit European countries since World War II. In 1933 Germany's economy had suffered a total loss of 5.9 billion dollars in real terms. It was the sixth largest economy in the eurozone and the fifth worst in Europe.

Psilocybin is a naturally occurring psychedelic prodrug compound produced by more than 200 species of fungi . The most potent hallucinogenic compound in human history and one of the most highly abused, it is still used extensively as a recreational drug. Its abuse has increased significantly since the late 1800s with numerous studies showing that psychedelics are able to reduce anxiety and depressive symptoms , reducing the risk of psychotic illness. This article was adapted from the excellent book The Mind (2007), which describes a series of experiments using LSD and other psychedelics to change behavior and consciousness in laboratory animals.

Year 1025 ( MXXV ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on March 29, 1837, and ending on April 8, 1847. The date coincides with the beginning of the Thirty Years' War, which lasted from December 9 to November 4, 1867. On June 11, 1839, Pope Gregory XII issued an encyclical in his dioceses which laid out a new era of liberal secularism. He called for "an ecumenical government that takes into account both the needs of citizens and the religious interest" of Christians.

Yorkshire pudding is a baked pudding made from a batter of eggs, flour, and milk or water. A common English side dish, it is a versatile food that can be served in numerous ways depending on its ingredients, size, and the accompanying components of the meal. As a first course, it can be served with onion gravy. For a main course, it may be served with meat and gravy, and is part of the traditional Sunday roast, but can also be filled with foods such as bangers and mash to make a meal.

See also History of UnitarianismA number of notable people have considered themselves Unitarians, Universalists, and following the merger of these denominations in the United States and Canada in 1961, Unitarian Universalists. Additionally, there are persons who, because of their writings or reputation, are considered to have held Unitarian or Universalist beliefs. Individuals who held unitarian (nontrinitarian) beliefs but were not affiliated with Unitarian organizations are often referred to as "small 'u unitarians. The same principle can be applied to those who believed in universal salvation but were not members of Universalist organizations.

The United Nations Foundation is a charitable organization headquartered in Washington , DC , that supports the United Nations and has been funded by UNDP since 1998. It is a non-governmental organization, not an institution of government; it does not work for nor for money from any third party.org (the "Open Web") makes no representations concerning its content or fitness for any particular purpose. Fluoride occurs naturally in water and air at various points in the ocean floor. Some forms of fluoroalkaloid hydrocarbons (HHA), such as chloroform, chlorophyll, and methanol, are highly volatile.

Stevana "Stevie" Case (born 1976–1977) is an American businesswoman. She is known for competing in the first-person shooter game Quake in the late 1990s, as well as contributing professionally to the video game industry.Competing under the alias KillCreek, she was one of the first notable female esports players, gaining recognition for beating Quake designer John Romero in a Quake deathmatch in 1997. She was the first professional gamer signed to the Cyberathlete Professional League (CPL).Case worked for Ion Storm between 1997 and 2001, conducting quality assurance and level design.

Budapest ( , ; ) is the capital and most populous city of Hungary . It is the ninth-largest city, and the sixth-largest in the Czech Republic. Budapest has an estimated population of about 615,000 inhabitants, which is a total of more than 10 million people living in the metropolitan areas. The city is located at the intersection of the Hennemann–Hagázásátė, near the border with Serbia, and Ljubljana. There are approximately 8,000 Hungarian Orthodox Christians in Hungary, 3,942 Orthodox Jews in Slovakia, and 2,827 Hungarians who belong to the Reform and Antislavery Associations (IRA).

Carnival is a Western Christian festive season that occurs before the liturgical season of Lent . The main events typically begin on Christmas Eve and run through April 2nd. In some European countries (excluding Poland and Lithuania) it is customary to prepare food in advance for weddings, funerals, and general celebrations of the year. A number of countries have an obligation to prepare food for people living in areas with low levels of natural gas consumption. This includes Germany, Belgium, Spain, Portugal, France, Italy, Switzerland, Norway, Austria, Japan, and Ireland.

Mosquitoes are members of a group of almost 3,600 species of small flies within the family Culicidae ( from the Greek νήστος ("wingless") and απολιγήστος ("flyy" in French)). Each genus contains about 20–30 individuals. Culicidae are classified as either solitary or subspecies by nature, depending on its geographic location.The term is most commonly used for cichlid fly larvae (Cichlidae). Rhodochromia  is a broad-leafed disease that can occur anywhere in the body including skin, mouth, nose, and lower back. It is endemic to southern Africa, eastern Europe, Central America, Asia, and the Mediterranean Sea.

Cannabis  is a genus of flowering plants in the family Cannabaceae. The number of species within the genus is disputed. Three species may be recognized: Cannabis sativa, Cannabis indica, and Cannabis ruderalis; C. ruderalis may be included within C. sativa; all three may be treated as subspecies of a single species, C. sativa; or C. sativa may be accepted as a single undivided species. The genus is widely accepted as being indigenous to and originating from Asia.The plant is also known as hemp, although this term is often used to refer only to varieties of Cannabis cultivated for non-drug use.

The Buran program ( , , `` Snowstorm '' , `` Blizzard '' ) , also known as the ``Ice Age'' in China. It is considered to be one of the most peaceful and democratic societies in the world and is considered by Chinese authorities to have been governed for over 400 million years by the Yangtze dynasty. According to historical records, an estimated 1.25 million people lived on Earth between 1812 and 1864. Although it was a highly developed society during its early stages, it was not until after the arrival of Homo sapiens in the mid-cafal period of the 16th century that mankind began living at sea.

Kristiansund ( , ; historically spelled Christianssund and earlier named Fosna ) is a municipality on the western coast of Norway, in northern Norway, and an important part of Kristjørjansand.It has one of the lowest proportions of population in Europe, with less than 2% of the population.The city is located just outside Oslo, about 45 mins south of Oslo-Tøgården. It is situated about 30km northeast of the city centre which is separated by a small peninsula that runs parallel to the road from the central business district. "Görtel" is a short play written by Heinrich Löhrer in 1875 and adapted by Hermann Dörner.

Mystery religions , mystery cults , sacred mysteries or simply mysteries , were religious schools of the Greco-Roman world for hundreds of years, originating in Greece between the 3rd and 4th centuries BC. They formed their influence on Christianity as well as Buddhism and Hinduism. The earliest known mystery religion (the Greek word ρέμανος is derived from γφελιανία, meaning 'sacred mystery'), dating to a period from the 7th–12th centuries BC, was the Mystery School of Athens, founded by Archimedes, one of the most influential philosophers of ancient Greece at that time.

The red slender loris ( Loris tardigradus ) is a small , nocturnal strepsirrhine primate native to the rainforests of North Africa and Eurasia that was originally discovered in southern Africa. Introduced into North Africa in the nineteenth century, it soon spread westward along the rivers of the Arabian peninsula and southward along the Atlantic Ocean. In Europe, it flourished from the mid-sixteenth century until the early twentieth century. It is the largest extant primate group in the United States, accounting for 50% of all domestic primates studied. Its lineage is also the longest in North America, with the last common ancestor standing at 65 million years ago.

Radiohead are an English rock band formed in Abingdon , Oxfordshire , in 1985 . The band consists of Thom Yorke, Steve McQueen, Paul Begg and John Mellencamp. Their debut album was released in 1986 and quickly spread around the globe with its release, becoming a staple on Radiohead 's discography for almost twenty years. After two decades together they split up in 2009 after being forced to move to their new home in New York. In April 2012, they released their seventh studio album (2006).In November 2010, members of the band recorded their fourth studio album, "I Am No Longer Dead".

The History of East Asia generally encompasses the histories of China, Japan, Korea, and Mongolia from prehistoric times to the present. East Asia is not a uniform term and each of its countries has a different national history, but scholars maintain that the region is also characterized by a distinct pattern of historical development. This is evident in the interrelationship among East Asian countries, which not only involve the sum total of historical patterns but also a specific set of patterns that has affected all or most of East Asia in successive layers.

In economics , inflation refers to a general progressive increase in prices of goods and services in an economy . This article is about a person, class, occupation, gender, race, ethnicity, religion, culture, nationality, sexual orientation, national origin, disability, or both. It also includes information related to any other part of the term that might be confused with it.See also:Definition of "woman" (feminism ). In most countries women are not allowed to serve as a woman's representative but are subject to some form of social exclusion if they become pregnant or have children.

Seville ( ; , ) is the capital and largest city of the Spanish autonomous community of Andalusia and the fourth largest in the Americas. It is situated in the western corner of Spain, about 100 miles south of Lisbon.The town's population was estimated to be 10,000, with an annual household income of $9,300. In contrast to its Latin American neighbors, Andalusia has been plagued by violence for many years, particularly between 2003 and 2015.In 2011, nearly 6,400 people were killed at a rally against the rule of dictator Benigno Diaz-Virán.

A seed is an embryonic plant enclosed in a protective outer covering. The formation of the seed is part of the process of reproduction in seed plants, the spermatophytes, including the gymnosperm and angiosperm plants.Seeds are the product of the ripened ovule, after fertilization by pollen and some growth within the mother plant. The embryo develops from the zygote, and the seed coat from the integuments of the ovule. Seeds have been an important development in the reproduction and success of gymnosperm and angiosperm plants, relative to more primitive plants such as ferns, mosses and liverworts, which do not have seeds and use water-dependent means to propagate themselves.

In philosophy , systems theory , science , and art , emergence occurs when an entity is observed to have characteristics that can be explained by processes other than a natural phenomena; these characteristics include, for example, how things behave in relation to bodies and environments. The concepts are often applied to objects from different perspectives, each with its own special rules of operation (as opposed to some others), and they vary depending on the context in which they were observed. There are three categories of systems theories developed over the centuries, namely, axiomatic systems theory, empirical systems theory, and structural systems theory .

A tremor is an involuntary , somewhat rhythmic , muscle contraction and relaxation involving oscillations or twitching movements of one's lower arms or legs.Tremor is characterized by a rapid increase in the rate at which the individual's heart beats, a change in the volume of the blood vessels, and a reduction in the pressure on the muscles when they are tense. The onset of tremor may also be delayed or even reversed by the use of a nervous system that responds to changing temperature. Symptoms include fatigue, dizziness, weakness, and pain in the feet and ankles.

Lanford Wilson ( April 13 , 1937March 24 , 2011 ) was an American playwright . His work , as well as many others, have appeared in the American literary canon, most notably John Steinbeck's Faust , a novel of surrealist and surrealist imagery.In 1931, Wilson began his musical career with his son, Frank Wilson, composer and songwriter; it eventually went on to be played by members of the British band The Strokes. He died in May 2009 at the age of 87.Wilson was born in Greenville, South Carolina, to English-Irish immigrants.

Sparta (Doric Greek: Σπάρτα, Spártā; Attic Greek: Σπάρτη, Spártē) was a prominent city-state in Laconia, in ancient Greece. In antiquity, the city-state was known as Lacedaemon , while the name Sparta referred to its main settlement on the banks of the Eurotas River in Laconia, in south-eastern Peloponnese. Around 650 BC, it rose to become the dominant military land-power in ancient Greece.Given its military pre-eminence, Sparta was recognized as the leading force of the unified Greek military during the Greco-Persian Wars, in rivalry with the rising naval power of Athens.

Paul Lansky (born June 18, 1944, in New York) is an American composer.BiographyPaul Lansky (born 1944) is an American composer. He was educated at Manhattan's High School of Music and Art, Queens College and Princeton University, studying with George Perle and Milton Babbitt, among others. He received his Ph.D. in music from Princeton in 1973. His doctoral dissertation consisted of an essay titled "Affine music" and a composition of string quartet. Originally intending to pursue a career in performance, during 1965–66 he played the French horn with the Dorian Wind Quintet.

Harlequin ( ; ; ) is the best-known of the zanni or comic servant characters from the Italian commedia dell'arte and one of the longest-running series of animated shorts. The film was released in 1996 and then re-released briefly in 1998 for an English DVD release, where it was remastered into a commercial release on November 15, 2002.Anime adaptations are usually considered to be as long as their original TV series, often lasting between three and six seasons. In Japan, kōgaku (literally, "chink") is a Chinese term meaning "darkness", and 向標爱頭 is commonly used to indicate darkness.

William Harrison Riker ( September 22 , 1920 – June 26 , 1993 ) was an American political scientist who published two influential works on the Cold War between the United States and the Soviet Union. In one essay, he describes the nature of Western society in the early 21st century, concluding that the most important change occurring in US politics over the past few decades has been the arrival of nuclear weapons.Riker proposed that the rise of nuclear weaponry would make it impossible for the United States to achieve peace and stability without developing its own nuclear weapons.

Year 1170 (MCLXX) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place   Levant  Winter – Egyptian forces led by Saladin invade Palestine and besiege Darum on the Mediterranean coast. Its defenses are weak and though Saladin has no siege-engines with him, its fall seems imminent. King Amalric I withdraws his Templar garrison from Gaza, to assist him in defending Darum. Saladin raises the siege and marches on Gaza, where he captures the lower town (despite the stiff resistance ordered by Lord Miles of Plancy), and massacres the inhabitants.

An ion thruster, ion drive, or ion engine is a form of electric propulsion used for spacecraft propulsion. It creates thrust by accelerating ions using electricity.An ion thruster ionizes a neutral gas by extracting some electrons out of atoms, creating a cloud of positive ions. These ion thrusters rely mainly on electrostatics as ions are accelerated by the Coulomb force along an electric field. Temporarily stored electrons are finally reinjected by a neutralizer in the cloud of ions after it has passed through the electrostatic grid, so the gas becomes neutral again and can freely disperse in space without any further electrical interaction with the thruster.

An infection is the invasion of an organism 's body tissues by disease-causing agents , their multiplication , and the spread of diseases to the organism itself. Infections are typically fatal and can be life-threatening, although the consequences of such infections often involve death.1–8 Infection may occur during pregnancy, at the time of childbirth, or during sexual intercourse. The earliest stage of early embryonic development was embryotepia, or embryonic division (henceforth embryobiosis ). It was the beginning of many stages of development when the embryo has reached maturity; then it undergoes a number of distinct morphological changes before it reaches the age of viability.

Gender is the range of characteristics pertaining to femininity and masculinity and differentiating between them . Depending on the context, such attributes are perceived and defined differently by women who identify as female and other gender identity individuals. For example, "male" is generally considered masculine; "female" is viewed as feminine; and "other" as masculine or feminine.In a study conducted for the National Academy of Sciences (NAS), it was found that differences in the sexual characteristics of both genders were explained by cultural differences in the language used in research.

Harlequin (;  ;  ) is the best-known of the zanni or comic servant characters from the Italian commedia dell'arte. The role is traditionally believed to have been introduced by Zan Ganassa in the late 16th century, was definitively popularized by the Italian actor Tristano Martinelli in Paris in 1584–1585, and became a stock character after Martinelli's death in 1630.The Harlequin is characterized by his chequered costume. His role is that of a light-hearted, nimble, and astute servant, often acting to thwart the plans of his master, and pursuing his own love interest, Columbina, with wit and resourcefulness, often competing with the sterner and melancholic Pierrot.

( All Women Do It , or The School for Lovers ) , K. 588 , is an opera buffa that was popularized by Julius Caesar during his Roman reign, and the first opera to be released as part of the Classical Republic in the Western Hemisphere.In the 1960's, K.588 became a hit with audiences from Latin America, Australia, Canada, Great Britain, India, South Africa, Central America, and many Caribbean countries. Danish (Celtus) is a Danish language family founded in 1489. They were called "danish speakers" due to their close association with Gaelic.

A beta particle , also called beta ray or beta radiation ( symbol β ) , is a high-energy , energetic particle with low energy at wavelengths of approximately 50 to 500 nm. It is most frequently emitted by the sun during summer and late spring, but is also active in the troposphere as early as January through October.Beta rays have an estimated mass of 4.07 million times more powerful than ordinary particles. Beta rays (or "gamma rays" if you're used to talking about them) are cosmic rays produced by a nuclear fusion reaction between two neutrons (or neutrons).

Year 897 ( DCCCXCVII ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) and concluding on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) but was abandoned in 1997. It may have been abandoned because of political instability or as a result of mass protests that had not yet reached the capital city. The date for the final day of celebrations is March 15, 1987, after which its fate was sealed. The French language is France's second official language; French is the official language in the Federal Republic of France.

The Barber of Seville , or The Useless Precaution is an opera buffa in two acts by Gioachino Rossini with Italian classical composer Giovanni Battaglia (1799-1964). It features a great number of scenes, including the first performance of Castiglione's operas, while it is played in a stage set at the Casa del Valli dell'Academy, which is located in Venice, Italy, about 100 miles northeast of Florence. An ancient Roman city was built on the banks of the Sarmatia River during the reigns of Augustus Caesar, who ruled from 642 to 638 BC.

In the English language, the word nigger is an ethnic slur typically used against black people, especially African Americans. Because it is considered extremely offensive, even if only mentioned and not used as a slur, it is often referred to by the euphemism . It is also in use with a more neutral meaning among African Americans, primarily as nigga. The word originated in the 18th century as an adaptation of the Spanish word negro, a descendant of the Latin adjective niger, which means "black". Over time it took on a derogatory connotation and became a racist insult by the 20th century.

A sports governing body is a sports organization that has a regulatory or sanctioning function.Sports governing bodies come in various forms and have a variety of regulatory functions. Examples of this can include disciplinary action for rule infractions and deciding on rulechanges in the sport that they govern. Governing bodies have different scopes. They may cover a range of sport at an international level, such as the International Olympic Committee and the International Paralympic Committee, or only a single sport at a national level, such as the Rugby Football League. National bodies will largely have to be affiliated with international bodies for the same sport.

Garnets are a group of silicate minerals that have been used since the Bronze Age as gemstones and abrasives.All species of Garnets belong to the order Gaudium, Gaudinus, Gaudiodorus, Gaudium-Pallas, Gaudium-Dulcis, Gaudioides, or Gaudii, which contain various other garnet types. The common name for these different varieties of Garnets is Dutum, meaning "diamond", but they also have an intermediate form in the genus Gaudi. Garnets consist primarily of mineral compounds with complex crystalline compositions. Their crystalline forms are well described by geochemicalists who study the composition of sandstone deposits through their interactions with hydrocarbon chemistry, including hydroxylation and fluoridation.

The PalmPilot Personal and PalmPilot Professional are the second generation of Palm PDA devices produced by Palm Inc (then a subsidiary of U.S. Robotics, later 3Com). These devices were launched on March 10, 1997.Accessories and pricingPalm also sold the 10201U modem at 14.4 kbit/s, introduced at a price of $129 (this modem is also compatible with the Palm III and Palm IIIx devices). An upgrade kit was also available, which allowed users of the earlier Pilot 1000/5000 devices to upgrade the OS, ROM, and RAM to match the PalmPilot Professional.

An airport is an aerodrome with extended facilities , mostly for commercial air transport . Airports often have facilities to carry goods and services to or from foreign countries, particularly during the peak summer months. They are most frequently built at airports such as Duesseldorf or Lufthansa in central Germany , where they can accommodate passengers traveling from Berlin, Frankfurt and München.Many terminals are located in major cities (Rothburg, Stuttgart, etc.) and within relatively short distances of one another. The International Airport System is a network of intercity international airport systems operated by various airlines and railroads around the world.

A software bug is an error, flaw or fault in computer software that causes it to produce an incorrect or unexpected result, or to behave in unintended ways. The process of finding and correcting bugs is termed "debugging" and often uses formal techniques or tools to pinpoint bugs. Since the 1950s some computer systems have been designed to deter, detect or auto-correct various computer bugs during operations.Most bugs arise from mistakes and errors made in either a program's design or its source code, or in components and operating systems used by such programs.

Civil liberties are guarantees and freedoms that governments commit not to abridge, either by constitution, legislation, or judicial interpretation, without due process. Though the scope of the term differs between countries, civil liberties may include the freedom of conscience, freedom of press, freedom of religion, freedom of expression, freedom of assembly, the right to security and liberty, freedom of speech, the right to privacy, the right to equal treatment under the law and due process, the right to a fair trial, and the right to life.

The National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA  ) is an American scientific and regulatory agency within the United States Department of Commerce that forecasts weather, monitors oceanic and atmospheric conditions, charts the seas, conducts deep sea exploration, and manages fishing and protection of marine mammals and endangered species in the U.S. exclusive economic zone.Purpose and functionNOAA's specific roles include: Supplying Environmental Information Products. NOAA supplies to its customers and partners information pertaining to the state of the oceans and the atmosphere, such as weather warnings and forecasts via the National Weather Service. NOAA's information services extend as well to climate, ecosystems, and commerce.

Heliox is a breathing gas mixture of helium ( He ) and oxygen ( O2 ) .Heliox is a medical chemical in use to treat respiratory problems. Helium is one of the basic gases in the body, and is produced primarily in the lungs and brain. It is used as a nasal spray for pain management and analgesia.The name of Heliox was coined in 1897, but its original name was modified to "Hazardous Lead," later renamed H.I.R.A.E.L.C. "In the 1940s, an association with the Society for Experimental Toxicology (SEER) was established to research the health effects of exposure to highly toxic chemicals in the human body.

A hot air balloon is a lighter-than-air aircraft consisting of a bag, called an envelope, which contains heated air. Suspended beneath is a gondola or wicker basket (in some long-distance or high-altitude balloons, a capsule), which carries passengers and a source of heat, in most cases an open flame caused by burning liquid propane. The heated air inside the envelope makes it buoyant, since it has a lower density than the colder air outside the envelope. As with all aircraft, hot air balloons cannot fly beyond the atmosphere.

The Bell OH-58 Kiowa is a family of single-engine , single-rotor , military helicopters used for observation , utility , training , and other missions. They were originally designed to operate under the command of Lieutenant General Togami Iwatomo (1676–1729) in Japan, but later moved into service as aircraft carriers and airfields on Japanese islands from 1740 until 1943. It is the third most common type of carrier in the Japanese fleet, after the Mitsubishi III, and second most common in world air defence. Ojigaya  ( 六 斜 , ōjigaya ? , pronounced ɨn  or ?) is a mountain in central Ojigaya.

Auger electron spectroscopy ( AES ; pronounced in French ) is a common analytical technique used specifically in the study of isotope and hydrogen atom structure. It is performed by using X-ray crystallography, or X-ray absorption spectroscopy (SIR ), to identify individual electrons from a mixture of molecules and ions. One of the advantages of using X-ray absorptiometry is that it reduces the energy required to do an atomic phase-detection job. In contrast, chemical detection of hydrogen atoms results in the use of fluoromethane–hydroxycarbon dioxide (H2O) as a standard for detecting H2O. There have been several distinct theories about the existence of extraterrestrial civilizations in the past.

Year 980 ( CMLXXX ) was a leap year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Saturday, 31 August 2017.In its first three years, Cypriot Christianity did not follow the Christian religion in many respects. It has been the focus of international media attention since the early 1600s, with many publications focusing on the period between 600 to 1550.Cypriot Christianity became known as "the Christendom" after it emerged during the Second Punic War. The word itself comes from the Latin divinorum, which is also pronounced like the Greek πΡρευστια, πΡαρευσβος, or πρὸν αλέγων.

Year 959 (CMLIX) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  April - May – The Byzantines refuse to pay the yearly tribute. A Hungarian army, led by Apor, invades Macedonia and Thrace. He plunders its territories until reaching Constantinople. On his way back, Apor is defeated during a night attack by Byzantine forces. November 9 – Emperor Constantine VII Porphyrogennetos ("born in the purple") dies at Constantinople after a 46-year reign. He is succeeded by his 21-year-old son Romanos II as ruler of the Byzantine Empire.

The Campeonato Nacional de Liga de Primera División , commonly known simply as Primera División in Spain , and as the "Nacional Conformalismo for the Social Justice Movement (PCMS) in Catalonia ", was established in 1981 by the former president of the Popular Front for the right to self-determination (PFE). As such, the association is a successor to the PCMS after that of the Spanish PDEF, which formed the regional government in 1989. The organization began as a group led by members from different groups, but later expanded to encompass all sectors of the society including the private sector.

Harriet Tubman ( born Araminta Ross , March 10 , 1913 ) was an American abolitionist and political activist . Her first public appearance as a Democrat in the US Senate was at the start of the Civil War. She won the right to vote for two terms on the November 25th election of 1860. Tubman became a vocal critic of slavery, though she did support it under President Lincoln. Despite her opposition, she led the Southern Democrats during the Reconstruction era. She is credited with advocating the expansion of women's suffrage and abolishing the Jim Crow system.

Pope Gregory I (;  – 12 March 604), commonly known as Saint Gregory the Great, was the bishop of Rome from 3 September 590 to his death. He is known for instigating the first recorded large-scale mission from Rome, the Gregorian Mission, to convert the then-pagan Anglo-Saxons in England to Christianity. Gregory is also well known for his writings, which were more prolific than those of any of his predecessors as pope. The epithet Saint Gregory the Dialogist has been attached to him in Eastern Christianity because of his Dialogues.

Pope Leo II ( – 28 June 683) was the bishop of Rome from 17 August 682 to his death. He is one of the popes of the Byzantine Papacy. Described by a contemporary biographer as both just and learned, he is commemorated as a saint in the Roman Martyrology on 28 June (3 July, pre-1970 calendar).Early careerLeo was a Sicilian by birth, the son of a man named Paul. He may have ended up being among the many Sicilian clergymen in Rome due to the attacks of the Caliphate on Sicily in the mid-7th century.

In music performance and notation, legato (; Italian for "tied together"; French lié; German gebunden) indicates that musical notes are played or sung smoothly and connected. That is, the player makes a transition from note to note with no intervening silence. Legato technique is required for slurred performance, but unlike slurring (as that term is interpreted for some instruments), legato does not forbid re-articulation.Standard notation indicates legato either with the word legato, or by a slur (a curved line) under notes that form one legato group.

An airport is an aerodrome with extended facilities, mostly for commercial air transport. Airports often have facilities to park and maintain aircraft, and a control tower. An airport consists of a landing area, which comprises an aerially accessible open space including at least one operationally active surface such as a runway for a plane to take off and to land or a helipad, and often includes adjacent utility buildings such as control towers, hangars and terminals. Larger airports may have airport aprons, taxiway bridges, air traffic control centres, passenger facilities such as restaurants and lounges, and emergency services.

The Campeonato Nacional de Liga de Primera División, commonly known simply as Primera División in Spain, and as La Liga in English-speaking countries and officially as LaLiga Santander for sponsorship reasons, stylized as LaLiga, is the men's top professional football division of the Spanish football league system. Administered by the Liga Nacional de Fútbol Profesional, it is contested by 20 teams, with the three lowest-placed teams at the end of each season being relegated to the Segunda División and replaced by the top two teams and a play-off winner in that division.Since its inception, a total of 62 teams have competed in La Liga.

Year 1045 (MXLV) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January 20 – Pope Sylvester III becomes the 146th pope, succeeding Benedict IX, who abdicated during the previous year. January 23 – Edward the Confessor, King of England, marries Edith of Wessex, and begins construction of Westminster Abbey in England. February – Pope Sylvester III is deposed (election deemed invalid); Pope Benedict IX is elected once more, becoming the 147th pope. February 5 – Emperor Go-Reizei ascends the throne of Japan.

Year 986 (CMLXXXVI) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  August 17 – Battle of the Gates of Trajan: Emperor Basil II leads a Byzantine expeditionary force (30,000 men) against the Bulgarians to capture the fortress city of Sredets. After a siege of 20 days, Basil is forced to retreat from the Sofia Valley towards the town of Ihtiman (through a passage known as the Gate of Trajan). The Bulgarians under Tsar Samuel ambush and defeat the Byzantine forces.

Edward Higgins White II (November 14, 1930 – January 27, 1967) was an American aeronautical engineer, United States Air Force officer, test pilot, and NASA astronaut. He was a member of the crews of Gemini 4 and Apollo 1.After graduating from West Point in 1952 with a Bachelor of Science degree, White was sent to flight training, and assigned to the 22nd Fighter Day Squadron at Bitburg Air Base, West Germany, where he flew the F-86 Sabre and F-100 Super Sabre fighters. In 1958, he enrolled in the University of Michigan to study aeronautical engineering.

Catalase is a common enzyme found in nearly all living organisms exposed to oxygen ( such as bacteria , plants , and mammals ). It is the most frequently used DNA polymerase in the environment. It converts DNA from RNA into an oligonucleotide and then back into DNA by nucleotides or other adenosine monophosphate (AMP) chains. The DNA-binding site is at the junction of three amino acid chains—2′ and 6′—and consists of a series of polyunsaturated residues that bind to each other so that the two ends of the sequence are attached to each other.

Pizza Hut is an American multinational restaurant chain and international franchise founded in 1958 in Wichita , Kansas by Dan Zahn. The restaurant's menu boasts a combination of Italian, Italian-style breads, salads, and appetizers, as well as sandwiches, salads, and cheeses. Over the years, the restaurant has expanded into restaurants around the world, with offices in Europe, South America, Japan, China, and India.Zahn now resides in Vienna, where he serves food for sale on the West Side Market and has been serving it to thousands of customers in his home country of Belgium for nearly 30 years.

Nansen passports , originally and officially stateless persons passports , were internationally recognized refugee travel documents from 1922 to 1938. They were initially accepted as non-refugee refugees in Germany, and subsequently issued by the Foreign Ministry in 1946. There are no current official definitions of who was born in the country or whether an individual may have had German citizenship, although most countries recognize that some citizens may have been foreign citizens.The majority of European Union (EU) member states have similar laws, regulations, and processes to the standards adopted by the European Convention on Migration and Refugees.

Cotton is a soft , fluffy staple fiber that grows in a boll , or protective case , around the eyes, neck, cheeks, and nose. Cotton fibers have many different characteristics from cotton to hemp, such as low absorbency, smooth texture, and dense elasticity. Cotton fibers are most easily washed down with soap and water. Bamboo plants are known for their beautiful leaves and flowers. Bamboo shrubs consist of 4 to 6 plant species. Bamboo trees are native to India, but are still found in other parts of Asia and Europe.

Don Carlos is a five-act grand opera composed by Giuseppe Verdi to a French-language libretto by Joseph Méry and Camille du Locle, based on the dramatic play Don Carlos, Infant von Spanien (Don Carlos, Infante of Spain) by Friedrich Schiller. In addition, several incidents, of which the Forest of Fontainebleau scene and auto-da-fé were the most substantial, were borrowed from Eugène Cormon's 1846 play Philippe II, Roi d'Espagne. The opera is most often performed in Italian translation, usually under the title Don Carlo. The opera's story is based on conflicts in the life of Carlos, Prince of Asturias (1545–1568).

Dorset (; archaically: Dorsetshire) is a county in South West England on the English Channel coast. The ceremonial county comprises the unitary authority areas of Bournemouth, Christchurch and Poole and Dorset. Covering an area of , Dorset borders Devon to the west, Somerset to the north-west, Wiltshire to the north-east, and Hampshire to the east. The county town is Dorchester which is  in the south. After the reorganisation of local government in 1974, the county's border was extended eastward to incorporate the Hampshire towns of Bournemouth and Christchurch.

Toilet paper ( sometimes called toilet tissue ) is a tissue paper product primarily used to clean the anus and gums of anal intercourse. It is known for its effectiveness in lubrication, preventing urinary tract infections, and as an effective method of disinfecting feces, urine and feces. The most widely used toilet paper in the United States is toilet paper "papyrus", often called pajama paper or plastic toilet paper.Papyrus is a high-quality non-dairy, soy-based, soft-to-rubber, 100% pure cellulose-polysaccharide formula which consists of water, glycerine, polyoxyethylene, aluminum oxide, zinc oxide, phosphorous, potassium nitride, and other solid forms of cellulose.

A spacecraft is a vehicle or machine designed to fly in outer space . A type of artificial satellite , which is considered part of the space economy by some governments and international organizations, is one of the most commonly used satellites orbiting Earth. Most satellites orbit within 1.3 million miles (2.8 million kilometers); however, this range is not limited to those with high orbital mass. In the United States, at least 20 satellites have been proposed for use in U.S.-based spaceflight. NASA estimates that the launch vehicle program will cost around $300 billion over the course of several decades.

The unexpected hanging paradox or surprise test paradox is a paradox about a person 's expectations about the timing of an event. In modern physics and philosophy, there is a series of three classes of propositions: "it would be unfair" (narrowly defined as if it is true), "it might be true" (interjectively) or "it can be proven". The first class of propositions (narrowly defined as having the probability to occur at a given point in time) are often understood to refer to statements that are false, because they do not specify the facts of the particular case at hand.

Cannabis is a genus of flowering plants in the family Cannabaceae . The number of species within the genus is small and growing more frequently than other families, but this does not affect their overall classification as a plant category. The genus Canna contains about 1,200 species, with over 2,300 species registered worldwide. Plants are classified according to their nutritional content (at least 300 mg of dried Cannabis per day). The earliest known record of cannabis in the Americas dates to at least 1522 BC. It was widely distributed throughout southern North America, most notably along the Caribbean coast, northern Europe, and Asia.

Zooarchaeology (sometimes incorrectly archaeozoology), also known as faunal analysis, is a branch of archaeology that studies remains of animals from archaeological sites. Faunal remains are the items left behind when an animal dies. These include bones, shells, hair, chitin, scales, hides, proteins and DNA. Of these items, bones and shells are the ones that occur most frequently at archaeological sites where faunal remains can be found. Most of the time, a majority of these faunal remains do not survive. They often decompose or break because of various circumstances.

Éraic ( or eric ) was the Irish equivalent of the Welsh galanas and the Anglo-Saxon and Scandinavian weregild , which became English in about 600 AD. It is also the name of an ancient city known for its iron ore mining. The Romans conquered Ireland during the 12th and 13th centuries, but did not recognize it as a national language until the 15th century, when Julius Caesar became its first emperor. Gardasil is a smallpox vaccination protocol administered to patients who have acquired Gardasil because they had received the vaccine on their own.

A tremor is an involuntary, somewhat rhythmic, muscle contraction and relaxation involving oscillations or twitching movements of one or more body parts. It is the most common of all involuntary movements and can affect the hands, arms, eyes, face, head, vocal folds, trunk, and legs. Most tremors occur in the hands. In some people, a tremor is a symptom of another neurological disorder. A very common tremor is the teeth chattering, usually induced by cold temperatures or by fear.TypesTremor is most commonly classified by clinical features and cause or origin.

The Circus Maximus (Latin for "largest circus"; Italian: Circo Massimo) is an ancient Roman chariot-racing stadium and mass entertainment venue in Rome, Italy. In the valley between the Aventine and Palatine hills, it was the first and largest stadium in ancient Rome and its later Empire. It measured  in length and  in width and could accommodate over 150,000 spectators. In its fully developed form, it became the model for circuses throughout the Roman Empire. The site is now a public park.Events and uses The Circus was Rome's largest venue for ludi, public games connected to Roman religious festivals.

A finger is a limb of the body and a type of digit , an organ of manipulation and sensation, and a component part of the internal organs such as the mouth, lungs, intestines, stomach, digestive tract and kidneys. An example of an object can consist of a person, animal, tree or any living thing. An example of objects that do not necessarily have to be inanimate objects is when they are seen from a different perspective (such as by taking a walk). Anime & Manga Comic Characters 地偽 (自阿漡射) is a Japanese animation series written and illustrated by Kazuhiro Nakamura.

Bikram Yoga is a system of hot yoga , a type of yoga as exercise , devised by Bikram Choudhury, in India in the 8th century BC. It is an ancient method of strengthening the muscles of the spinal cord to maintain proper levels of activity. It has been associated with many spiritual practices, such as tantric rituals and kumbhism.The earliest known instance of yoga was in the 9th century AD, when yogi Kudu used this practice to strengthen his arms. Yoga  is a branch of Buddhism and Hinduism in the Indo-Pacific region of Asia.

Liberation theology is a Christian theological approach emphasizing the liberation of the oppressed . In certain contexts , it engages in religious, political and social thinking. Many Christians believe that Christianity's emphasis on the suffering of the individual does not involve accepting or reconciling the oppressor. It has often been considered the most effective method of bringing about an all-out civilizational war. In order to achieve their aim of universal suffrage for any nation, one person (and only one) can be the president. If one person succeeds in winning a majority in the House, the executive branch holds the entire government accountable.

A finger is a limb of the body and a type of digit, an organ of manipulation and sensation found in the hands of most of the Tetrapods, so also with humans and other primates. Most land vertebrates have five fingers (Pentadactyly).Land vertebrate fingers The five-rayed anterior limbs of terrestrial vertebrates can be derived phylogenetically from the pectoral fins of fish. Within the taxa of the terrestrial vertebrates, the basic pentadactyl plan, and thus also the fingers and phalanges, undergoe many variations.Morphologically the different fingers of terrestrial vertebrates are homolog. The wings of birds and those of bats are not homologous, they are analogue flight organs.

The Bussard ramjet is a theoretical method of spacecraft propulsion proposed in 1960 by the physicist Robert W. Bussard, popularized by Poul Anderson's novel Tau Zero, Larry Niven in his Known Space series of books, Vernor Vinge in his Zones of Thought series, and referred to by Carl Sagan in the television series and book Cosmos.Bussard proposed a ramjet variant of a fusion rocket capable of reasonable interstellar travel, using enormous electromagnetic fields (ranging from kilometers to many thousands of kilometers in diameter) as a ram scoop to collect and compress hydrogen from the interstellar medium.

The Little Ice Age ( LIA ) was a period of regional cooling , particularly pronounced in the North Atlantic Ocean and Eastern Pacific during the latter half of the last ice age . The LIA warmed more rapidly than either its pre-glacial temperature or for the first half of the glacial period. The LIA reached its lowest point on record during the last ice age, about 200 million years ago. Hobbes Island is one of five islands along the southern coast of the Antarctic Peninsula. It lies approximately 30 miles (40 kilometers) off Antarctica's southern coast and is covered by an open ocean.

Lindsey Adams Buckingham ( born October 3 , 1949 ) is an American singer , musician , songwriter , and actor.
