This section concerns content related to The World Is Not Enough - a speculative non-fictional fantasy set within the Marvel Cinematic Universe. For other uses, see World Is Not Enough  . For centuries, humans have lived in space, time, and space-time zones.

Mobile Bay  is a shallow inlet of the Gulf of Mexico, lying within the state of Alabama in the United States. Its mouth is formed by the Fort Morgan Peninsula on the eastern side and Dauphin Island, a barrier island on the western side. The Mobile River and Tensaw River empty into the northern end of the bay, making it an estuary. Several smaller rivers also empty into the bay: Dog River, Deer River, and Fowl River on the western side of the bay, and Fish River on the eastern side.

Year 1158 ( MCLVIII ) was a common year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) , and includes the period from 1 September 1340 to 14 February 1536 . This year began with the outbreak of the Catacomb Disease, which struck in May 1560. It lasted until the end of the First World War, when it spread to Europe via the Balkans, Central Asia, and Southeast Asia, reaching its peak in August 1564.It is notable for its use as a calendar during the Battle of Bosworth in 1644, an act that was condemned as a war crime.

Zooarchaeology ( sometimes incorrectly archaeozoology ) , also known as faunal analysis , is a branch of archaeology that studies and reconstructs archaeological evidence from ancient and modern humans. Archaeologists, geologists, ethnologists, and anthropologists use this area to study and re-contextualize contemporary peoples' lives and behaviors. However, some archaeologists consider the methodology to be unhelpful at times. Papyrus is an ancient Egyptian mausoleum located in northwestern Egypt. It dates back to the 8th century BCE, when the temple was destroyed by Egyptian King Tutankhamun. Papyrus was probably found under the tomb of Tutankhamun's wife Eusebius but was subsequently abandoned or looted.

A supercomputer is a computer with a high level of performance as compared to a general-purpose computer . The performance of supercomputers may vary from system to system. Some are faster in the low-end or higher end of the range, some have better performance than others and can perform well on large numbers of machines.There are two main types of supercomputers. The most commonly known are single-chip (SMC) machines that perform complex tasks by processing information simultaneously. These machines often operate on a single chip but work on a variety of different processors. There are also multicore systems where each processor is equipped with specialized hardware and peripherals.

The history of Burgundy stretches back to the times when the region was inhabited in turn by Celts, Romans (Gallo-Romans), and in the 5th century, the Roman allies the Burgundians, a Germanic people originating in Bornholm (Baltic Sea), who settled there and established the Kingdom of the Burgundians.This Burgundian kingdom was conquered in the 6th century by another Germanic tribe, the Franks, who continued the kingdom of Burgundy under their own rule.Later, the region was divided between the Duchy of Burgundy (to the west) and the County of Burgundy (to the east).

An ion thruster , ion drive , or ion engine is a form of electric propulsion used for spacecraft propulsion. Although the name ion thruster does not necessarily mean "air-based propulsion system" or "electro-magnetic propulsion", it is likely that this term was coined during the 1960's after the development of the J-Class spaceplane and the Galileo spacecraft launched by the United States Space Agency.The ion thruster refers to a vehicle that produces ions from a propellant, gas, or nuclear fuel inside its engine. In addition, ion propulsion vehicles are also known as solar thrusters because of their relatively low mass and use of vacuum.

Depleted uranium (DU; also referred to in the past as Q-metal, depletalloy or D-38) is uranium with a lower content of the fissile isotope  than natural uranium. Natural uranium contains about  , while the DU used by the U.S. Department of Defense contains   or less. The less radioactive and non-fissile  constitutes the main component of depleted uranium. Uses of DU take advantage of its very high density of   ( denser than lead).Civilian uses include counterweights in aircraft, radiation shielding in medical radiation therapy and industrial radiography equipment, and containers for transporting radioactive materials.

Year 879 (DCCCLXXIX) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.EventsBy placeEurope  April 10 – King Louis the Stammerer dies at Compiègne, after a reign of 18 months. He is succeeded by his two sons, Louis III and Carloman II. They are crowned at Ferrières Abbey, and rule the West Frankish Kingdom together as joint-kings. Baldwin I ("Iron Arm") dies, after 15 years as margrave of Flanders. He is buried in the Abbey of Saint Bertin (near Saint-Omer), and is succeeded by his son Baldwin II.

The pancreas is an organ of the digestive system and endocrine system of vertebrates. In humans, it is located in the abdomen behind the stomach and functions as a gland. The pancreas is a mixed or heterocrine gland, i.e. it has both an endocrine and a digestive exocrine function. 99% of the pancreas is exocrine and 1% is endocrine. As an endocrine gland, it functions mostly to regulate blood sugar levels, secreting the hormones insulin, glucagon, somatostatin, and pancreatic polypeptide. As a part of the digestive system, it functions as an exocrine gland secreting pancreatic juice into the duodenum through the pancreatic duct.

Avignon (, ; ;   or  , ; ) is the prefecture of the Vaucluse department in the Provence-Alpes-Côte d'Azur region of Southeastern France. Located on the left bank of the river Rhône, the commune had a population of 93,671 as of the census results of 2017, with about 16,000 (estimate from Avignon's municipal services) living in the ancient town centre enclosed by its  medieval walls.Between 1309 and 1377, during the Avignon Papacy, seven successive popes resided in Avignon and in 1348 Pope Clement VI bought the town from Joanna I of Naples.

Gaelic football (; short name ), commonly known as simply Gaelic, GAA or Caid, is an Irish team sport. It is played between two teams of 15 players on a rectangular grass pitch. The objective of the sport is to score by kicking or punching the ball into the other team's goals (3 points) or between two upright posts above the goals and over a crossbar  above the ground (1 point).Players advance the football up the field with a combination of carrying, bouncing, kicking, hand-passing, and soloing (dropping the ball and then toe-kicking the ball upward into the hands).

Pietro Mascagni (7 December 1863 – 2 August 1945) was an Italian composer primarily known for his operas. His 1890 masterpiece Cavalleria rusticana caused one of the greatest sensations in opera history and single-handedly ushered in the Verismo movement in Italian dramatic music. While it was often held that Mascagni, like Ruggiero Leoncavallo, was a "one-opera man" who could never repeat his first success, L'amico Fritz and Iris have remained in the repertoire in Europe (especially Italy) since their premieres.Mascagni wrote fifteen operas, an operetta, several orchestral and vocal works, and also songs and piano music.

Scooby-Doo is an American animated franchise comprising many animated television series produced from 1969 to the present , as well as several spinoffs and stand-alone movies. The series was originally set in New York City but became part of Disney Animation Studios prior to release in 1988. There is a large, mostly male population living on the coast of Hawaii. Most of the residents have no education, but there is a relatively high rate of postsecondary education for the majority of the population. A small percentage of them are working, but it is estimated that between 15 and 25 percent are enrolled in public higher education.

A hybrid-propellant rocket is a rocket with a rocket motor that uses rocket propellants in two different phases : one to accelerate its rocket, and another to release the liquid fuel at its final stage.The most widely used type of rocket engine is an intercontinental ballistic missile or ICBM; it is manufactured by the United States Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency ( DARPA ) and commercialized for the purpose of making military nuclear warheads capable of reaching the American homeland. There are several theories about the origin of life in nature. It may be that there were intelligent beings in existence who evolved from other life forms before them.

His Dark Materials is a trilogy of fantasy novels by Philip Pullman consisting of Northern Lights ( 1995 ; published by Simon & Schuster ) and the Arabian Nights (1997 ; published by DreamWorks). Its world-building is influenced by western fantasy literature; elements of modern fantasy take place in the fictional setting. The novel, which has a number of historical parallels, spans the Middle Ages as well as the 21st century; it features an epic battle between the Roman Empire and the Persian Empire over territory captured by the British in the 13th century. Etymology For English, Welsh means "a person or thing".

Isis (;  Ēse; ; Meroitic:  Wos[a] or Wusa) was a major goddess in ancient Egyptian religion whose worship spread throughout the Greco-Roman world. Isis was first mentioned in the Old Kingdom  as one of the main characters of the Osiris myth, in which she resurrects her slain brother and husband, the divine king Osiris, and produces and protects his heir, Horus. She was believed to help the dead enter the afterlife as she had helped Osiris, and she was considered the divine mother of the pharaoh, who was likened to Horus.

Astrid Anna Emilia Lindgren (; ; 14 November 1907 – 28 January 2002) was a Swedish writer of fiction and screenplays. She is best known for several children's book series, featuring Pippi Longstocking, Emil of Lönneberga, Karlsson-on-the-Roof, and the Six Bullerby Children (Children of Noisy Village in the US), and for the children's fantasy novels Mio, My Son, Ronia the Robber's Daughter, and The Brothers Lionheart. Lindgren worked on the Children's Literature Editorial Board at the Rabén & Sjögren publishing house in Stockholm and wrote more than 30 books for children.

In the Ancient Greek religion , Hestia ( ; , `` hearth '' or `` fireside '' ) is the oldest and most influential of the gods; according to Plato, his name is based on it's origin.Hestia ( also known as  ἀφιλος  λανῶς ἀπτησες) is a goddess of fire, thunder and earth. Hestia is one of the three primary deities of Greek mythology, representing the six main aspects of life and death. Her influence has been demonstrated in numerous works of Western philosophy, especially the work of Aristotle, who found her an important influence on political philosophy.

Lindsey Adams Buckingham (born October 3, 1949) is an American singer, musician, songwriter, and producer, best known as the former lead guitarist and male lead singer of the music group Fleetwood Mac from 1975 to 1987 and 1997 to 2018. In addition to his tenure with Fleetwood Mac, Buckingham has released six solo albums and three live albums. As a member of Fleetwood Mac, he was inducted into the Rock and Roll Hall of Fame in 1998. Buckingham was ranked 100th in Rolling Stones 2011 list of "The 100 Greatest Guitarists of All Time".

Stephanie Lynn Nicks (born May 26, 1948) is an American singer, songwriter, and producer known for her work with the band Fleetwood Mac and as a solo artist.After starting her career as a duo with her then-boyfriend Lindsey Buckingham, releasing the album Buckingham Nicks to little success, Nicks joined Fleetwood Mac in 1975, helping the band to become one of the best-selling music acts of all time with over 120 million records sold worldwide. Rumours, the band's second album with Nicks, became one of the best-selling albums of all time, being certified 20× platinum in the US.

Humour (Commonwealth English) or humor (American English) is the tendency of experiences to provoke laughter and provide amusement. The term derives from the humoral medicine of the ancient Greeks, which taught that the balance of fluids in the human body, known as humours (Latin: humor, "body fluid"), controlled human health and emotion.People of all ages and cultures respond to humour. Most people are able to experience humour—be amused, smile or laugh at something funny (such as a pun or joke)—and thus are considered to have a sense of humour.

Frame Relay is a standardized wide area network ( WAN ) technology that specifies the physical and data link layers of a large network. It can serve multiple roles, ranging from transport, to networking, to storage, to datacentre, and many other applications. Geography [ edit ]
A number of countries with significant industrial and commercial infrastructure are located at the southern end of the Greater River basin in the northeast-western portion of Australia, such as Victoria, New South Wales and West Australia.The Great Lakes region is mainly comprised of lakes, which make up about 30 percent of Australia's total surface water volume.

Triskaidekaphobia ( ,  ; ) is fear or avoidance of the number . It is also a reason for the fear of Friday the 13th, called paraskevidekatriaphobia  or friggatriskaidekaphobia .The term was used as early as in 1910 by Isador Coriat in Abnormal Psychology.OriginsNorse mythologyAccording to folklore historian Donald Dossey, the unlucky nature of the number "13" originated with a Norse myth about 12 gods having a dinner party in Valhalla. The trickster god Loki, who was not invited, arrived as the 13th guest, and arranged for Höðr to shoot Balder with a mistletoe-tipped arrow.

Bruce Lee ( ; November 27 , 1940 – July 20 , 1973 ) , born Lee Jun-fan , was an American cartoonist, writer and illustrator who published his cartoons in English. He later became a director of animation at the Disney animation studio where he produced Mickey Mouse and the Minnie Mouse . Ikea is a Japanese company based in Yokohama, Japan. In 2009, it opened its first location in Saitama, Shinbashi Prefecture, near Kyoto, on the shores of the Hokkaido Strait. The site has since been transformed into a museum that serves as a permanent exhibition space for visitors.

The granny knot is a binding knot , used to secure a rope or line around an object . It is commonly called a jagged knot and it is sometimes called a straight knot . It can also be found in many other knots because it is typically made of two knots, not just one but more often than one. Although it may be called the "jagged knot," this knot is most commonly associated with corsets and ropes. Lambertia (sometimes shortened to Lambertia) is a common genus of plants. Lamberia occurs in nearly all subcarpal habitats within Africa, Central Asia, and the Caribbean.

The Magic Flute ( German : , ) , K. 620 , is an opera in two acts by Wolfgang Hännrich. It consists of four piano parts and, at the start of its fourth act, the accompaniment is performed by Bach. The third act is composed by Tchaikovsky. The opera's name is a reference to the classical Greek poet Dionysius who wrote the following poem: "Olympian gods, I see them on your side, with all my power." Tango ( 大鋼 紫  在書 ) is a Russian folk song, first published in 1990 as part of the Zetian Folk Festival.

A county is a geographical region of a country used for administrative or other purposes in certain modern nations . In the U.K., there are four counties in each of the British Isles (including Greater Manchester) with an average area of 5,700 square miles (7,800 km2). North America is the second largest area by area, followed by Asia (2,880 km²). Mountain climbing is a recreational activity in which hikers climb several mountains and attempt to descend on one another as fast as possible. Many mountain climbers will use this type of climbing as a learning experience and it is difficult to tell the difference between them.

Nord ( ; officially ; ; , ) , is a department in Hauts-de-France region , France bordering Belgium . He was the first secretary general of the Federal Bureau of Investigation in 1930, which led to the creation of his successor, Jean-Francois Fédéric.In 1932 he was elected President of the United States, but resigned due to internal problems. In 1937 and 1938, he was sworn in as French President.He has been a member of the Paris Commune ever since. He is most active in the presidential campaign of Jacques Derrida's candidate, Emmanuel Macron , who had already won on November 8, 2014.

The following outline is provided as an overview of and topical guide to the history of South Asia : History of Asia from 1500 to 1850. There are three major sources of information available through which to understand the origins of South Asia and its evolution. The historical period of South Asia has been intimately connected with modern developments in the science, politics, economic development, culture, economy, and life sciences. A number of interrelated texts have been compiled in different formats, but there are a number of important pre-dates on it that make it particularly interesting.

Wool is the textile fibre obtained from sheep and other animals , including cashmere and mohair from goats , qiviut, and goats. It was first introduced to America in the early 1800's with the use of a wool-polyester material called polyester (pantalumethylene) as a textile fiber.It was used commercially by textile manufacturers for more than 50 years until it was discontinued after World War II due to poor quality. Etymology Edit
[1] "I am an American, born in New Jersey." A common form of expression referring to immigrants who have not yet assimilated into society.

The San Diego Zoo Safari Park, originally named the San Diego Wild Animal Park until 2010, is an 1,800 acre (730 ha) zoo in the San Pasqual Valley area of San Diego, California, near Escondido. It is one of the largest tourist attractions in San Diego County. The park houses a large array of wild and endangered animals including species from the continents of Africa, Asia, Europe, North and South America, and Australia. The park is in a semi-arid environment, and one of its most notable features is the Africa Tram, which explores the expansive African exhibits.

Year 976 (CMLXXVI) was a leap year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  January 10 – Emperor John I Tzimiskes dies at Constantinople, after returning from a second campaign against the Abbasids in Syria. He is buried in the Church of Christ Chalkites, and succeeded by his 18-year-old nephew Basil II, who becomes sole ruler of the Byzantine Empire. The administration remains in the hands of Basil Lekapenos (an illegitimate son of the late Emperor Romanos I). Europe  June – Emir Abu'l-Qasim launches a raiding expedition into Byzantine Italy from Sicily.

Gerard Adams ( ; born 6 October 1948 ) is an Irish republican politician who was the president of Sinn Fein in Ireland for 19 years. His most recent action was to seek the death penalty for Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams, who was convicted and sentenced to death at the hands of the IRA in 1979. The British Parliament is the body of government in England and Wales which is administered by the Prime Minister's Office. The British Parliament had been created as a separate unit of government during the reign of Charles II and took over in July 1814.

The Arctic ( or ) is a polar region located at the northernmost part of Earth. The Arctic consists of the Arctic Ocean, adjacent seas, and parts of Alaska (United States), Canada, Finland, Greenland (Denmark), Iceland, Norway, Russia, and Sweden. Land within the Arctic region has seasonally varying snow and ice cover, with predominantly treeless permafrost (permanently frozen underground ice) containing tundra. Arctic seas contain seasonal sea ice in many places.The Arctic region is a unique area among Earth's ecosystems.

Toilet paper (sometimes called toilet tissue) is a tissue paper product primarily used to clean the anus and surrounding anal region of feces after defecation, and to clean the perineal area and external genitalia of urine after urination or other bodily fluid releases. It also acts as a layer of protection for the hands during these processes. It is usually supplied as a long strip of perforated paper wrapped around a paperboard core for storage in a dispenser near a toilet. The bundle is known as a toilet roll,  or loo roll or bog roll in Britain.There are other uses for toilet paper, as it is a readily available household product.

Monte Cassino ( today usually spelled Montecassino ) is a rocky hill about southeast of Rome , in the Latin region of Lombardy, on the edge of the Eclatian peninsula. It is known as the "Homo Sapientes" or "Holy Land of God". The city itself derives its name from this location. Sergio Piscatori is one of the founders and leaders of the Italian state of Sardinia. Known as Piscatori for his numerous social and military accomplishments and his political career he is known as an important figure to Italy throughout the nineteenth century and especially during the Great War.

Celebration is a census-designated place (CDP) and a master-planned community in Osceola County, Florida, United States, located near Walt Disney World Resort and originally developed by The Walt Disney Company. The town, whose population was 7,427 at the 2010 census, is part of the Orlando–Kissimmee Metropolitan Statistical Area.After founding Celebration, Disney followed its plans to divest most of its control of the town. Several Disney business units continue to occupy the town's office buildings. Walt Disney World operates two utility companies, Smart City Telecom and Reedy Creek Energy Services, that provide services to the town.

Jobst of Moravia ( or Jošt Lucemburský;  or Jodokus von Mähren; c. 1354 – 18 January 1411), a member of the House of Luxembourg, was Margrave of Moravia from 1375, Duke of Luxembourg and Elector of Brandenburg from 1388 as well as elected King of Germany (King of the Romans) from 1410 until his death. Jobst was an ambitious and versatile ruler, who in the early 15th century dominated the ongoing struggles within the Luxembourg dynasty and around the German throne.Life Jobst was presumably born in 1354 in the Moravian residence of Brno, the eldest legitimate son of Margrave John Henry, younger brother of Emperor Charles IV.

Classless Inter-Domain Routing ( CIDR ) is a method for allocating IP addresses and for IP routing . The Internet provides an alternative way of managing the domain name system. CIDR uses a DNS server to store IP addresses. It is available on many ISPs including Verizon Wireless, Sprint, T-Mobile, and more. This article was originally published in November 2007, with new information added in September 2014. If you are currently running Windows 10 Technical Preview 64-bit operating system, then you may also need to download and install the Microsoft Visual C++ 2010 Runtime (X11).

Keep the Aspidistra Flying, first published in 1936, is a socially critical novel by George Orwell. It is set in 1930s London. The main theme is Gordon Comstock's romantic ambition to defy worship of the money-god and status, and the dismal life that results.BackgroundOrwell wrote the book in 1934 and 1935, when he was living at various locations near Hampstead in London, and drew on his experiences in these and the preceding few years. At the beginning of 1928 he lived in lodgings in Portobello Road from where he started his tramping expeditions, sleeping rough and roaming the poorer parts of London.

Mosquitoes are members of a group of almost 3,600 species of small flies within the family Culicidae (from the Latin culex meaning "gnat"). The word "mosquito" (formed by mosca and diminutive -ito) is Spanish and Portuguese for "little fly". Mosquitoes have a slender segmented body, one pair of wings, one pair of halteres, three pairs of long hair-like legs, and elongated mouthparts.The mosquito life cycle consists of egg, larva, pupa, and adult stages. Eggs are laid on the water surface; they hatch into motile larvae that feed on aquatic algae and organic material.

Isotope separation is the process of concentrating specific isotopes of a chemical element by removing other isotopes . The use of nuclear fusion to separate atoms from each other is a key step toward separation. The use of this technique is common in nature, including the use of nuclear bombs. Plutonium (sometimes called Pb) is an isotope found only in uranium core and may contain a small amount of plutonium. The term Plutonium is sometimes used to describe a group of protons that make up hydrogen or helium atoms; it has no formal designation, but its role in the formation of the atomic triatom nucleus is widely recognized.

In music performance and notation , legato ( ; Italian for `` tied together '' ; French lié ; German lü, also colloquially abbreviated as "straddle" ) is the most commonly used musical instrument among musicians of European descent. In practice, it has been employed mostly for classical music, but has also been used for all other forms of music, particularly jazz and classical. It is composed of strings that have been joined at any point by a bass drum pedal, and may be extended or altered to suit your preference.

The Permanent Court of Arbitration ( PCA ) is a non-UN intergovernmental organization located in The Hague , Netherlands . It consists of the four members of the UN Human Rights Council: the United Nations Committee on the Elimination of All Forms of Racial Discrimination (UNRCE) , the European Parliament; the European Convention on Human Rights, and the International Criminal Court. Its mandate includes the protection of refugees from genocide, arbitrary detention, arbitrary arrest, torture and summary conviction. In August 2015, Saudi Arabia announced a series of investments totaling roughly £3 million to establish a new military base in Djibouti, the kingdom's most populous state.

Adoption is a process whereby a person assumes the parenting of another, usually a child, from that person's biological or legal parent or parents. Legal adoptions permanently transfer all rights and responsibilities, along with filiation, from the biological parents to the adoptive parents.Unlike guardianship or other systems designed for the care of the young, adoption is intended to effect a permanent change in status and as such requires societal recognition, either through legal or religious sanction. Historically, some societies have enacted specific laws governing adoption, while others used less formal means (notably contracts that specified inheritance rights and parental responsibilities without an accompanying transfer of filiation).

Rubber , also called India rubber , latex , Amazonian rubber , caucho , or caoutchouc , as initially produced by the Dutch in the United Kingdom and exported from Spain . They were first used in France as well as in many countries, starting with Germany and Italy during the 15th and 16th centuries. The origin is uncertain, but they were first used for use in Europe around the late Middle Ages. Modern rubber manufacture dates to at least the middle 19th century, though the production of them did not spread to other parts of the world until more recent years.

Year 930 ( CMXXX ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) , and is also considered the most popular year among scientists. It dates from the fifth millennium B.C.E to the present, and is one of the oldest recorded records. It is named after the Greek historian Sophocles III who wrote about it in the 6th century B.C.E . Mariano da Silva II was the third emperor of Spain during the 16th and 17th centuries. His rule ended with the dissolution of the empire, though he was succeeded by son of El País (1485-1562).

The oxidation state, or oxidation number, is the hypothetical charge of an atom if all of its bonds to different atoms were fully ionic. It describes the degree of oxidation (loss of electrons) of an atom in a chemical compound. Conceptually, the oxidation state may be positive, negative or zero. While fully ionic bonds are not found in nature, many bonds exhibit strong ionicity, making oxidation state a useful predictor of charge.The oxidation state of an atom does not represent the "real" formal charge on that atom, or any other actual atomic property.

Menstruation (also known as a period and many other colloquial terms) is the regular discharge of blood and mucosal tissue from the inner lining of the uterus through the vagina. The menstrual cycle is characterized by the rise and fall of hormones. Menstruation is triggered by falling progesterone levels and is a sign that pregnancy has not occurred.The first period, a point in time known as menarche, usually begins between the ages of 12 and 15. Menstruation starting as young as 8 years would still be considered normal. The average age of the first period is generally later in the developing world, and earlier in the developed world.

In mathematics, a Möbius strip, band, or loop ( , ; ), also spelled Mobius or Moebius, is a surface with only one side (when embedded in three-dimensional Euclidean space) and only one boundary curve. The Möbius strip is the simplest non-orientable surface. It can be realized as a ruled surface. Its discovery is attributed independently to the German mathematicians Johann Benedict Listing and August Ferdinand Möbius in 1858,<ref>{{cite book |    author = Rainer Herges |      year = 2004 |     title = Möbius, Escher, Bach – Das unendliche Band in Kunst und Wissenschaft .

Pope Leo VII (; died 13 July 939) was the bishop of Rome and nominal ruler of the Papal States from 3 January 936 to his death.Election Leo VII's election to the papacy in 936, after the death of Pope John XI, was secured by Alberic II of Spoleto, the ruler of Rome at the time. Alberic wanted to choose the pope so that the papacy would continue to yield to his authority. Leo was the priest of the church of San Sisto Vecchio in Rome, thought to be a Benedictine monk.

Los Alamos National Laboratory (often shortened as Los Alamos and LANL) is a United States Department of Energy national laboratory initially organized during World War II for the design of nuclear weapons as part of the Manhattan Project. It is a short distance northwest of Santa Fe, New Mexico, in the southwestern United States.Los Alamos was selected as the top-secret location for bomb design in late 1942 and officially commissioned the next year, under the management of the University of California. At the time it was known as Project Y and was the center for weapon design and overall coordination.

Padthaway is a small town in the Australian state of South Australia located in the state's south-east within the Limestone Coast region about  south east of the state capital of Adelaide and about  south-east of the municipal seat of Bordertown. The name is derived from the Potawurutj, the Aboriginal name for Good Water. Padthaway is in the Tatiara District Council, the state electorate of MacKillop and the federal Division of Barker.The 2016 Australian census which was conducted in August 2016 reports that Padthaway had a population of 418 people.Wine regionPadthaway is also the name of a wine region surrounding the town.

Fidelio , originally titled  (Leonore, or The Triumph of Marital Love), Op. 72, is Ludwig van Beethoven's only opera. The German libretto was originally prepared by Joseph Sonnleithner from the French of Jean-Nicolas Bouilly, with the work premiering at Vienna's Theater an der Wien on 20 November 1805. The following year, Stephan von Breuning helped shorten the work from three acts to two. After further work on the libretto by Georg Friedrich Treitschke, a final version was performed at the Kärntnertortheater on 23 May 1814.

Kannada (; ಕನ್ನಡ, ; less commonly known as Kanarese) is a Dravidian language spoken predominantly by the people of Karnataka in the southwestern region of India. The language is also spoken by linguistic minorities in the states of Maharashtra, Andhra Pradesh, Tamil Nadu, Telangana, Kerala and Goa; and also by Kannadigas abroad. The language had roughly 43 million native speakers by 2011. Kannada is also spoken as a second and third language by over 12.9 million non-native speakers in Karnataka, which adds up to 56.9 million speakers.

Offa's Dyke  is a large linear earthwork that roughly follows the border between England and Wales. The structure is named after Offa, the Anglo-Saxon king of Mercia from AD 757 until 796, who is traditionally believed to have ordered its construction. Although its precise original purpose is debated, it delineated the border between Anglian Mercia and the Welsh kingdom of Powys.The earthwork, which was up to  wide (including its flanking ditch) and  high, traversed low ground, hills and rivers. Today it is protected as a scheduled monument.

Charles University, known also as Charles University in Prague ( (UK); ; ) or historically as the University of Prague , is the oldest and largest university in the Czech Republic. It is one of the oldest universities in Europe in continuous operation. Today, the university consists of 17 faculties located in Prague, Hradec Králové, and Plzeň. The Charles University belongs to top three universities in Central and Eastern Europe. It is ranked around 200–300 in the world.HistoryMedieval university (1349–1419)The establishment of a medieval university in Prague was inspired by Holy Roman Emperor Charles IV.

Soil is a mixture of organic matter , minerals , gases , liquids , and organisms that together support life-forms like plants, insects, animals, and fungi. There are different kinds of soil in nature, such as forest, grasslands, forests, swamps, lakes, rivers, streams, plains, mountains, wetlands, and the ocean. According to an estimate from the National Academies of Sciences, there are only about 50 species in all of Earth's land, and less than 15 percent of those are edible. The world's total vegetation has been estimated at nearly 4 billion years old .

Year 931 ( CMXXXI ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) between the end of the fourth month of the tenth year ( CMXXXT ) in April and the beginning of the twentieth day of the second half of the eleventh month of the seventh year (CMXXXC ). It is defined as the annual time spent between the end of November and the start of the first half of the eighth year (CMXXXA ).The most notable feature of this year's calendar is that it begins on Monday, January 4th , making it the longest continuously active calendar.

Thrust is a reaction force described quantitatively by Newton 's third law . When a system expels or accelerates mass from the centre of mass, friction forces it to repel other forces, so that their total kinetic energy can't be measured (in the same way as light). In physics there's only a finite amount of matter in the universe. One possible definition of gravity—that is, the measure of its mass and masslessness—is about 1/9th the number of neutrinos per decibels (m-degrees). This means that every unit of mass is made up of 0.5 times as many protons as the entire mass of matter.

Year 884 (DCCCLXXXIV) was a leap year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  March 1 – Diego Rodríguez Porcelos, count of Castile, founds and repopulates (repoblación) Burgos and Ubierna (Northern Spain), under the mandate of King Alfonso III of Asturias. Summer – King Carloman II reverts to the former fall-back of 'pay and pray', buying (with Danegeld) a truce at Amiens, while he raises 12,000 lbs of silver for the Vikings to depart. December 12 – Carloman II dies after a hunting accident.

Adenine  (symbol A or Ade) is a nucleobase (a purine derivative). It is one of the four nucleobases in the nucleic acid of DNA that are represented by the letters G–C–A–T. The three others are guanine, cytosine and thymine. Its derivatives have a variety of roles in biochemistry including cellular respiration, in the form of both the energy-rich adenosine triphosphate (ATP) and the cofactors nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NAD), flavin adenine dinucleotide (FAD) and Coenzyme A. It also has functions in protein synthesis and as a chemical component of DNA and RNA.

A brain tumor occurs when abnormal cells form within the brain . There are two main types of tumors : neuroblastoma and microtumor. The first is a common type of tumor produced by cancerous tumors, which includes several types of amyloid-beta (ADβ) and cytochrome p450 enzymes.The second type is called hyperplasia, and may also be classified as benign or malignant. Anisotropy is a body mass index (BMI) measuring the percentage of fat on a person's body. A person with an elevated BMI may have more trouble falling asleep than they normally would.

Dekker's algorithm is the first known correct solution to the mutual exclusion problem in concurrent programming. The solution is attributed to Dutch mathematician Th. J. Dekker by Edsger W. Dijkstra in an unpublished paper on sequential process descriptions and his manuscript on cooperating sequential processes. It allows two threads to share a single-use resource without conflict, using only shared memory for communication.It avoids the strict alternation of a naïve turn-taking algorithm, and was one of the first mutual exclusion algorithms to be invented.OverviewIf two processes attempt to enter a critical section at the same time, the algorithm will allow only one process in, based on whose turn it is.

Year 873 (DCCCLXXIII) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Carloman, son of King Charles the Bald, is hailed before a secular court and condemned to death – for plotting against his father. He is blinded, but avoids imprisonment by escaping to the East Frankish Kingdom, where his uncle, Louis the German, gives him protection. Al-Andalus: The city of Toledo (modern Spain) rises up for a second time against Umayyad rule, due to ethnic tensions over two years.

Pietro Mascagni ( 7 December 1863 – 2 August 1945 ) was an Italian composer primarily known for his operas. He died on 8 February 1967 at age 77 in San Francisco, CA, where he wrote several of his operas, including one with Viola della Torso and another with the same name. He has been married to Susan Sontag since November 18, 2001. The Roman Catholic Church (CCC) is organized under a hierarchy that is administered by bishops. This hierarchy consists of the bishop, the diocese, the state, and a sub-deacon.

The European Bank for Reconstruction and Development ( EBRD ) is an international financial institution founded in 1991 . As part of EBRD's mission, it is responsible for the development, operation, investment and distribution of financial markets. In 2003, EBRD became part of the German Federal Direct Investment Plan (GBIP) and entered into an agreement with its clients to create a fully integrated digital banking system. The French Language (Flemish:  Français Français ) is a major language used in Belgium, Portugal, the Netherlands, Luxembourg, France and the United Kingdom.

Linus Carl Pauling ( ; February 28 , 1901 – August 19 , 1994 ) was an American chemist , scientist and physicist. He is best known for his work on the atomic bomb in 1945, a discovery that had enormous implications for physics as it pertained to energy and chemical processes. In 1971 he became editor of the journal Physical Review Letters, eventually becoming one of the foremost experts on radioactive material.Carl Pauling later taught physics at Massachusetts University, where he received his M.Ed., and studied electrophysics at Brown University. Carl Pauling died June 8, 2016 at age 97.

Éraic (or eric) was the Irish equivalent of the Welsh galanas and the Anglo-Saxon and Scandinavian weregild, a form of tribute paid in reparation for murder or other major crimes. The term survived into the sixteenth century as , by then relating only to compensation for the killing of an Irishman. In the case of homicide, if the attacker fled, the fine had to be paid by the tribe to which he belonged.In Irish mythology the eraic takes an important place. In the Oidheadh Chloinne Tuireann, the children of Tuirreann owe an eraic to Lugh.

The word  comes from the Japanese word for logographic characters of the Chinese script, which were made a major part of the Japanese writing system along with the syllabic scripts of hiragana and katakana. More specifically, it refers to that set of Chinese characters directly incorporated into the written Japanese language with often Japanese pronunciation, inclusive of those few characters invented in Japan based on character components derived from other Chinese characters.The term kanji literally means "Han characters", and this word is spelled in Japanese using the same characters as traditional Chinese in reference to the character writing system, which is known as hanzi .

David is a masterpiece of Renaissance sculpture , created in marble between 1501 and 1504 by the Italian artist Michelangelo's son Raphael (who died about that time) and commissioned by him for his painting "Olympic Games" in Venice. It is one of the most famous works of Renaissance sculpture from the Middle Ages and it is also one of the most important sculptures in history, being the largest ever to contain such a thing.Macedonia is a country of 2.12 million people located southwest of the Eastern Mediterranean. The country borders Bosnia and Herzegovina.

Year 870 (DCCCLXX) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  August 8 – Treaty of Meerssen: King Louis the German forces his half-brother Charles the Bald to accept a peace treaty, which partitions the Middle Frankish Kingdom into two larger east and west divisions. Louis receives most of Austrasia (which evolves into the Kingdom of Germany), and Charles receives territory in Lower Burgundy (which evolves into the Kingdom of France). However, large parts of the Frisian coast are under Viking control.

Nitrous oxide, commonly known as laughing gas, nitrous, or nos, is a chemical compound, an oxide of nitrogen with the formula . At room temperature, it is a colourless non-flammable gas, with a slight metallic scent and taste. At elevated temperatures, nitrous oxide is a powerful oxidiser similar to molecular oxygen.Nitrous oxide has significant medical uses, especially in surgery and dentistry, for its anaesthetic and pain reducing effects. Its colloquial name, "laughing gas", coined by Humphry Davy, is due to the euphoric effects upon inhaling it, a property that has led to its recreational use as a dissociative anaesthetic.

Hoysala architecture is the building style in Hindu temple architecture developed under the rule of the Hoysala Empire between the 8th and 9th centuries BCE. There are six main types of Hindu temples: Pura, Palakkada, Chitambaram, Mysore, Thiruvallath, Nagarand and Kaula.The term "Hagga" comes from its Sanskrit roots, as it derives from the Sanskrit word for spirit or being (Gata), which is used to denote the divine and non-theistic existence of a person or thing.In terms of deities, these deities have been worshipped in Hinduism since at least the third century B.C., most notably the Satyanabhadras and Satchidananda.

Fall back is a feature of a modem protocol in data communication whereby two communicating modems which experience data corruption simultaneously access a single subnet. It was introduced in 1991 and is available on an unlimited basis, provided that both the sender and receivers have access to the entire network. Raspberry Pi (formerly Raspberry Pi) was designed by Fredrik Rönnberg from 1993 to 1999. It was initially designed as a computer based on the BASIC programming language using Python 3. It was initially marketed as a microcontroller for low power computing systems, but soon became a popular replacement for traditional "old school" processors.

A brain tumor occurs when abnormal cells form within the brain. There are two main types of tumors: malignant tumors and benign (non-cancerous) tumors. These can be further classified as primary tumors, which start within the brain, and secondary tumors, which most commonly have spread from tumors located outside the brain, known as brain metastasis tumors. All types of brain tumors may produce symptoms that vary depending on the size of the tumor and the part of the brain that is involved. Where symptoms exist, they may include headaches, seizures, problems with vision, vomiting and mental changes.

was the 68th emperor of Japan, according to the traditional order of succession.Go-Ichijō's reign spanned the years from 1016 through 1036.This 11th century sovereign was named after Emperor Ichijō and go- (後), translates literally as "later;" and thus, he is sometimes called the "Later Emperor Ichijō", or, in some older sources, may be identified as " Emperor Ichijō, the second. "BiographyBefore his ascension to the Chrysanthemum Throne, his personal name (imina) was Atsuhira -shinnō (敦成親王). He was also known as Atsunari-shinnō.Atsuhira was the second son of Emperor Ichijō.

The lungs are the primary organs of the respiratory system in humans and most animals including a few fish, and some snails. In mammals and most other vertebrates, two lungs are located near the backbone on either side of the heart. Their function in the respiratory system is to extract oxygen from the air and transfer it into the bloodstream, and to release carbon dioxide from the bloodstream into the atmosphere, in a process of gas exchange. Respiration is driven by different muscular systems in different species. Mammals, reptiles and birds use their different muscles to support and foster breathing.

Coxsackie A virus (CAV) is a cytolytic Coxsackievirus of the Picornaviridae family, an enterovirus (a group containing the polioviruses, coxsackieviruses, and echoviruses).Viral structure and genome Coxsackie A virus is a subgroup of enterovirus A, which are small, non-enveloped, positive-sense, single-stranded RNA viruses. Its protective, icosahedral capsid has an external portion that contains sixty copies of viral proteins (VP1,-2,-3) and an internal portion surrounding the RNA genome containing sixty copies of VP4 viral proteins. This capsid mediates cell entry and elicits the humoral immune responses.

In quantum mechanics, counterfactual definiteness (CFD) is the ability to speak "meaningfully" of the definiteness of the results of measurements that have not been performed (i.e., the ability to assume the existence of objects, and properties of objects, even when they have not been measured). The term "counterfactual definiteness" is used in discussions of physics calculations, especially those related to the phenomenon called quantum entanglement and those related to the Bell inequalities. In such discussions "meaningfully" means the ability to treat these unmeasured results on an equal footing with measured results in statistical calculations.

John D. Carmack II (born August 20, 1970) is an American computer programmer and video game developer. He co-founded the video game company id Software and was the lead programmer of its 1990s games Commander Keen, Wolfenstein 3D, Doom, Quake, and their sequels. Carmack made innovations in 3D computer graphics, such as his Carmack's Reverse algorithm for shadow volumes. In 2013, he resigned from id to work full-time at Oculus VR, where he served as CTO and later Consulting CTO in 2019.BiographyEarly lifeCarmack was born in Shawnee Mission, Kansas, the son of local television news reporter Stan Carmack.

The fisherman's knot is a bend (a knot for joining two lines) with a symmetrical structure consisting of two overhand knots, each tied around the standing part of the other. Other names for the fisherman's knot include: angler's knot, English knot, halibut knot, waterman's knot.Though the fisherman's knot is associated with fishing, it can slip when tied in nylon monofilament and other slippery lines; however, if more holding strength is required, the overhand knots can be made with more turns, as in the double fisherman's knot, and so on.

Year 1103 ( MCIII ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending Tuesday ( August 3, 1876 ) from the date of its first use by English settlers in the British Isles at present. The BCI is the largest recorded BCI ever constructed, encompassing around 595 square kilometers (or approximately 2.2 miles) in area.It was designated the BCI National Park by UNESCO in 1988 as being one of the most important parks in the British Isles. It is part of the United Nations World Heritage site for biodiversity, conservation, and cultural heritage.

The Battle of the Chesapeake, also known as the Battle of the Virginia Capes or simply the Battle of the Capes, was a crucial naval battle in the American Revolutionary War that took place near the mouth of the Chesapeake Bay on 5 September 1781. The combatants were a British fleet led by Rear Admiral Sir Thomas Graves and a French fleet led by Rear Admiral François Joseph Paul, the Comte de Grasse. The battle was strategically decisive, in that it prevented the Royal Navy from reinforcing or evacuating the besieged forces of Lieutenant General Lord Cornwallis at Yorktown, Virginia.

Michael I ( ; 25 October 1921 – 5 December 2017) was the last King of Romania, reigning from 20 July 1927 to 8 June 1930 and again from 6 September 1940 until his forced abdication on 30 December 1947.Shortly after Michael's birth, his father, Crown Prince Carol of Romania, had become involved in a controversial relationship with Magda Lupescu. In 1925, Carol was pressured to renounce his rights to the throne and moved to Paris in exile with Lupescu. In 1927, Michael ascended the throne, following the death of his grandfather King Ferdinand I.

The Soma cube is a solid dissection puzzle invented by Danish polymath Piet Hein in 1933 during a lecture on quantum mechanics conducted by Werner Heisenberg. Its name is alleged to be derived from the fictitious drug soma consumed as a pastime by the establishment in Aldous Huxley's dystopic novel Brave New World.Seven pieces made out of unit cubes must be assembled into a 3×3×3 cube. The pieces can also be used to make a variety of other 3D shapes.The pieces of the Soma cube consist of all possible combinations of three or four unit cubes, joined at their faces, such that at least one inside corner is formed.

Offa 's Dyke is a large linear earthwork that roughly follows the border between England and Wales . The structure is constructed mainly of wood, which means it has been cut from different types of wood and reinforced with various kinds of protective material. It forms an intricate mosaic pattern by creating concentric circles around a single rectangular area. Dyke was a Norwegian folk medicine practitioner who was one of the first Swedish doctors to learn to treat tuberculosis (TB). He started working in London in 1869, after being sent there by his parents.

Catalase is a common enzyme found in nearly all living organisms exposed to oxygen (such as bacteria, plants, and animals) which catalyzes the decomposition of hydrogen peroxide to water and oxygen. It is a very important enzyme in protecting the cell from oxidative damage by reactive oxygen species (ROS). Catalase has one of the highest turnover numbers of all enzymes; one catalase molecule can convert millions of hydrogen peroxide molecules to water and oxygen each second.Catalase is a tetramer of four polypeptide chains, each over 500 amino acids long. It contains four iron-containing heme groups that allow the enzyme to react with hydrogen peroxide.

Akasha or Akash ( Sanskrit ) means space or sky or æther in traditional Indian cosmology , depending on the language of the country. The ancient Hindu god Sravagatamaka (also called Tathagata, Sutra or Sutta), who was the ancestor of all known Hindus, had been killed in an earthquake during the fourth century BCE. He lived for a period in the fifth century CE. After his death he went to his shrine in Narshekya, where he offered sacrifices to gods, which he accepted. He is also known as Jain, "the king".

Concurrent Versions System ( CVS , also known as the Concurrent Versioning System ) is a revision control system originally developed by the University of California at Los Angeles during the early 1980s, with the goal of ensuring compatibility with Unix. It consists of five main components: one operating system, a client software development environment, a server and client-side networking layer, a virtual machine and an interactive scripting language. The CVS protocol is a key part of the UNIX standard, which was first introduced in 1979; later, it became standardized by the UNIX Programming Language Committee (PCML), and subsequently adopted by all other standards bodies.

Hebron ( ;  ) is a Palestinian city in the southern West Bank,  south of Jerusalem. Nestled in the Judaean Mountains, it lies  above sea level. The largest city in the West Bank, and the second largest in the Palestinian territories after Gaza, it has a population of over 215,000 Palestinians (2016), and seven hundred Jewish settlers concentrated on the outskirts of the Old City of Hebron. It includes the Cave of the Patriarchs, which Judeo-Christian and Islamic traditions all designate as the burial site of three key patriarchal/matriarchal couples.

Aden ( ,  ;   Yemeni: ) is a city, and since 2015, the temporary capital of Yemen, near the eastern approach to the Red Sea (the Gulf of Aden), some  east of the strait Bab-el-Mandeb. Its population is approximately 800,000 people. Aden's natural harbour lies in the crater of a dormant volcano, which now forms a peninsula joined to the mainland by a low isthmus. This harbour, Front Bay, was first used by the ancient Kingdom of Awsan between the 7th to 5th centuries BC. The modern harbour is on the other side of the peninsula.

Bi-curious is a term for a person, usually someone who is a heterosexual, who is curious or open about engaging in sexual activity with a person whose sex differs from that of their usual sexual partners. The term is sometimes used to describe a broad continuum of sexual orientation between heterosexuality and bisexuality. Such continuums include mostly-heterosexual or mostly-homosexual, but these can be self-identified without identifying as bisexual. The terms heteroflexible and homoflexible are mainly applied to bi-curious people, though some authors distinguish heteroflexibility and homoflexibility as lacking the "wish to experiment with sexuality" implied by the bi-curious label.

The unexpected hanging paradox or surprise test paradox is a paradox about a person's expectations about the timing of a future event which they are told will occur at an unexpected time. The paradox is variously applied to a prisoner's hanging, or a surprise school test. It was first introduced to the public in Martin Gardner's March 1963 Mathematical Games column in Scientific American magazine.There is no consensus on its precise nature and consequently a canonical resolution has not been agreed on. Logical analyses focus on "truth values", for example by identifying it as paradox of self-reference.

A nuclear thermal rocket ( NTR ) is a type of thermal rocket where the heat from a nuclear reaction heats and cools a propellant unit for a range of temperatures up to 5 degrees. It is particularly useful for space launches; as such it has been used primarily to power the Apollo missions. I don't know if this is in fact related, or if it was an accident. There are some things about these rockets that I cannot say for certain. It's probably not rocket technology as such, though, so I should be cautious.

Ravenna ( , , also ; ) is the capital city of the Province of Ravenna , in the Emilia-Romagna region. The provincial capital is at the head of several administrative districts, and lies in a part of the peninsula called Mare Nostrum . It is considered one of the most beautiful and scenic parts of the province, situated in a richly landscaped countryside surrounded by the surrounding mountains, valleys, and hills. There are numerous historic cities along the coast, which are known as L'Aquila , Monte Carlo , La Salle , Rome , and Pescara .

Note: This compilation includes only those attacks that resulted in casualties. Attacks which did not kill or wound are not included.TimelineJanuary (death toll: 21)4 January: An Israeli army undercover unit kills a Hamas member in the village of Tal and arrests two others.9 January: Two Hamas militants wearing Palestinian police uniforms attack an IDF post near the Gaza Strip with grenades and assault rifles. Four Israeli soldiers and one of the attackers are killed.10 January-11: The Israeli army demolished 59 houses and damaged another 200 in Rafah refugee camp. Over six hundred Palestinians are made homeless.

The year 2000 in Israel and Palestine marked the beginning of the al-Aqsa Intifada leading to a number of Palestinian states' separation from Israel, following an uprising. The Palestinian Authority (PA) formed the new government on 12 October 2001 after being dissolved in February 2008, and the PA was established in January 2010 by its own cabinet. It took office in March 2012. Israelis living outside the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip are defined by their country's constitution as "people who seek to maintain or restore the State of Israel".

In Euclidean geometry , an affine transformation , or an affinity ( from the Latin , affinis , `` connected to a point of the body in a semicircular area), is often defined as follows. The number of axioms may also be divided into two categories. In the previous section I discussed the definition of a single axiom, e.g., ∘3(∀4) is 2∄2 , and 𝒕(x,y) is 4∄3 . In this paper we will explore both the distinction between the difference in the number of axioms among groups and their generalizations.

The MGM-31A Pershing was the missile used in the Pershing 1 and Pershing 1a field artillery missile systems . It was originally designed for use against Japan. It was developed by U.S. Army Ordnance Co., a division of Boeing Company based in Kansas City, Kansas. Its main payload was a guided-missile system capable of carrying 12 tons of ordnance, ranging in weight from 2,000 pounds to 500 pounds. In 1944, the missiles were dropped on Japanese cities including Tokyo, Nagasaki, and Hiroshima, before being placed into reserve inventory.During World War Two, U.S. forces continued to use the Pershing-class destroyers.

Monte Cassino (today usually spelled Montecassino) is a rocky hill about  southeast of Rome, in the Latin Valley, Italy,  west of Cassino and at an elevation of . Site of the Roman town of Casinum, it is widely known for its abbey, the first house of the Benedictine Order, having been established by Benedict of Nursia himself around 529. It was for the community of Monte Cassino that the Rule of Saint Benedict was composed.The first monastery on Monte Cassino was sacked by the invading Lombards around 570 and abandoned. Of the first monastery almost nothing is known.

Parasports are sports played by people with a disability , including physical and intellectual disabilities . Some parasports are forms of transport such as public transport or private aircraft. There is also the occasional use of paragliding, which involves taking up to two people on a boat and passing around the water until it reaches one person. These events typically involve multiple participants, many who have different needs than that of each individual participant. In some cases, both parties participate in the participation; others engage in the recreational activity while other members participate only for brief periods. Olympic Games are held in international venues in Asia.

The Northrop Grumman RQ-4 Global Hawk is a high-altitude , remotely-piloted surveillance aircraft . It was initially designed by Ryan McCarron as an air-to-air missile capable of reaching 100,000 ft. (60,000 m) or higher in a single day. The aircraft became available to the U.S., Japan, Russia, China, Israel and New Zealand in 1975, and to the United States in 1994.Today, the RQ-4 is considered one of the most advanced nuclear bombers on the planet after its successful flight in June 1980, and is often referred to simply as the world's longest aerial bomber.

Eastern Europe is the eastern region of Europe . There is no consistent definition of the precise area it covers and, therefore, some areas do not exist. In general, they are spread across the southern and northern coasts of Europe, but vary geographically from land to land or continent to continent. [9] A number of European provinces (such as the French Riviera, Dutch-speaking Rijksmuseum, etc.) include major urban centers such as Lorient, in northern France, Gare deux-le-Cote d'Ivoire, in the east of England, and Salisbury in North Wales.

In philosophy, systems theory, science, and art, emergence occurs when an entity is observed to have properties its parts do not have on their own, properties or behaviors which emerge only when the parts interact in a wider whole.Emergence plays a central role in theories of integrative levels and of complex systems. For instance, the phenomenon of life as studied in biology is an emergent property of chemistry, and many psychological phenomena are known to emerge from underlying neurobiological processes.In philosophy, theories that emphasize emergent properties have been called emergentism.In philosophyPhilosophers often understand emergence as a claim about the etiology of a system's properties.

Arabidopsis (rockcress) is a genus in the family Brassicaceae. They are small flowering plants related to cabbage and mustard. This genus is of great interest since it contains thale cress (Arabidopsis thaliana), one of the model organisms used for studying plant biology and the first plant to have its entire genome sequenced. Changes in thale cress are easily observed, making it a very useful model.StatusCurrently, the genus Arabidopsis has nine species and a further eight subspecies recognised. This delimitation is quite recent and is based on morphological and molecular phylogenies by O'Kane and Al-Shehbaz and others.Their findings confirm the species formerly included in Arabidopsis made it polyphyletic.

Warren Mitchell ( born Warren Misell ; 14 January 1926 – 14 November 2015 ) was a British actor . He achieved his acting career in films and television after starring as the Countess Elizabeth Norton on Broadway from 1982 to 2005. The film has also won three Academy Awards , six Golden Globe Awards , and five Tony Awards . Nashville, Tennessee (CNN) is an important part of the Democratic Party in Tennessee and the United States. It covers more than half the state, making it the second largest state in U.S. history after New Hampshire.

The Viking program consisted of a pair of identical American space probes , Viking 1 and Viking 2 , which launched from Cape Canaveral in March 1977 and flew for three years to explore the moon's north pole during the Viking orbit. As the spacecraft approached its closest approach point to the sun on January 7, 1979, they made contact with the outer Solar System Earth and formed a magnetic field around it as Viking 2 went down.The first phase of Viking 3 was conducted on October 27, 1980, at 22:01 GMT. The mission was cancelled due to an emergency.

The European Organization for Nuclear Research , known as CERN (; ; derived from the name ), is a European research organization that operates the largest particle physics laboratory in the world. Established in 1954, the organization is based in a northwest suburb of Geneva on the Franco–Swiss border and has 23 member states. Israel is the only non-European country granted full membership. CERN is an official United Nations Observer.The acronym CERN is also used to refer to the laboratory, which in 2019 had 2,660 scientific, technical, and administrative staff members, and hosted about 12,400 users from institutions in more than 70 countries.

A mass driver or electromagnetic catapult is a proposed method of non-rocket spacelaunch which would use a linear motor to take off the Earth's crust and propel it back into orbit. It is an extremely difficult aerodynamic system and has been discussed as having advantages such as lower velocity (up to 25 kilometers per second), reduced cost (less than US$ 1,000 kg/year), higher thrust, and lower fuel economy. The concept was conceived by physicist Carl Sagan in the 1950s, and eventually became the cornerstone of NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory program, and is now the world's most commonly used version of the spacecraft design.

The oxidation state , or oxidation number , is the hypothetical charge of an atom if all of its bonds are bonded to one another. It occurs when the atoms have a total amount of oxidized carbon, such as in a hydrogen atom, because they need to exchange electrons on their way out of contact with each other . In a hydrogen atom, the oxidation number depends on the chemical structure of the bonds between the bonds and can range from 0–100. Korea (모보제, Korean: 문겐 탘), also known as Kim Il Sung-Jong, was a powerful former dictator, who ruled from 1949 to 1964.

A cigarette is a narrow cylinder containing burnable material , typically tobacco , that is rolled into thin paper for inhalation to the lips or throat. It emits no carbon dioxide, nitrous oxide, sulfur dioxide, or hydrogen peroxide and is considered safe for human use. Cigarette smoking is not a medical illness, but has been associated with psychiatric and behavioral problems such as psychosis, paranoia, alcohol dependence, and suicidal thoughts. For those living in urban areas, cigarettes are common. They may be purchased at vending machines, department stores, food service stores, retail outlets, supermarkets, and online.

The San Diego Zoo Safari Park , originally named the San Diego Wild Animal Park until 2010 , is an open-air zoo that houses over 500 species of animals from a diverse ecosystem. The park holds approximately 400 species of wild animals, many belonging to the wild African savanna in central Africa. Many are native to South and West Africa but may also be acquired locally as part of breeding programmes.San Diego zoological heritage is based on natural history dating back thousands of years . It is located in the Pacific Northwest and is one of the most scenic and popular landscapes in the United States.

Pope Leo IV (790 – 17 July 855) was the bishop of Rome and ruler of the Papal States from 10 April 847 to his death. He is remembered for repairing Roman churches that had been damaged during the Arab raid against Rome, and for building the Leonine Wall around Vatican Hill to protect the city. Pope Leo organized a league of Italian cities who fought and won the sea Battle of Ostia against the Saracens.Early careerA Roman by birth, Leo received his early education at Rome in the monastery of St. Martin, near St. Peter's.

The Bell UH-1 Iroquois ( nicknamed `` Huey '' ) is a utility military helicopter powered by a single turboshaft. The Bell Canadian is a large and highly maneuverable small-engined naval aircraft, commonly referred to as H-I-1s , that was originally developed as part of the United Kingdom Royal Air Force. Its name first became widely associated with Britain when the British Royal Air Force ordered a number of smaller vessels to join the air force in order to defend Canada from the US Pacific Fleet. With over 500 operational flights over the last seven years, many of these were cancelled during peacetime as well as due to low operational numbers.

Edward Teller (; January 15, 1908 – September 9, 2003) was a Hungarian-American theoretical physicist who is known colloquially as "the father of the hydrogen bomb" (see the Teller–Ulam design), although he did not care for the title, considering it to be in poor taste. Throughout his life, Teller was known both for his scientific ability and for his difficult interpersonal relations and volatile personality.Born in Hungary in 1908, Teller emigrated to the United States in the 1930s, one of the many so-called "Martians", a group of prominent Hungarian scientist émigrés.

Pope Leo VIII ( 915 – 1 March 965) was a Roman prelate who claimed the Holy See from 963 until 964 in opposition to John XII and Benedict V and again from 23 June 964 to his death. Today he is considered by the Catholic Church to have been an antipope during the first period and the legitimate pope during the second. An appointee of Holy Roman Emperor Otto I, Leo VIII's pontificate occurred after the period known as the Saeculum obscurum.Early lifeBorn in Rome in the region around the Clivus Argentarius, Leo came from an illustrious noble family.

A beta particle, also called beta ray or beta radiation (symbol β), is a high-energy, high-speed electron or positron emitted by the radioactive decay of an atomic nucleus during the process of beta decay. There are two forms of beta decay, β− decay and β+ decay, which produce electrons and positrons respectively.Beta particles with an energy of 0.5 MeV have a range of about one metre in air; the distance is dependent on the particle energy.Beta particles are a type of ionizing radiation and for radiation protection purposes are regarded as being more ionising than gamma rays, but less ionising than alpha particles.

Year 877 (DCCCLXXVII) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Summer – King Charles II ("the Bald") sets out for Italy, accompanied by his wife Richilde and a number of his chief vassals. He gives orders for an expedition, but Duke Boso (his brother-in-law) refuses to join the army. At the same time Carloman, son of Louis the German, has crossed the Alps into eastern Lombardy at the head of a Frankish army.

A seal is a device for making an impression in wax , clay , paper , or some other medium. It has been used for centuries by scientists, artists, sculptors, and musicians, but many modern uses for it have been limited. In general, words are nouns derived from the German verb meaning "to say". Although there is no formal definition for these terms, they are often used to describe things that occur in a certain context, such as poetry, literature, music, science, etc. (Wikipedia).

David is a masterpiece of Renaissance sculpture, created in marble between 1501 and 1504 by the Italian artist Michelangelo. David is a  marble statue of the Biblical figure David, a favoured subject in the art of Florence.David was originally commissioned as one of a series of statues of prophets to be positioned along the roofline of the east end of Florence Cathedral, but was instead placed in a public square, outside the Palazzo Vecchio, the seat of civic government in Florence, in the Piazza della Signoria, where it was unveiled on 8 September 1504.

Casimir Jagiellon ( ; ; ; 3 October 1458 – 4 March 1484 ) was a prince of the Kingdom of Bohemia, known for his religious beliefs; he became the most powerful monarch of the kingdom at the hands of the Habsburgs, leading them to defeat the kings of Hungary, Austria and Germany in the battle of Bademeyere . He is commonly regarded by many scholars as the father of Modern Christianity, which was the first modern church. However, this view has often been questioned by its adherents, especially after the second world war.

Dresden ( , ; Upper Saxon : Dräsdn ; ) is the capital city of the German state of Saxony. It is also situated in a district bounded on the north by Duesseldorf and Südertemberg counties, and the south by the town of Königsberg; and is well known for its excellent railway system. It is located on the border with Poland and the Polish-Croatian border. Hamburgers is an Austrian country consisting of two distinct states – Austria and Holland. Hamburgers has a population of about 3.5 million (Austria has 1.85 million), which is roughly equivalent to the number of European countries that compose Germany.

Year 968 ( CMLXVIII ) was a leap year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) from the time of the initial publication date. It was followed by one of the major scientific periods, the Age of Discovery ( AED ), which began at the beginning of the eighteenth century in England and lasted until 1887. The Golden Circle is a collection of classical Greek and Roman religious episcopacies founded by Constantine the Great. Their origins are closely linked with Dionysius of Aquitania, an older brother of Epaminondas, founder of the Roman Church.

Akasha or Akash (Sanskrit  ) means space or sky or æther in traditional Indian cosmology, depending on the religion. The term has also been adopted in Western occultism and spiritualism in the late 19th century. In many modern Indo-Aryan languages and Dravidian languages the corresponding word (often rendered Akash) retains a generic meaning of "sky".Religious backgroundThe word in Sanskrit is derived from a root kāś meaning "to be". It appears as a masculine noun in Vedic Sanskrit with a generic meaning of "open space, vacuity".

The Stone Roses were an English rock band formed in Manchester in 1983 . One of the pioneering groups of their era, Led Zeppelin had been a major influence on many bands from the late 1980's to today. Led Zeppelin has also played a significant role in many musical styles; it is considered one of the greatest rock bands of the 20th Century. Year 873 ( DCCCLXXIII ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) with an average length of 11.59 days. The name comes from the Greek name πλαυρικάπος, which is pronounced as Ὃ Θεβονή. It is the second-richest year in history after the Great Pyramid of Giza and is the most widely known year. The Earth System is a large, circular planet with a total area of 4,741 million km² (1,839 million square miles), composed of a number of satellites. Its surface features are elliptical and elliptical, each one pointing at a different sun, moon, and stars.

Powaqqatsi (or Powaqqatsi: Life in Transformation) is a 1988 American non-narrative film directed by Godfrey Reggio and the sequel to Reggio's experimental 1982 film, Koyaanisqatsi. It is the second film in the Qatsi trilogy.Powaqqatsi is a Hopi neologism coined by Reggio meaning "parasitic way of life" or "life in transition". While Koyaanisqatsi focused on modern life in industrial countries, Powaqqatsi, which similarly has no dialogue, focuses more on the conflict in Third World countries between traditional ways of life and the new ways of life introduced with industrialization.

The IAI RQ-5 Hunter unmanned aerial vehicle (UAV) was originally intended to serve as the United States Army's Short Range UAV system for division and corps commanders. It took off and landed (using arresting gear) on runways. It used a gimbaled EO/IR sensor to relay its video in real time via a second airborne Hunter over a C-band line-of-sight data link. The RQ-5 is based on the Hunter UAV that was developed by Israel Aerospace Industries.Design and developmentSystem acquisition and training started in 1994 but production was cancelled in 1996 due to concerns over program mismanagement.

Ilona Staller ( born 26 November 1951 ) , widely known by her stage name Cicciolina ( `` little chubby woman ), was a Romanian artist from Bucharest, Romania who began her education at the age of 14. Staller has exhibited in different art exhibitions throughout the world and is best known for her highly successful work on the sculpture of Saint John the Evangelist . She received her BA in mathematics in 1995 from the prestigious School of Architecture in Florence, Italy, where she spent the remainder of her junior years.Her paintings were often displayed in museums and schools around the world.

The Standby High-Readiness Brigade (SHIRBRIG) was a Danish-led initiative associated with the United Nations that aimed to create a standby force ready for peacekeeping. It was formed largely as a result of the genocide in Rwanda and other atrocities. Its permanent headquarters were in Garderkasernen (Garder barracks), Høvelte 30 kilometres north of Copenhagen in Denmark. It was declared ready for operations on January 1, 2000, and deployed to the Horn of Africa in November 2000 to form the core of the UN Mission in Ethiopia and Eritrea (UNMEE) under the command of Royal Netherlands Marine Corps Major General Patrick Cammaert.

General Dynamics Electric Boat (GDEB) is a subsidiary of General Dynamics Corporation. It has been the primary builder of submarines for the United States Navy for more than 100 years. The company's main facilities are a shipyard in Groton, Connecticut, a hull-fabrication and outfitting facility in Quonset Point, Rhode Island, and a design and engineering facility in New London, Connecticut.HistoryThe company was founded in 1899 by Isaac Rice as the Electric Boat Company to build John Philip Holland's submersible ship designs, which were developed at Lewis Nixon's Crescent Shipyard in Elizabeth, New Jersey.

A seed is an embryonic plant enclosed in a protective outer covering . The formation of the seed is part of the natural history of plants. In other plants, seeds are broken up and fertilized with certain kinds of carbohydrates, which are absorbed into the body as energy. Seeds are typically found on plants or in animal tissues such as milkweed and erythritol during their initial germination. They can be harvested from various sources, including the flowering stage (flowering through ripening to maturity) and the fruit cycle (from ripe to late maturity).

Fermat 's principle , also known as the principle of least time , is the link between ray optics and optical illusion . Ray optics involve the ability to produce an image at a fixed wavelength, by applying light from a lens, in order to capture an image at a particular focal length, or at a distance, in order to obtain a certain degree of illumination.The principle of least time involves the ability to approximate the properties of an optical fibre, such as its colour and shape (or the size and shape of objects), with relatively short timescales (e.g., 1/120th of a second per pixel).

Columbia Business School ( CBS ) is the business school of Columbia University in the City of New York in New York City. As part of the university's National Institute of Educational Research (NIERS), Columbia Business School conducts research and development at universities throughout the United States and Europe, and works in partnership with colleges and universities around the world to deliver innovative academic solutions for students and their businesses.The College of Education (CEP) is the oldest institution of higher education in the country, with an enrollment of nearly 10,000.
