In this regard it is chemically quite distinct from cotton, which is mainly cellulose.CharacteristicsWool is produced by follicles which are small cells located in the skin. These follicles are located in the upper layer of the skin called the epidermis and push down into the second skin layer called the dermis as the wool fibers grow.

In the English language , the word nigger is an ethnic slur typically used against black people , especially African American men and women, who are perceived by many as a threat to the health of their communities or the lives of others . "The Black Lives Matter movement continues its mission of racial justice. Through education and action, we have built a culture of mutual respect, inclusion and equality between blacks and Whites. We are committed to building a diverse and inclusive society that seeks to empower, protect and promote individual freedom in all areas of life."

Ravenna ( , , also ; ) is the capital city of the Province of Ravenna, in the Emilia-Romagna region of Northern Italy. It was the capital city of the Western Roman Empire from 402 until the empire collapsed in 476. It then served as the capital of the Ostrogothic Kingdom until it was re-conquered in 540 by the Byzantine Empire. Afterwards, the city formed the centre of the Byzantine Exarchate of Ravenna until the last exarch was executed by the Lombards in 751.Although it is an inland city, Ravenna is connected to the Adriatic Sea by the Candiano Canal.

Risk is a strategy board game of diplomacy , conflict and conquest for two to six players . The standard rules consist of five hexagonal tables (each of which contains one hexagon), numbered 1-5, 6-12. Players take turns either holding or playing a hand of four tiles in the opposite direction.Each tile has a special power associated with it. They range from 3/4 to 7/8, which are used to indicate that an action must be taken. A single tile may represent more than one tile; for example, 2/4 of a tile can represent eight tiles.

Coxsackie A virus ( CAV ) is a cytolytic Coxsackievirus of the Picornaviridae family , an enterovirus ( a group consisting mostly of viruses ). Its origin is uncertain, and has never been documented in Australia. It is common throughout Australia and New South Wales . It infects almost every organism including mammals, primates, birds, rodents, bats, fish, reptiles, amphibians, reptiles, fungi, algae, invertebrates, and plants.CAV is also found in other species such as pterosphaeropoeic clonal cells and protozoan parasites. In general, it does not infect or kill all non-nesting hosts, and thus is relatively harmless.

Hebron ( ; ) is a Palestinian city in the southern West Bank , south of Jerusalem . Nestled in the Jordan River Delta, Hebron lies adjacent to Tel-Aviv ( ), a town on the northern end of the Jordan Valley known as Haifa.Israel is an occupying power in the Gaza Strip that has repeatedly violated international law, and has conducted offensive actions against Israel.The conflict began when Israel launched two rocket attacks on Israeli civilians and settlers near the settlement of Tulkarem during the Six-Day War, killing more than 100 Palestinians and injuring 1,500.

Year 897 (DCCCXCVII) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Spring – King Lambert II travels to Rome with his mother, Queen Ageltrude and brother Guy IV, Lombard duke of Spoleto, to meet Pope Stephen VI to receive reconfirmation of his imperial title. Guy is murdered on the Tiber by agents of Alberic I, a Frankish nobleman with political interests. He seizes Spoleto (possibly at the instigation of King Berengar I) and sets himself up as duke.

George Shipway ( 25 May 1908–1982 ) was a British author best known for his historical novels , but he died of cancer in 1982 at age 86. He spent four decades writing fiction, including a few series that appeared before his death and one that survived to be published by HarperCollins . In the early 1930s, he became an international literary luminary, championing literature beyond the scope of his time.He first became acquainted with Thomas Hobbes' ideas of moral law when he read the classic The Law of Moral Sentences . He wrote several additional works, including The Discourses of Sir Richard Carrier and The Discourse on Poverty (1893).

The Porsche 914 or VW-Porsche 914 is a mid-engined sports car designed , manufactured and marketed collaboratively by Volkswagen and its sister company, Audi (NYSE: AM). It was produced in 1968 and 1969, when the German automotive division was founded, with the first model sold in 1972. History
In early years, the Porsche family was formed in 1892 by Johann Porsche (1899-1966), who became the heir to the Porsche brand, following his father's death in 1902. The family owned an extensive public portfolio from 1909 to 1926.

Turandot ( , ; see below) is an opera in three acts by Giacomo Puccini, posthumously completed by Franco Alfano in 1926, and set to a libretto in Italian by Giuseppe Adami and Renato Simoni. Turandot best-known aria is "Nessun dorma", which became globally popular in the 1990s following Luciano Pavarotti's performance of it for the 1990 FIFA World Cup.Though Puccini first became interested in the subject matter when reading Friedrich Schiller's 1801 adaptation, he based his work more closely on the earlier play Turandot (1762) by Count Carlo Gozzi.

The United Nations Foundation is a charitable organization headquartered in Washington, DC, that supports the United Nations and its activities. It was established in 1998 with a $1 billion gift to the United Nations by philanthropist Ted Turner, who believed the UN was crucial for addressing the world's problems. Originally primarily a grantmaker, the UN Foundation has evolved into a strategic partner to the UN, mobilizing support to advance the Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs), and help the UN address issues such as climate change, global health, gender equality, human rights, data and technology, peace, and humanitarian responses.

A monopropellant rocket ( or `` monochemical rocket '' ) is a rocket that uses a single chemical as its main propellant, and the composition of the powder it contains. Rocket boosters are produced by burning an inert metal powder in a large liquid-fueled rocket engine called an oxidizer. In 1835, Charles Darwin wrote The Descent of Man (1841), a book on human evolution which he published with his wife Lucy Smith (1914). Darwin's vision of human evolution led to the development of various hypotheses about the history of the human race; some of those theories have been incorporated in the book.

Chrysippus of Soli (; , ;  ) was a Greek Stoic philosopher. He was a native of Soli, Cilicia, but moved to Athens as a young man, where he became a pupil of Cleanthes in the Stoic school. When Cleanthes died, around 230 BC, Chrysippus became the third head of the school. A prolific writer, Chrysippus expanded the fundamental doctrines of Zeno of Citium, the founder of the school, which earned him the title of Second Founder of Stoicism.Chrysippus excelled in logic, the theory of knowledge, ethics, and physics.

The overhand knot , also known as a knot and half knot , is one of the most fundamental knots in knotting. It is sometimes referred to as the Half-Hitch, but this name refers not only to its characteristics but to its use in both traditional knotting (i.e., two hands working simultaneously) and non-traditional knotting. A knot usually has a "half" or "quarter" part, depending on the strength of the knot and the tension in the joint between the hands. It can also be divided into three parts, which may be called semicolons or quaternions .

A musician is a person who composes, conducts, or performs music. According to the United States Employment Service, "musician" is a general term used to designate one who follows music as a profession. Musicians include songwriters who compose music as well as write lyrics for songs, conductors who direct a musical performance, or performers who perform for an audience. A music performer is generally either a singer who provides vocals or an instrumentalist who plays a musical instrument. Musicians may perform on their own or as part of a group, band or orchestra.

A musician is a person who composes , conducts , or performs music . According to the United States Employment Law Act, any person who performs music for hire shall be entitled to receive an award of unemployment compensation (EIR) in accordance with the applicable law and rules. There are several methods used to calculate the unemployment rate by calculating the unemployment rate. One of them is the Workforce Development Index; one of the two most popular ways to determine how quickly people are being employed, this measure has more than doubled in the past two decades.

The Australian Secret Intelligence Service ( ASIS ) is the foreign intelligence agency of Australia , tasked with the covert support of Australian and international intelligence services as well as counter-terrorism agencies such as the National Security Agency, the FBI and the UN Security Council. The term "Cabinet" comes from the Hebrew Bible; it is used in 1 Kings 11:5 to describe the council consisting of six members, appointed by God's elect. It is often used as a synonym for the office of President, which is defined in Genesis 3:13 as "the government of the elect".

Avignon ( , ; ; or , ; ) is the prefecture of the Vaucluse department in the Provence-Alpes-Côte d'Azur region, near Pompidou. It is part of the central region of the French mainland, which borders France and is bounded by the Gulf of Guadeloupe to the north, the Cote D'Azur to the east, the Fédéroïc to the south, and the Sartois to the north.The Vaucluse district dates to the 17th century and has long been regarded as Parisian's most important port for trade. It was the seat of royal power from 1604 until 1808, when the French king Louis XIV named it the "Valley of Versailles".

A jubilee is a particular anniversary of an event, usually denoting the 25th, 40th, 50th, 60th, and the 70th anniversary. Of biblical origin, the term is often now used to denote the celebrations associated with the reign of a monarch after a milestone number of years have passed.Religious usageThe Jubilee ( yovel) year (every 50th year) and the Sabbatical year (every seventh year) are Biblical commandments concerning ownership of land and slaves. The laws concerning the Sabbatical year are still observed by many religious Jews in the State of Israel, while the Jubilee has not been observed for many centuries.

Year 1107 ( MCVII ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) during the first half of the 13th century. It is based on the Roman Calendar and chronology. On July 11, 1523 Emperor Augustus ordered his troops to return to Rome to secure the fortifications built in order to take over Italy from Julius Caesar.The year was marked by intense military conflict with rival tribes. The emperor decided to abandon the war against the Piso Tribes, whom he feared would become one of the main powers in the country.

In combinatorics and in experimental design, a Latin square is an n × n array filled with n different symbols, each occurring exactly once in each row and exactly once in each column. An example of a 3×3 Latin square isThe name "Latin square" was inspired by mathematical papers by Leonhard Euler (1707–1783), who used Latin characters as symbols, but any set of symbols can be used: in the above example, the alphabetic sequence A, B, C can be replaced by the integer sequence 1, 2, 3.

Twyla Tharp ( ; born July 1 , 1941 ) is an American dancer , choreographer , and author who started out performing live on stage in her home town of Minneapolis, Minnesota. She became one of America's most well known entertainers in the late '90s, becoming an all-time classic. After starring in shows including "A Little Night's Dream", "Falling Out of My Mind", "The Bluebird" & "Dancing Across the Sea", she moved to New York where she taught at a prestigious liberal arts school before returning to Minneapolis in 1992.

A funeral home , funeral parlor or mortuary , is a business that provides burial and funeral services for the families of deceased soldiers and other personnel who died in service of the United States Armed Forces at the front line when they died.The term "bodies" was coined by Army Chief of Staff John Nicholson (February 17, 1945 – May 3, 2009) in an interview to Rolling Stone magazine: "If you wanted to make me feel good about what I'm doing with my life, it would be to say, 'Just give yourself a break.

Civil liberties are guarantees and freedoms that governments commit not to abridge , either by constitution , legislation , or any other means of government. These rights are protected by the United Nations Charter, which has been used to promote freedom in many countries across the globe. Although human rights have been recognized worldwide for decades, most international law still holds that their fundamental value is an individual right. The U.S. Constitution states, "It shall be the object of the government of the United States to preserve and protect all the rights and privileges of the United States."

Triskaidekaphobia ( , ; ) is fear or avoidance of the number . It is also a reason for the formation of phobias in schizophrenia and bipolar disorder. There is no known way to control its onset or symptoms, although it is thought to affect about 10%-25% of the population. It has been used as an alternative medicine for psychiatric disorders, anxiety, sleep disorders and other forms of psychosis. Fluoride is a natural compound with a high affinity for polysorbate amine (PCa), a monoamine oxidase inhibitor (MAOI).

A resistojet is a method of spacecraft propulsion (electric propulsion) that provides thrust by heating a, typically non-reactive, fluid. Heating is usually achieved by sending electricity through a resistor consisting of a hot incandescent filament, with the expanded gas expelled through a conventional nozzle.Resistojets have been flown in space since 1965 on board military Vela satellites. However, they only became used in commercial applications in 1980 with the launch of the first satellites in the INTELSAT-V program. Many GEO spacecraft, and all 95 Iridium, used Aerojet MR-501/MR-502 series resistojet engines.

Cotton is a soft, fluffy staple fiber that grows in a boll, or protective case, around the seeds of the cotton plants of the genus Gossypium in the mallow family Malvaceae. The fiber is almost pure cellulose, and can contain minor percentages of waxes, fats, pectins, and water. Under natural conditions, the cotton bolls will increase the dispersal of the seeds.The plant is a shrub native to tropical and subtropical regions around the world, including the Americas, Africa, Egypt and India. The greatest diversity of wild cotton species is found in Mexico, followed by Australia and Africa.

The Bussard ramjet is a theoretical method of spacecraft propulsion proposed in 1960 by the physicist Robert W. Bussard , whose work has attracted widespread public interest. It involves taking an external spacecraft and spinning it toward the sun from a position on the planet Earth, orbiting the sun, as well as returning the spacecraft to its normal orbit before re-entering it with its wheels. In order to maintain the orbital velocity of the engine, the rocket can move about 40 times more slowly than regular engines.Bussard's system was developed at the National Institute of Standards and Technology in Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory (NLL).

Pope Leo VIII ( 915 – 1 March 965 ) was a Roman prelate who claimed the Holy See from Pope Leo III (10 June 935 – 24 July 985). Following the death of Emperor Justinian II in 967, Leo became emperor and ruled as reigning pontiff until 6 August 980.He was born at Piacenza in Italy to an affluent family of monks. He married the widow of his brother, the Duke of Pozzo-Fiume.In his early years, he lived with his wife and two sons. At the age of eleven, he began his education at the Palatine Academy, where he taught himself English.

Wind tunnels are large tubes with air blowing through them which are used to replicate the interaction between air and an object flying through the air or moving along the ground. Researchers use wind tunnels to learn more about how an aircraft will fly. NASA uses wind tunnels to test scale models of aircraft and spacecraft. Some wind tunnels are large enough to contain full-size versions of vehicles. The wind tunnel moves air around an object, making it seem as if the object is flying.Most of the time, large powerful fans suck air through the tube.

Thomas Becket , also known as Saint Thomas of Canterbury , Thomas of London and later Thomas à Becket (1649-1712), was an influential early English medieval cleric. The son of a bishop of Winchester in England, he was widely believed to have become the most influential cleric in the West. His influence on the Catholic world is said to have come largely from his efforts to reconcile the Church of England with the Protestant tradition. He was succeeded by Charles II, king of Somerset, who became more moderate toward Catholicism in his approach to the problem of clergy reform.

A jubilee is a particular anniversary of an event , usually denoting the 25th , 40th , 50th , 60th, or 70th anniversary of the First World War, when Britain's military and diplomatic presence in the war ended. It has also been called the "Great Seal of Gibraltar". Early Medieval England (14-1512) was the seat of the first English colony on British soil, situated between the two kingdoms of Scotland, North and South. From the start of the 16th century it was considered part of northern England; however, its political and economic history is widely disputed.

Milan Kundera ( , ; born 1 April 1929 ) is a Czech writer who went into exile in France to study French literature. She is best known as the author of several works including "La Méthique et le Monde" (1988), and her most recent collection, L'Express de l'Hôtel-Ortega (1991–93). She was born in Toulouse on 14 March 1937 and moved to Paris after being introduced to French literature during university. After completing her studies, she returned to La Méthique in 1985 to write for herself. She is considered one of the greatest modern writers of the 20th century.

Patch collecting or badge collecting ( also , scutelliphily , from Latin scutellus meaning little shield , and Greek phileein for shield of shields), is a form of identification with a specific individual that dates back hundreds of years. The concept was first adopted as a general idea by scholars at the turn of the 11th century; however, it was later codified among many cultures throughout history.The notion of having an identification with one's personal identity has long been a popular tool in identification studies. Scholars have used such tools to help distinguish between individuals based on their race, class, ethnicity, and national origin.

Pope Leo X ( ; born Giovanni di Lorenzo de ' Medici , 11 December 14751 December 1521 ) was one of Rome's most prominent figures and philanthropists during the reign of Julius Caesar Augustus, and was an early advocate for Christianization. He gave his life in support of Christianization. The Catholic Church is a major power within the Roman Catholic Church: it forms the center of political, historical and social activity around the world. It is considered among the top ten-most influential powers in all of Latin America, and the third-largest religion in history after Christianity and Islam.

William Tyndale (; sometimes spelled Tynsdale, Tindall, Tindill, Tyndall;  – ) was an English biblical scholar and linguist who became a leading figure in the Protestant Reformation in the years leading up to his execution. He is well known as a translator of the Bible into English, and was influenced by the works of prominent Protestant Reformers such as Erasmus of Rotterdam and Martin Luther.Tyndale's translation of the Bible was used for subsequent English translations, including the Great Bible and the Bishops' Bible, authorized by the Church of England.

Dementia manifests as a set of related symptoms , which usually surface when the brain is damaged by injury or disease. Symptoms include fever, fatigue, agitation, muscle weakness, weakness, pain in extremities, headache, and loss of balance. Epilepsy is characterized by the inability to control excessive or prolonged use of certain drugs. Individuals with epilepsy can develop specific problems with their immune systems. Individuals with epilepsy are more likely to develop mood disorders such as delusions, paranoia, hallucinations, and psychosis, and less likely to be able to talk to adults.

Alain Marie Pascal Prost ( born 24 February 1955 ) is a French retired racing driver . A four-time Formula One champion and World Champion , Pascal has won 23 races, as well as 11 championships, including five WEC titles since 1996. He was the first Canadian Grand Prix driver not to win his third European Grand Prix. Pascal's career spanned eight years from 1968 until his retirement in 2003. He also raced professionally at the Paris-San Remo circuit between 1978 and 2002.During this time he won seven straight F1 championships, while only losing one to Martin Weizmann.

Thermonuclear fusion is the process of atoms combining or “fusing” together with huge amounts of heat. There are two forms of thermonuclear fusion: uncontrolled, in which the resulting energy is released in an uncontrolled manner, as it is in thermonuclear weapons ("hydrogen bombs") and in most stars; and controlled, where the fusion reactions take place in an environment allowing some or all of the energy released to be harnessed for constructive purposes.Temperature requirementsTemperature is a measure of the average kinetic energy of particles, so by heating the material it will gain energy.

Saxony-Anhalt ( ; ) is a state of Germany, bordering the states of Brandenburg, Saxony, Thuringia and Lower Saxony. It covers an area of and has a population of 2.19 million inhabitants, making it the 8th-largest state in Germany by area and the 11th-largest by population. Its capital is Magdeburg and its largest city is Halle (Saale).The state of Saxony-Anhalt was formed in July 1945 after World War II, when the Soviet army administration in Allied-occupied Germany formed it from the former Prussian Province of Saxony and the Free State of Anhalt.

Delhi (;  Dillī;  Dillī;  Dêhlī), officially the National Capital Territory (NCT) of Delhi, is a city and a union territory of India containing New Delhi, the capital of India. Straddling the Yamuna river, but primarily its western or right bank, Delhi shares borders with the state of Uttar Pradesh in the east and with the state of Haryana in the remaining directions. The NCT covers an area of . According to the 2011 census, Delhi's city proper population was over 11 million, while the NCT's population was about 16.8 million.

The National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration ( NOAA ) is an American scientific and regulatory agency within the United States. The agency coordinates the activities of federal and state agencies and serves in the national security, commerce, and environmental protection of the United States from terrorist threats. Titanic (    ) is a celestial body with a total length of 528 kilometres. It covers about 45% of the planet surface, with a radius of 30 to 39 km. The mass of the Taino system is approximately 2.5 times greater than the Earth's diameter at its equator.

The PDP-7 was a minicomputer produced by Digital Equipment Corporation as part of the PDP series . Introduced in 1964, the PDP-7 was widely deployed throughout the United States, Canada, and Germany. It was designed to be cheap and simple to use. The PDP is an intercontinental telephone system operated by a U.S. company called Bell America (BOA), under contract to Bell South America. It is a telecommunications network for the U.S. and Canada that operates over 4 million homes and provides voice, data, mobile, internet and telecommunication services on a single platform.

Juan Moreno y Herrera–Jiménez (born 30 July 1948), known as Jean Reno , is a French actor of Andalusian Spanish origin. He has worked in American, French, English, Japanese, Spanish and Italian movie productions; Reno appeared in films such as Crimson Rivers, Godzilla, The Da Vinci Code, Mission: Impossible, The Pink Panther, Ronin, Les Visiteurs, Wasabi, The Big Blue, Hector and the Search for Happiness and Léon: The Professional.Early lifeReno was born Juan Moreno y Herrera-Jiménez in Casablanca, Morocco. His parents were Spanish, natives of Sanlúcar de Barrameda and Jerez de la Frontera in Andalucia.

The RQ-3 DarkStar ( known as Tier III- or `` Tier three minus '' during development ) is an unmanned air vehicle developed under the NASA's Air Force Space Command for use by the U.S. military, with a range ranging from less than 800 feet (150 m) to 8,200 feet (6,600 m). It is the second unmanned air vehicle design in the program, and was first announced by President George W. Bush earlier this year. "I'm coming to Los Santos. I'm starting to want to stay where I'm at."

Rice is the seed of the grass species Oryza sativa ( Asian rice ) or less commonly Oryza glaberrima (Chinese Rice) in Australia and New Zealand, mainly cultivated as a delicacy for children aged 4–8 years. It is an essential food for children of all ages including children under two who have difficulty digesting it due to low nutritional status. Etymology [ edit ]
In ancient Greek poetry, the word was derived from the Indo-Germanic letter "e" (also ei) ("one"), literally "one", meaning "to be" (Greek: κάν ἡ τ ēμι χάραταν ἁ κυτιστος).

A solvent (from the Latin solvō, "loosen, untie, solve") is a substance that dissolves a solute, resulting in a solution. A solvent is usually a liquid but can also be a solid, a gas, or a supercritical fluid. Water is a solvent for polar molecules and the most common solvent used by living things; all the ions and proteins in a cell are dissolved in water within the cell.The quantity of solute that can dissolve in a specific volume of solvent varies with temperature. Major uses of solvents are in paints, paint removers, inks, dry cleaning.

Barbecue or barbeque ( informally BBQ in the UK and US , barbie in Australia and braai in South Africa ) is a form of barbecue. Dinner usually starts at around 2:00pm on the evening of the Feast of St Patrick, which is regarded as Saint Patrick's Day. There are also special occasions from 12th May to the 15th of December. Most restaurants have food options for dinner; although they do not open until after midday, it is generally recommended that people order by themselves and get their usual portions during the day.

North America 's first transcontinental railroad ( known originally as the `` Pacific Railroad '' and later as the ``Trapcoast Railroad ) was built during the period from 1879 to 1915. The train is currently operating in Europe, Canada, the Americas, and South America, and it has served for over 50 years. It has a total of 1,200 miles of track between Washington, D.C., San Francisco, Los Angeles, Santa Ana, and New Orleans.HistoryThe railroads of Mexico City were first established in 1872 by the Mexican king Juan Manuel Laredo II, who had previously been exiled to the Dominican Republic after his death.

Year 874 ( DCCCLXXIV ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on March 31, 1814. It was the eighth year of the Seven Years' War between France and Britain. The Battle of Bougainville was fought on February 30, 1814 in the East of France under the banner of the English Volunteer Army. There it was the most significant battle of the French Civil War but also the third major victory for the British army during the Napoleonic Wars.As part of the Thirty Years' War , France participated in several victories in the war's final stages.

Eastern Europe is the eastern region of Europe. There is no consistent definition of the precise area it covers, partly because the term has a wide range of geopolitical, geographical, ethnic, cultural, and socioeconomic connotations. Russia, located in Eastern Europe, is both the largest and most populous country of Europe, spanning roughly 40% of the continent's total landmass, with over 15% of its total population.According to the Center for Educational Technologies at Wheeling Jesuit University, there are "almost as many definitions of Eastern Europe as there are scholars of the region".

Plotinus (; , Plōtînos;  – 270 CE) was a philosopher in the Hellenistic tradition, born and raised in Roman Egypt. Plotinus is regarded by modern scholarship as the founder of Neoplatonism. His teacher was the self-taught philosopher Ammonius Saccas, who belonged to the Platonic tradition. Historians of the 19th century invented the term "Neoplatonism" and applied it to refer to Plotinus and his philosophy, which was vastly influential during Late Antiquity, the Middle Ages, and the Renaissance. Much of the biographical information about Plotinus comes from Porphyry's preface to his edition of Plotinus' most notable literary work, The Enneads.

Michael I ( ; 25 October 1921 – 5 December 2017 ) was the last King of Romania , reigning from 26 September 1923 to 11 January 1925. His son, Alexander II, was elected president in 1926 and became president in 1930. In 1936 he founded the National Committee on Civil Society . He had a successful civil rights campaign in the 1980s, which helped him to win re-election.Romania was formally annexed to the United States on 30 April 1963 as part of President Lyndon Johnson's "One Nation, Two Systems" deal. The Roman Empire  is the oldest surviving Roman Empire empire in the Mediterranean basin [1].

A luge is a small one- or two-person sled on which one sleds supine ( face up ) and feet-first are used to move about.Luge sleds can travel at high speeds with their weight attached to the sled.The term may have been invented as early as the 1800s in England. Luge sleds use four rows of sledging, which each seat weighs 4.4 kg. The seats are also provided with a removable roofing liner, which helps to keep the sled from toppling upon impact.Luge sleds consist of five individual sleds, each consisting of four individuals.

Auger electron spectroscopy (AES; pronounced  in French) is a common analytical technique used specifically in the study of surfaces and, more generally, in the area of materials science. It is a form of electron spectroscopy that relies on the Auger effect, based on the analysis of energetic electrons emitted from an excited atom after a series of internal relaxation events. The Auger effect was discovered independently by both Lise Meitner and Pierre Auger in the 1920s. Though the discovery was made by Meitner and initially reported in the journal Zeitschrift für Physik in 1922, Auger is credited with the discovery in most of the scientific community.

Hazardous waste is waste that has substantial or potential threats to public health or the environment.Characteristic hazardous wastes are materials that are known or tested to exhibit one or more of the following hazardous traits:IgnitabilityReactivityCorrosivityToxicityListed hazardous wastes are materials specifically listed by regulatory authorities as hazardous wastes which are from non-specific sources, specific sources, or discarded chemical products.Hazardous wastes may be found in different physical states such as gaseous, liquids, or solids. A hazardous waste is a special type of waste because it cannot be disposed of by common means like other by-products of our everyday lives.

François Marie Adrien Maurice Mitterrand (26 October 19168 January 1996) served as President of France from 1981 to 1995, the longest time in office in the history of France. As First Secretary of the Socialist Party, he was the first left-wing politician to assume the presidency under the Fifth Republic.Reflecting family influences, Mitterrand started political life on the Catholic nationalist right. He served under the Vichy Regime during its earlier years. Subsequently he joined the Resistance, moved to the left, and held ministerial office several times under the Fourth Republic. Mitterrand opposed Charles de Gaulle's establishment of the Fifth Republic.

Pas-de-Calais (, "strait of Calais"; ; also ) is a department in northern France named after the French designation of the Strait of Dover, which it borders. It has the most communes of all the departments of France, 890, and is the 8th most populous. The Calais Passage connects to the Port of Calais on the English Channel. Pas-de-Calais borders the departments of Nord and Somme and is connected to the English county of Kent via the Channel Tunnel.HistoryInhabited since prehistoric times, the Pas-de-Calais region was populated in turn by the Celtic Belgae, the Romans, the Germanic Franks and the Alemanni.

Indonesian  is the official language of Indonesia. It is a standardized variety of Malay, an Austronesian language that has been used as a lingua franca in the multilingual Indonesian archipelago for centuries. Indonesia is the fourth most populous nation in the world, with over 270 million inhabitants—of which the majority speak Indonesian, which makes it one of the more widely spoken languages in the world.Most Indonesians, aside from speaking the national language, are fluent in at least one of the more than 700 indigenous local languages; examples include Javanese and Sundanese, which are commonly used at home and within the local community.

Giovanni Pacini (17 February 17966 December 1867) was an Italian composer, best known for his operas. Pacini was born in Catania, Sicily, the son of the buffo Luigi Pacini, who was to appear in the premieres of many of Giovanni's operas. The family was of Tuscan origin, living in Catania when the composer was born.His first 25 or so operas were written when Gioachino Rossini dominated the Italian operatic stage. But Pacini's operas were "rather superficial", a fact which, later, he candidly admitted in his Memoirs.

KFC ( also known as Kentucky Fried Chicken ) is an American fast food restaurant chain headquartered in Louisville , Kentucky. The chain was founded in 1963 with a small group of franchisee, and has been closed since 2012 due to bankruptcy proceedings. Since its launch on September 11th, 2013 the chain has sold 10 million meals around the globe.In 2017, the number of franchisees increased by 3.9%, from 1.6 billion to 6.2 million. Fluoroacetyl chloride (FAC) is an organic compound composed of hexavalent octanoate glycerol and polyamino-ethylene glycol ether.

Psilocybin  is a naturally occurring psychedelic prodrug compound produced by more than 200 species of fungi. The most potent are members of the genus Psilocybe, such as P. azurescens, P. semilanceata, and P. cyanescens, but psilocybin has also been isolated from about a dozen other genera. Psilocybin is itself biologically inactive but is quickly converted by the body to psilocin, which has mind-altering effects similar, in some aspects, to those of LSD, mescaline, and DMT. In general, the effects include euphoria, visual and mental hallucinations, changes in perception, a distorted sense of time, and perceived spiritual experiences.

The Maunder Minimum, also known as the "prolonged sunspot minimum", was a period around 1645 to 1715 during which sunspots became exceedingly rare. During a 28-year period (1672–1699) within the minimum, observations revealed fewer than 50 sunspots. This contrasts with the typical 40,000–50,000 sunspots seen in modern times over a similar timespan.The minimum was described by solar astronomers Edward Walter Maunder (1851–1928), and his wife Annie Russell Maunder (1868–1947), who studied how sunspot latitudes changed with time. Two papers were published in Edward Maunder's name in 1890 and 1894, and he cited earlier papers written by Gustav Spörer.

Svante August Arrhenius ( , ; 19 February 1859 – 2 October 1927) was a Swedish scientist. Originally a physicist, but often referred to as a chemist, Arrhenius was one of the founders of the science of physical chemistry. He received the Nobel Prize for Chemistry in 1903, becoming the first Swedish Nobel laureate. In 1905, he became director of the Nobel Institute, where he remained until his death.Arrhenius was the first to use principles of physical chemistry to estimate the extent to which increases in atmospheric carbon dioxide are responsible for the Earth's increasing surface temperature.

Palm OS (also known as Garnet OS) is a discontinued mobile operating system initially developed by Palm, Inc., for personal digital assistants (PDAs) in 1996. Palm OS was designed for ease of use with a touchscreen-based graphical user interface. It is provided with a suite of basic applications for personal information management. Later versions of the OS have been extended to support smartphones. Several other licensees have manufactured devices powered by Palm OS.Following Palm's purchase of the Palm trademark, the currently licensed version from ACCESS was renamed Garnet OS.

Bristol  is a city, ceremonial county and unitary authority in England. Situated on the River Avon, it is bordered by the ceremonial counties of Gloucestershire, to the north; and Somerset, to the south. Bristol is the most populous city in South West England.The wider Bristol Built-up Area is the eleventh most populous urban area in the United Kingdom.Iron Age hill forts and Roman villas were built near the confluence of the rivers Frome and Avon, and around the beginning of the 11th century, the settlement was known as Brycgstow (Old English "the place at the bridge").

Mercury (;  ) is a major god in Roman religion and mythology, being one of the 12 Dii Consentes within the ancient Roman pantheon. He is the god of financial gain, commerce, eloquence, messages, communication (including divination), travelers, boundaries, luck, trickery, and thieves; he also serves as the guide of souls to the underworld.In Roman mythology, he was considered to be either the son of Maia, one of the seven daughters of the Titan Atlas, and Jupiter, or of Caelus and Dies.

Los Alamos National Laboratory ( often shortened as Los Alamos and LANL ) is a United States Department of Energy (DOE) science laboratory located in Fort Worth, Texas. In 1965, the agency established an Office of Science to promote the scientific study of nuclear weapons and their potential effects.During the 1970s, research at LN developed into a joint effort between the Government of Texas and the National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency (GNISA ). The two agencies collaborated jointly during the Vietnam War.In 1974, the U.S. Congress passed the Atomic Energy Act—an act that increased the number of federal government scientists from six to ten.

Strasbourg ( , , ; ; , ) is the prefecture and largest city of the Grand Est region of North-West France. Its borders with Portugal, Switzerland, and Denmark are bounded on each side by Burgundy, Antwerp, Tromsø and St. Helena. Etymology‎ [ edit ]

Dorset ( ; archaically : Dorsetshire ) is a county in South West England on the English Channel coast . In the past few centuries it had been part of Great Britain for almost 100 years, before the arrival of Northern Ireland from the Isle of Arran in the First World War.It is situated along the coastline of Bristol Bay and south-west towards the north with an average width of 7.5km. It is one of the oldest counties in England and is among the last counties to be ruled by William II. It also includes parts of Kent, Hampshire, Northumberland and Humberland counties, where it is home to several large cities.

The bowline ( or ) is an ancient and simple knot used to form a fixed loop at the end of a long string. Its main purpose is to keep the string in line with the rest of the length, ensuring that it does not stray too far through a hole in the string when it strikes the bottom. It was originally created as a way of creating circular-shaped strings, called "struts", but it has recently been adopted by other types of knots because they allow the string to travel through space without being seen or touched by the body of the knot itself.

The Jagiellonian University ( Polish : Uniwersytet Jagielloński ( UJ ) ) is a public research university in Kraków , Poland. It was founded in 1912 and became a member of the European Union in 1975. It has produced over 600 scientific papers on biological organisms. Honeybees (Apis mellifera) are terrestrial pollinators which are native to the northern United States and Canada, and are commonly found along the shores of the Rocky Mountain range across the western United States. They are considered an integral part of the population of southern Mexico due to its abundance of native bees that provide important pollination for large species of insects.

A think tank , or policy institute , is a research institute that performs research and advocacy concerning topics such as global health, environmental policy, and other issues related to international law.In addition to conducting studies and advising policy makers, institutes are often placed in advisory roles. These positions can include leading international policy-makers, public servants, political appointees, and members of the executive branch. The United Nations Educational, Scientific, and Cultural Organization (UNESCO) has an Advisory Committee on Policy Developments, chaired by the Secretary General, responsible for implementing various UN policy programs.

Astrid Anna Emilia Lindgren ( ; ; 14 November 1907 – 28 January 2002 ) was a Swedish writer of art and literature, and the daughter of Sweden's foremost literary figure. Her early works included The Children's Book of the Wilds, The Girl Who Never Came to Be and The Song of the Sea (1950–1954). Her work is best known for its provocative poems and prose; it has been considered one of the most popular works of Western literature ever printed.Emilia started her writing career as an artist and illustrator during the period of World War II.

Pioneer 10 (originally designated Pioneer F) is an American space probe, launched in 1972 and weighing , that completed the first mission to the planet Jupiter. Thereafter, Pioneer 10 became the first of five artificial objects to achieve the escape velocity needed to leave the Solar System. This space exploration project was conducted by the NASA Ames Research Center in California. The space probe was manufactured by TRW Inc.Pioneer 10 was assembled around a hexagonal bus with a  diameter parabolic dish high-gain antenna, and the spacecraft was spin stabilized around the axis of the antenna.

A Select Library of the Nicene and Post-Nicene Fathers of the Christian Church , usually known as the Nicene and Episcopalian Fathers of the Catholic Church. The Orthodox Church has many branches, although some of them are more closely related to it than other churches. They are led by Saint Cyril of Alexandria, Patriarch Bartholomew IV of Antioch, Patriarch St. Mark of Nyssa, and Archbishops John Paul II (1440-1505), Peter II (1536-1606), Clement VIII (1626-1707), Gregory XII (1711-1703), and Nicholas III (1713-1719).

In celestial mechanics, escape velocity or escape speed is the minimum speed needed for a free, non-propelled object to escape from the gravitational influence of a primary body, thus reaching an infinite distance from it. It is typically stated as an ideal speed, ignoring atmospheric friction. Although the term "escape velocity" is common, it is more accurately described as a speed than a velocity because it is independent of direction; the escape speed increases with the mass of the primary body and decreases with the distance from the primary body.

Melissa Sue Anderson ( born September 26 , 1962 ) is an American-Canadian actress . She began her career as a young actress on The Cosby Show, and has since appeared in more than 50 shows, films and television programs, such as House of Cards, Family Guy, Star Wars: The Force Awakens, Mad Max: Fury Road, Star Wars: The Empire Strikes Back, The X-Files and the forthcoming sequel series. The character "Cannonball," also commonly referred to as "Chaser," was a comic book character portrayed by Peter Milligan in DC Comics from 1968 through 1976.

Script Creation Utility for Maniac Mansion ( SCUMM ) is a video game engine developed at Lucasfilm Games , later released under the Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International license, which means it has the same rights as . It was originally developed for PlayStation 3 and Microsoft platforms.The engine is capable of generating graphical effects that look identical to games such as Star Wars or X-Wing but can use different graphics hardware in combination with some minor adjustments.In SCUMM, the animation is composed of multiple layers of polyhedra and other components.Each layer has a special visual effect that creates three different views.

Halebidu ( IAST : Haḷēbīḍ , literally `` old capital , city , encampment '' or `` ruined city '' ) is one of the great cities in Ancient Egypt . The name reflects that it was located along the Tigris river and was founded in the time of Cyrus the Great, who led his expedition against the Canaanites.The ruins of the city, known as Ḥāsa  and Ḥūba  in the Phoenicians and Assyrians refer to the area in which Haḷatebīḍ remains today. They are a modern architectural marvel of ancient Egyptian construction, sculptural engineering, monumental sculpture, and architecture.There are several historical and contemporary archeological sites in the city of Haṣafar.

In electronics, a multiplexer (or mux; spelled sometimes as multiplexor), also known as a data selector, is a device that selects between several analog or digital input signals and forwards the selected input to a single output line. The selection is directed by a separate set of digital inputs known as select lines. A multiplexer of  inputs has  select lines, which are used to select which input line to send to the output.A multiplexer makes it possible for several input signals to share one device or resource, for example, one analog-to-digital converter or one communications transmission medium, instead of having one device per input signal.

As of July 6, 2017, there are 5.7 billion solar masses, roughly equal to the entire Earth's surface area. Tajiks (, Tājīk, Tājek; ) are a Persian-speaking Iranian ethnic group native to Central Asia, living primarily in Afghanistan, Tajikistan, and Uzbekistan. Tajiks are the largest ethnicity in Tajikistan, and the second-largest in Afghanistan and Uzbekistan. They speak varieties of Persian, a Western Iranian language. In Tajikistan, since the 1939 Soviet census, its small Pamiri and Yaghnobi ethnic groups are included as Tajiks. In China, the term is used to refer to its Pamiri ethnic groups, the Tajiks of Xinjiang, who speak the Eastern Iranian Pamiri languages.

While a significant majority of water vessels are powered by diesel engines, with sail power and gasoline engines also popular, boats powered by electricity have been used for over 120 years. Electric boats were very popular from the 1880s until the 1920s, when the internal combustion engine became dominant. Since the energy crises of the 1970s, interest in this quiet and potentially renewable marine energy source has been increasing steadily, especially as more efficient solar cells have become available, for the first time making possible motorboats with an infinite range like sailboats. The first practical solar boat was probably constructed in 1975 in England.

Rice is the seed of the grass species Oryza sativa (Asian rice) or less commonly Oryza glaberrima (African rice). The name wild rice is usually used for species of the genera Zizania and Porteresia, both wild and domesticated, although the term may also be used for primitive or uncultivated varieties of Oryza.As a cereal grain, domesticated rice is the most widely consumed staple food for over half of the world's human population, especially in Asia and Africa. It is the agricultural commodity with the third-highest worldwide production, after sugarcane and maize.

Kristiansund (, ; historically spelled Christianssund and earlier named Fosna) is a municipality on the western coast of Norway in the Nordmøre district of Møre og Romsdal county. The administrative center of the municipality is the town of Kristiansund (established in 1742), which is the major town for the whole Nordmøre region. Other notable settlements in the municipality include the villages of Kvalvåg, Rensvik, and Nedre Frei.The  municipality is the 333rd largest by area out of the 356 municipalities in Norway. Kristiansund is the 51st most populous municipality in Norway with a population of 24,179.

François Marie Adrien Maurice Mitterrand ( 26 October 19168 January 1996 ) served as President of France from 1981 to 1993. His wife Jeanette, daughter Anne and son François was among the leading members of the French Revolutionary Army during the Franco-Prussian War of 1870-1914. In 1894 he became the first foreign minister to be appointed by the French government; he was one of the first prime ministers to accept the invitation of Pope Pius XII. Monsieur de Trianon was born on 31 June 1844 in Paris and died at the age of 40 on 23 November 1891 in Paris.

The Collatz conjecture in mathematics asks whether repeating two simple arithmetic operations will eventually transform every positive integer into one that has exactly zero and the value of any other integer. Since it's impossible to define a function which takes the first non-zero bit, we can't prove its identity by adding more or removing the remainder. In his classic text on mathematical proofs, Thomas Schelling describes the notion of proof as "a method for determining how far an assertion can be regarded as certain." His definition is useful for proving beyond doubt that some statements are true, but not necessarily true itself.

Igor Fyodorovich Stravinsky  (6 April 1971) was a Russian composer, pianist and conductor, later of French (from 1934) and American (from 1945) citizenship. He is widely considered one of the most important and influential composers of the 20th century and a pivotal figure in modernist music.Stravinsky's compositional career was notable for its stylistic diversity. He first achieved international fame with three ballets commissioned by the impresario Sergei Diaghilev and first performed in Paris by Diaghilev's Ballets Russes: The Firebird (1910), Petrushka (1911), and The Rite of Spring (1913).

Aden ( , ; Yemeni : ) is a city , and since 2015 , the temporary capital of Yemen . In the past decade, it has been divided into seven districts with separate nationalities. Afghanistan ( س ای ه  ) is a country located within Afghanistan, in an area of Afghanistan that encompasses parts of Pakistan, Afghanistan's north, and North Turkestan Province and its southern reaches. It was one of the most densely populated states in the former Soviet Union, with approximately 3 million people residing in less than 1% of the territory.

The National Academies of Sciences, Engineering, and Medicine (also known as NASEM or the National Academies) is the collective scientific national academy of the United States. The name is used interchangeably in two senses: (1) as an umbrella term for its three quasi-independent honorific member organizations the National Academy of Sciences (NAS), the National Academy of Engineering (NAE), and the National Academy of Medicine (NAM); and (2) as the brand for studies and reports issued by the operating arm of the three academies, the National Research Council (NRC).

The language is widely spoken there as it is known for its rich dialect, though it has historically been found only in other Spanish speaking regions such as Catalonia and Alicante.Spain is Latin-speaking, with about 30 percent of its population in the north, while the remaining 6.7 percent are concentrated in eastern Europe and southern Scandinavia.

This is a list of monarchs who ruled over East Francia, and the Kingdom of Germany (Regnum Teutonicum), from the division of the Frankish Empire in 843 until the collapse of the German Empire in 1918.Note on titlesThe Kingdom of Germany started out as the eastern section of the Frankish kingdom, which was split by the Treaty of Verdun in 843. The rulers of the eastern area thus called themselves rex Francorum ("king of the Franks"), rex Francorum orientalium ("king of the East Franks"), and later just rex.

Rococo (, also ), less commonly Roccoco or Late Baroque, is an exceptionally ornamental and theatrical style of architecture, art and decoration which combines asymmetry, scrolling curves, gilding, white and pastel colors, sculpted molding, and trompe-l'œil frescoes to create surprise and the illusion of motion and drama. It is often described as the final expression of the Baroque movement.The Rococo style began in France in the 1730s as a reaction against the more formal and geometric Louis XIV style. It was known as the "style Rocaille", or "Rocaille style".

A melody (from Greek μελῳδία, melōidía, "singing, chanting"), also tune, voice or line, is a linear succession of musical tones that the listener perceives as a single entity. In its most literal sense, a melody is a combination of pitch and rhythm, while more figuratively, the term can include other musical elements such as tonal color. It is the foreground to the background accompaniment. A line or part need not be a foreground melody.Melodies often consist of one or more musical phrases or motifs, and are usually repeated throughout a composition in various forms.

The Porsche 914 or VW-Porsche 914 is a mid-engined sports car designed, manufactured and marketed collaboratively by Volkswagen and Porsche from 1969 until 1976. It was only available as a targa-topped two-seat roadster powered by either a flat-4 or flat-6 engine.HistoryPre-development By the late 1960s, both Volkswagen and Porsche were in need of new models; Porsche was looking for a replacement for their entry-level 912, and Volkswagen wanted a new range-topping sports coupé to replace the Volkswagen Type 34 Karmann Ghia coupé. At the time the majority of Volkswagen's development work was handled by Porsche as part of an agreement that dated back to Porsche's founding.

Paul Leo Molitor ( born August 22 , 1956 ) , nicknamed `` Molly '' and `` The Ignitor '', is the first author of a novel. His most memorable contribution was the final page in his popular book, which he edited to be published in 1968. Molitor has since been widely known as one of the greatest English novelists of the last two centuries.Molina also contributed an additional chapter to the third novel, written at the age of twelve, that won the Nobel Prize in Literature. He is the author of several literary bestsellers and hundreds of short stories, along with over thirty other novels.

The lion ( Panthera leo ) is a large cat of the genus Panthera native to Africa and India . It has a short snout, small claws, long nose, and beak that resembles a crescent-shaped pectoral crest.The lion is also sometimes mistaken for a carnivorous mammal, although its appearance varies significantly between different species. For instance, cats are usually described as having an extremely muscular body, but in fact may have much greater size than their closest relative, mammals such as deer and bears. In addition, lions also have distinctive vocalizations which help them to convey their mood and personality.

Radiohead are  an English rock band formed in Abingdon, Oxfordshire, in 1985. The band consists of Thom Yorke (vocals, guitar, piano, keyboards), brothers Jonny Greenwood (lead guitar, keyboards, other instruments) and Colin Greenwood (bass), Ed O'Brien (guitar, backing vocals) and Philip Selway (drums, percussion). They have worked with producer Nigel Godrich and cover artist Stanley Donwood since 1994. Radiohead's experimental approach is credited with advancing the sound of alternative rock.After signing to EMI in 1991, Radiohead released their debut single, "Creep", in 1992.

Montague Rhodes James  (1 August 1862 – 12 June 1936) was an English author, medievalist scholar and provost of King's College, Cambridge (1905–1918), and of Eton College (1918–1936). He was Vice-Chancellor of the University of Cambridge (1913–15).James's work as a medievalist and scholar is still highly regarded, but he is best remembered for his ghost stories, which some consider among the best in the genre. He redefined the ghost story for the new century by abandoning many of the formal Gothic clichés of his predecessors and using more realistic contemporary settings.

The Viking program consisted of a pair of identical American space probes, Viking 1 and Viking 2, which landed on Mars in 1976. Each spacecraft was composed of two main parts: an orbiter designed to photograph the surface of Mars from orbit, and a lander designed to study the planet from the surface. The orbiters also served as communication relays for the landers once they touched down.The Viking program grew from NASA's earlier, even more ambitious, Voyager Mars program, which was not related to the successful Voyager deep space probes of the late 1970s.

Bristol is a city , ceremonial county and unitary authority in England . A wide area network (WAN) is a telecommunications network that extends over a large geographic area. Wide area networks are often established with leased telecommunication circuits.Businesses, as well as schools and government entities, use wide area networks to relay data to staff, students, clients, buyers and suppliers from various locations around the world. In essence, this mode of telecommunication allows a business to effectively carry out its daily function regardless of location. The Internet may be considered a WAN.Design optionsThe textbook definition of a WAN is a computer network spanning regions, countries, or even the world.

Courtesan , in modern usage , is a euphemism for a `` kept '' mistress or prostitute , particularly one who has been paid at least as little as she was expected to pay, or who is considered the wife and mother of a child . The term originally referred to such women as the daughters of servants and maidservants rather than to the sons and daughters of men. An  liquor  is anything that contains two or more liquids (usually either water or gas). Most  alcohol  is made by extracting solids from distilled spirits and distilling them to produce a mixture of alcoholic beverages and liquor.

Lieutenant General Henry Shrapnel ( 3 June 1761 – 13 March 1842 ) was a British Army officer whose name is given to him as Lieutenant General Shrapnel, the son of Colonel George Shrapnel . His father served alongside him in both the German army and United Kingdom as a sergeant during the occupation of London. On 23 October 1942, he was placed under surveillance by the Gestapo during the evacuation of the city of Rastania from its Nazi-occupied Sudetenland district. The next day he was questioned about his links to the Gestapo and was sentenced to death.

A white cane is a device used by many people who are blind or visually impaired. A white cane primarily allows its user to scan their surroundings for obstacles or orientation marks, but is also helpful for onlookers in identifying the user as blind or visually impaired and taking appropriate care. The latter is the reason for the cane's white colour, which in many jurisdictions is mandatory.Variants Long cane: Designed primarily as a mobility tool used to detect objects in the path of a user. Cane length depends upon the height of a user, and traditionally extends from the floor to the user's sternum.

Edward Higgins White II ( November 14 , 1930 – January 27 , 1967 ) was an American aeronautical engineer who retired in 1946 from active service in the United States Navy. He was awarded a gold medal for his work during the Vietnam War. He served as U.S. Army Chief Engineer until 1965, then transferred his technical expertise to the Air Force in 1970.He died at his home in Arlington National Cemetery on December 8, 2001, at the age of 96 years. Year 870 ( DCCCLXX ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ended on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ). The first two years of the year, it was known as the "Dark Year". During that period there were many different types of light, which would appear in different colours. Dwarf Fortress (born March 6, 1577) was a city named for the warrior-tamer King Harold the Great, who had fought an important war with Germanic tribes during the First Crusade.

Arabidopsis ( rockcress ) is a genus in the family Brassicaceae . They are small flowering plants related to cabbage, lettuce, and other leafy perennial herbaceous species.Brassicaceae can grow up to six feet tall, with long, narrow leaves and many flowers on their stems. In winter they bloom in spring and autumn, but in summer they are typically replaced by cloverleaf.Insects of brassicaceae include both domestic and sub-fertilizer pollinators such as bees, butterflies, flies, and caterpillars. This section focuses on some of the more commonly found species of this group. It will also describe the most commonly seen and known genera of these species.

Year 1068 (MLXVIII) was a leap year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  January 1 – Empress Eudokia Makrembolitissa, wife of the late Emperor Constantine X, marries General Romanos Diogenes (a member of a prominent Cappadocian family) – who is proclaimed co-emperor as Romanos IV of the Byzantine Empire. Autumn – Romanos IV begins a campaign against the Seljuk Turks, leading a Byzantine expeditionary force (which is in poor condition). He is successful in recapturing the fortress city of Hieropolis (modern-day Manbij) near Aleppo in northern Syria.

Fermat's principle, also known as the principle of least time, is the link between ray optics and wave optics. In its original "strong" form, Fermat's principle states that the path taken by a ray between two given points is the path that can be traveled in the least time. In order to be true in all cases, this statement must be weakened by replacing the "least" time with a time that is "stationary" with respect to variations of the path — so that a deviation in the path causes, at most, a second-order change in the traversal time.

The pancreas is an organ of the digestive system and endocrine system of vertebrates . In humans , it is one of the five main structures of the body. It is responsible for a large number of functions that affect reproduction, including digestion, nutrition, reproductive processes, hormonal regulation, energy balance, and immune function. The pancreas is also responsible for the production of hormones such as insulin, which may cause changes in blood sugar and glucose levels during pregnancy or to increase hormone levels during menstruation. The pancreas is a part of the oocyte, where it releases secreted hormones from cells.

was the 69th emperor of Japan , according to the traditional order of succession.Go-Suzaku 's reign spanned the years from 1854–1946. He ruled for nearly nine hundred years and took office in 1907 as Emperor Hirohito of Japan.His legacy was a strong influence on how modern Japan views Japan, and is often compared to that of the Western world, where Japanese Buddhism is traditionally valued.During his time as Emperor, Emperor Hirohito introduced some of the best innovations in contemporary Japanese medicine, such as kōkata, which were regarded as one of the greatest contributions to the treatment of cancer and other diseases.

Menstruation ( also known as a period and many other colloquial terms ) is the regular discharge of blood and semen, usually accompanied by a mild to moderate pulse. It has been suggested that menstruating women have a relatively high risk of having an infection or infection-free menstrual cycle. In menopausal women, it is common to experience bleeding at night, often resulting from vaginal opening infections.There are several methods of diagnosis:1. The National Institute of Dental Diseases (NIHD) identifies patients with chronic pelvic pain who may be referred to the NIDDK for diagnostic evaluation. Anaheim is located approximately 30 kilometers west of Hamburg, Germany.

Courtesan, in modern usage, is a euphemism for a "kept" mistress or prostitute, particularly one with wealthy, powerful, or influential clients. The term historically referred to a courtier, a person who attended the court of a monarch or other powerful person.History In European feudal society, the court was the centre of government as well as the residence of the monarch, and social and political life were often completely mixed together. Prior to the Renaissance, courtesans served to convey information to visiting dignitaries, when servants could not be trusted. In Renaissance Europe, courtiers played an extremely important role in upper-class society.

Columbina (in Italian Colombina, meaning "little dove"; in French and English Colombine) is a stock character in the commedia dell'arte. She is Harlequin's mistress, a comic servant playing the tricky slave type, and wife of Pierrot. Rudlin and Crick use the Italian spelling Colombina in Commedia dell'arte: A Handbook for Troupes.HistoryThe role of the female servant was originally that of an entr'acte dancer. Women were not allowed to be part of the story that was being played out on stage, but they were allowed to have a dance in-between the action.

Montevideo  is the capital and largest city of Uruguay. According to the 2011 census, the city proper has a population of 1,319,108 (about one-third of the country's total population) in an area of . Montevideo is situated on the southern coast of the country, on the northeastern bank of the Río de la Plata.The city was established in 1724 by a Spanish soldier, Bruno Mauricio de Zabala, as a strategic move amidst the Spanish-Portuguese dispute over the platine region. It was also under brief British rule in 1807, but eventually the city was retaken by Spanish criollos.

Seville (; , ) is the capital and largest city of the Spanish autonomous community of Andalusia and the province of Seville. It is situated on the lower reaches of the River Guadalquivir, in the southwest of the Iberian Peninsula.Seville has a municipal population of about 690,000 , and a metropolitan population of about 1.5 million, making it the largest city in Andalusia, the fourth-largest city in Spain and the 26th most populous municipality in the European Union. Its old town, with an area of , contains three UNESCO World Heritage Sites: the Alcázar palace complex, the Cathedral and the General Archive of the Indies.

Albert the Magnanimous KG , elected King of the Romans as Albert II ( 10 August 139727 October 1439 ) and Pope John Paul II ( 11 February 1476 ), who died in a battle at Rome where he is thought to have been struck by a spear.His reign was also short, consisting of his first term as king, his second term as pope, and his most recent successor, Emperor Constantine IV (12 September 151389–16 February 1636). Anaesthesia is a medical disorder that is often mistaken for congenital malformations caused by other conditions (e.g., anemia, dyskinesia or epilepsy).

The Ante-Nicene Fathers, subtitled "The Writings of the Fathers Down to A.D. 325", is a collection of books in 10 volumes (one volume is indexes) containing English translations of the majority of Early Christian writings. The period covers the beginning of Christianity until the promulgation of the Nicene Creed at the First Council of Nicaea.PublicationThe series was originally published between 1867 and 1873 by the Presbyterian publishing house T. & T. Clark in Edinburgh under the title Ante-Nicene Christian Library (ANCL), as a response to the Oxford movement's Library of the Fathers which was perceived as too strongly identified with the Anglo-Catholic movement.

The PalmPilot Personal and PalmPilot Professional are the second generation of Palm PDA devices produced by Palm Inc ( then named Palm Mobile). The device was introduced in 1998 and has gained over 90 million downloads for its user base during its development and production. It was launched as the PalmPilot 2.1, a high-end low-power smartphone capable of running an 8-core Cortex-A57 processor, a 4-megapixel rear camera sensor, and 128GB of DDR3 memory. The PalmPad 2 also comes preloaded with 3D Touch to make use of this technology. The PalmPad Pro is based on the latest Palm's design and features built-in NFC and WiFi connectivity.

Robert Ross is an American blues singer , songwriter , acoustic and electric guitarist , slide guitarist , and harmonica player , among many others.Ross holds multiple international award nominations (in all genres) for Best Songwriter in a Contemporary Modern Music Series at the International Symphonic Awards from the International Grammy Association, the World Jazz Foundation, the Society of Blues Biennials and the Royal Society of Philolinguistics.Ross is the fourth most recognized American blues singer in the world after Elvis Costello and Buddy Holly.Ross was inducted into the American Guitar Hall of Fame on November 7, 1986. He received his B.A.

Henry Olusegun Adeola Samuel ( born 19 February 1963 ) , known professionally as Seal , is a British singer-songwriter, arranger, songwriter, producer, and composer who has released over 40 studio albums. The United Kingdom is a member country of the world's three largest music production systems: the Provinces of England, Ireland, Scotland and Northern Ireland. Since the mid-20th century, the UK has produced around 4,300,000 albums and was the home of more than a million musical events.The UK is ranked second among the major music markets in terms of album sales after Norway, behind only Finland and Canada.

Pali is a Middle Indo-Aryan liturgical language native to the Indian subcontinent . It is widely studied because it is considered to have been written after the Biblical period when its origin was first recorded. The Greek νυρις (θεσίας) literally means "beautiful." The word διαλογων (pronounced ʌəm), meaning "beautiful," or "beautiful," is derived from the Latin ἐντος (phosphorus). The Greek word for beautiful is often translated as "beautiful" in reference to ancient poetry, such as poetry of Dionysius Aquileia and Plato. In antiquity, pagan beliefs were based on fear.

Year 1103 (MCIII) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Levant  Spring – Bohemond I, Norman prince of Antioch, is released from Seljuk imprisonment at Niksar, after a ransom is paid of 100,000 gold pieces. During his absence, Tancred (Bohemond's nephew) attacks the Byzantines, and re-captures the cities of Tarsus, Adana and Mamistra in Cilicia. Tancred is deprived of his lordship by Bohemond's return, and is rewarded with a small fief within the Principality of Antioch.

Pope Leo VI (880 – 12 February 929) was the bishop of Rome and nominal ruler of the Papal States for just over seven months, from June 928 to his death. His pontificate occurred during the period known as the Saeculum obscurum.Family and early careerLeo VI was born into a Roman family, and his father was Christophorus, who had been primicerius under Pope John VIII around the year 876. Tradition has it that he was a member of the Sanguini family. Before his pontificate, Leo served as the cardinal-priest of Santa Susanna.PontificateLeo was elected pope around June 928, during a period of anarchy.

A Select Library of the Nicene and Post-Nicene Fathers of the Christian Church, usually known as the Nicene and Post-Nicene Fathers (NPNF), is a set of books containing translations of early Christian writings into English. It was published between 1886 and 1900. Unlike the Ante-Nicene Fathers which was produced by using earlier translations of the Ante-Nicene Christian Library (ANCL), the Nicene and Post-Nicene Fathers was printed simultaneously in Europe and in America, by T. & T. Clark, by Christian Literature Company and other American editors. The translations were in the main revised versions of those made for the Oxford Movement Library of the Fathers series.

Paclitaxel (PTX), sold under the brand name Taxol among others, is a chemotherapy medication used to treat a number of types of cancer. This includes ovarian cancer, esophageal cancer, breast cancer, lung cancer, Kaposi's sarcoma, cervical cancer, and pancreatic cancer. It is administered by intravenous injection. There is also an albumin-bound formulation.Common side effects include hair loss, bone marrow suppression, numbness, allergic reactions, muscle pains, and diarrhea. Other serious side effects include heart problems, increased risk of infection, and lung inflammation. There are concerns that use during pregnancy may cause birth defects.

Naval Submarine Base New London is the primary United States Navy East Coast submarine base , also known as the "sea fortress." It has approximately 8,400 square miles of sea area (about 10 times the country's entire population size), which is about 2,800 square miles in size. This includes a total of 23 operating submarines and more than 3,000 destroyers.There are a variety of naval facilities on each of its three subgroups, but most are located along the harbor shore, making it an easy landing place for American military troops or other vessels conducting operations offshore.

In celestial mechanics , escape velocity or escape speed is the minimum speed needed for a free , non-propelled object to be propelled. However, space travel is extremely unstable because its orbit does not change very quickly; the orbits of the most common stars have a radius between one and ten times larger than their orbital motion relative to the Sun. Galaxies in the human galaxy are made up of many tiny, massive particles called subatomic particles. These nuclei contain only a few billion elements (about 100,000 atoms) that interact with each other and are called the "superluminous".

A wide area network ( WAN ) is a telecommunications network that extends over a large geographic area . Wide-area networks are those used to transport telephones, computers, television, computers, etc. Wide-area networks typically serve many purposes, such as communication from remote places to other areas, as well as storage, distribution and access to information in order to deliver communications at high speeds. Broadband networks vary widely in their deployment, frequency, and type of services. High school students who attended a public high school have a higher probability of attending college or university than those who did not attend one.

Domenico Cimarosa ( ; 17 December 1749 – 11 January 1801 ) was an Italian composer of the Neapolitan school who became a key figure in the music of Renaissance art and classical music. His works include Violin, Concerto No. 3, Piano Concerto No. 4, Fugue No. 6, Clarinet Concerto No. 1, and Strings Concerto No. 7. Gustavo Berlioz (1824–1907), commonly known as the father of American jazz guitarists Paul Elam and Al Green, played bass and rhythm sections for most of their lives. Berlioz was well-known to his peers for his influence on the modern jazz movement.

The Novikov self-consistency principle , also known as the Novikov self-consistency conjecture and Larry Niven 's law of conservation of variance , holds that a pair of variables are consistent if it can be stated in terms of their states, without regard to the state they are in.This paper discusses the theory of Decimal Time, which has been described earlier in this paper. It is further discussed later in this post, where we review the properties of Decimal Time. Anomalies (also abbreviated to 𝒞𝒕) are non-normal objects with an odd probability of occurrence . Such objects have one or more random effects such as gravitational waves and other phenomena.

The Hoysala Empire was a Kannadiga power originating from the Indian subcontinent that ruled most of what is now Karnataka. In the late 17th Century, the Hoysala conquered the southern half of South India and consolidated control over the country's remaining territory in the region. Its influence spread throughout north India through the Punjab region and into Bengal.Hoysala rule extended westward for nearly two centuries. By the end of the 19th Century, its borders with West Bengal, East India, Maharashtra, Assam, Rajasthan and Tamil Nadu had been absorbed by the Empire and its resources used to establish a state of warring armies.

Classless Inter-Domain Routing (CIDR ) is a method for allocating IP addresses and for IP routing. The Internet Engineering Task Force introduced CIDR in 1993 to replace the previous classful network addressing architecture on the Internet. Its goal was to slow the growth of routing tables on routers across the Internet, and to help slow the rapid exhaustion of IPv4 addresses.IP addresses are described as consisting of two groups of bits in the address: the most significant bits are the network prefix, which identifies a whole network or subnet, and the least significant set forms the host identifier, which specifies a particular interface of a host on that network.

The M18A1 Claymore is a directional anti-personnel mine developed for the United States Armed Forces . Its inventor , Norman A. Hirschberg (born February 27, 1948), was an American engineering engineer with more than 25 years of engineering experience who served in the Army's Strategic Air Command. In early August 1914, Adolf Hitler and his Third Reich invaded Poland and occupied Poland under the command of General Ulf Wieckenkow. Following the surrender of World War I, the Allies made their way northwards from East Germany through Hungary and Czechoslovakia to the Rhine countryside.

Year 879 ( DCCCLXXIX ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Monday ( link will show the day of the week). The year was set at the end of the first millennium BC by the Sumerians.The period was divided into ten periods: the 12th, 16th, and 23rd centuries BC, until the last 1550 AD. There are over 1,400 known years in total from the beginning to the end of the third millennium BC. This is the most populous period of the Solar System.The astronomical system dates from the sixth to the 19th centuries BC.

An inverse multiplexer ( often abbreviated to inverse MUX or IMUX ) allows a data stream to be broken into smaller and larger segments, sometimes called "samples". In some implementations, the samples represent the entire length of a data file. Examples are stored as PNGs, GIFs, and TIFF files, such as those hosted on GitHub. It is currently unclear whether these formats were used by Apple in the 1980s or even when they were added in their current generation.A nonlinear linear regression is an estimation of the coefficient of variation between two sets of estimates.
