Heliox is a breathing gas mixture of helium (He) and oxygen (O2).Heliox is a medical treatment for patients with difficulty breathing. The mixture generates less resistance than atmospheric air when passing through the airways of the lungs, and thus requires less effort by a patient to breathe in and out of the lungs.Heliox has been used medically since the 1930s, and although the medical community adopted it initially to alleviate symptoms of upper airway obstruction, its range of medical uses has since expanded greatly, mostly because of the low density of the gas.

Naval Submarine Base New London is the primary United States Navy East Coast submarine base, also known as the "Home of the Submarine Force." It is located in Groton, Connecticut directly across the Thames River from its namesake city of New London.HistoryIn 1868, the State of Connecticut gave the Navy  of land along the Thames River in Groton to build a Naval Station. Due to a lack of federal funding, it was not until 1872 that two brick buildings and a T-shaped pier were constructed and officially declared a Navy Yard.

Commander Keen is a series of side-scrolling platform video games developed primarily by id Software . The series consists of eight games in varying levels of difficulty, based on the premise that players need to beat various obstacles, such as jumping and grappling. The series was initially marketed as a single-player game, but its development took more than six years. It was discontinued in 2009.In 1999, Lucasfilm announced the "Scooped Platformer" (later known as the Star Wars: Knights of the Old Republic series) as a digital download offering. A large asteroid field is a type of planetary body formed by a collision between stars and asteroids.

The Space Shuttle program was the fourth human spaceflight program carried out by the U.S. National Aeronautics and Space Administration during the Kennedy Space Flight Test and Development Program (KSAT) from 1966 to 1972. It involved the deployment of the first flight test spacecraft in 1957 as part of the Apollo lunar module program. Its launch followed NASA's "C" mission on July 5, 1962, when it flew six more landings and successfully completed its 20th trip to the Moon.The Space Shuttle was the first commercial vehicle to carry humans to the Moon using a robotic landing module.

A hybrid-propellant rocket is a rocket with a rocket motor that uses rocket propellants in two different phases: one solid and the other either gas or liquid. The hybrid rocket concept can be traced back to at least the 1930s.Hybrid rockets avoid some of the disadvantages of solid rockets like the dangers of propellant handling, while also avoiding some disadvantages of liquid rockets like their mechanical complexity. Because it is difficult for the fuel and oxidizer to be mixed intimately (being different states of matter), hybrid rockets tend to fail more benignly than liquids or solids.

Shakespearean tragedy is the designation given to most tragedies written by playwright William Shakespeare . Many of his history plays have been adapted for television, film, radio and the web. There are also numerous novels, including The Kingkiller Chronicle . The Great Famine of 1764–67 was the largest famine in modern history—from 1871 to 1918 it brought more than 3.5 million persons to an estimated 814,600 deaths. It killed some 2.2 million people, many of them from disease, illness, or famine. According to a 2005 report by the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC), nearly 1.3 million people died through malnutrition during that period.

Gregory of Nyssa, also known as Gregory Nyssen (; c. 335 – c. 395), was bishop of Nyssa, Cappadocia, from 372 to 376 and from 378 until his death. He is venerated as a saint in Roman Catholicism, Eastern Orthodoxy, Oriental Orthodoxy, Anglicanism, and Lutheranism. Gregory, his elder brother Basil of Caesarea, and their friend Gregory of Nazianzus are collectively known as the Cappadocian Fathers.Gregory lacked the administrative ability of his brother Basil or the contemporary influence of Gregory of Nazianzus, but he was an erudite theologian who made significant contributions to the doctrine of the Trinity and the Nicene Creed.

In mathematics, the Dirac delta distribution ( distribution), also known as the unit impulse symbol, is a generalized function or distribution over the real numbers, whose value is zero everywhere except at zero, and whose integral over the entire real line is equal to one.The current understanding of the impulse is as a linear functional that maps every continuous function to its value at zero, or as the weak limit of a sequence of bump functions, which are zero over most of the real line, with a tall spike at the origin.

Year 876 (DCCCLXXVI) was a leap year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  At the invitation of Benevento, the newly-restored Byzantine fleet appears in the waters off Otranto. On the orders of Emperor Basil I, the Byzantines sail up the Adriatic Sea and reconquer part of southern Italy. The city of Bari is occupied in the name of the Byzantine Empire. Instead of holding it for his 'ally' Adelchis of Benevento, Basil makes it the capital of the new Byzantine Theme of Longobardia.

"Wilhelmus van Nassouwe", usually known just as "Wilhelmus" (; ; English translation: "The William"), is the national anthem of both the Netherlands and the Kingdom of the Netherlands. It dates back to at least 1572, making it the oldest national anthem in use today, provided that the latter is defined as consisting of both a melody and lyrics. Although "Wilhelmus" was not recognized as the official national anthem until 1932, it has always been popular with parts of the Dutch population and resurfaced on several occasions in the course of Dutch history before gaining its present status.

In linguistics, an adjective (abbreviated ) is a word that modifies a noun or noun phrase or describes its referent. Its semantic role is to change information given by the noun.Traditionally, adjectives were considered one of the main parts of speech of the English language, although historically they were classed together with nouns. Nowadays, certain words that usually had been classified as adjectives, including the, this, my, etc., typically are classed separately, as determiners.Some examples: That's an interesting idea. (attributive) That idea is interesting. (predicative)  The good, the bad, and the ugly.

The Himalayas , or Himalaya ( ; Sanskrit : , `` snow '' , `` dwelling '' , `` abode '' ), is the sixth largest country in India and one of only six countries. It is the richest country in the world, with an estimated $1 trillion in GDP and $3.6 trillion in net foreign exchange investment. This article originally appeared on BBC News . The Great Pyramid is a giant pyramid constructed by Egyptian pyramids over a 3,200-year period during which it was visited by some of the greatest explorers of modern times.

Norman Quentin Cook (born Quentin Leo Cook; 31st July 1963), also known by his stage name Fatboy Slim, is an English musician, DJ and record producer who helped to popularise the big beat genre in the 1990s. In the 1980s, Cook was the bassist for the Hull-based indie rock band the Housemartins, who achieved a UK number-one single with their a cappella cover of "Caravan of Love". After the Housemartins split, Cook formed the electronic band Beats International in Brighton, who produced the number-one single "Dub Be Good to Me".

Porphyry ( ; , Porphyrios `` purple-clad '' ) may refer to : Porphyry ( geology ) , an igneous rock, from the southwestern subarctic of Antarctica. This region includes the Greenland Ice Sheet basin, and contains a vast expanse of deep sea water that covers most of southern Greenland. Its composition is mainly made of carbonate, silica, manganese, calcium carbonate, phosphorous, fluorine, magnesium, calcium sulfate, copper, and nickel, with low levels of carbonate as a result.It is dominated by iron and nickel, with relatively small amounts of nitrogen in the form of sulfur dioxide.

The Illustrated Man is a 1951 collection of 18 science fiction short stories by American writer Ray Bradbury. A recurring theme throughout the stories is the conflict of the cold mechanics of technology and the psychology of people. It was nominated for the International Fantasy Award in 1952.The unrelated stories are tied together by the frame story of "The Illustrated Man", a vagrant former member of a carnival freak show with an extensively tattooed body whom the unnamed narrator meets. The man's tattoos, allegedly created by a time-traveling woman, are individually animated, and each tells a different tale.

The Ante-Nicene Fathers , subtitled `` The Writings of the Fathers Down to A.D. 325 '' , is a collection of scholarly works published between the late Middle Ages and the present, comprising more than forty-six chapters. In addition to the work of Aristotle and Platonism, the manuscript was composed of approximately sixty-nine essays addressed to the most important persons on this earth, as well as to its subjects: Aristides, Plato, Aristotle, Aquinas, Hippocrates, Diodorus Siculus, St. Paul, Dionysius (c. 410–400 AD) and Ptolemy. Many of the essays were translated from Latin into Greek.

The Sikorsky UH-60 Black Hawk is a four-blade, twin-engine, medium-lift utility helicopter manufactured by Sikorsky Aircraft. Sikorsky submitted the S-70 design for the United States Army's Utility Tactical Transport Aircraft System (UTTAS) competition in 1972. The Army designated the prototype as the YUH-60A and selected the Black Hawk as the winner of the program in 1976, after a fly-off competition with the Boeing Vertol YUH-61.Named after the Native American war leader Black Hawk, the UH-60A entered service with the U.S. Army in 1979, to replace the Bell UH-1 Iroquois as the Army's tactical transport helicopter.

The Jagiellonian University (Polish: Uniwersytet Jagielloński (UJ)) is a public research university in Kraków, Poland. Founded in 1364 by King Casimir III the Great, it is the oldest university in Poland and the 13th oldest university in continuous operation in the world. It is often regarded as Poland's most prestigious academic institution. The university has been viewed as a guardian of Polish culture, particularly for continuing operations during the partitions of Poland and the two World Wars, as well as a significant contributor to the intellectual heritage of Europe.The campus of the Jagiellonian University is centrally located within the city of Kraków.

Thomas Becket , also known as Saint Thomas of Canterbury, Thomas of London and later Thomas à Becket (21 December 1119 or 1120 – 29 December 1170), was Archbishop of Canterbury from 1162 until his murder in 1170. He is venerated as a saint and martyr by the Catholic Church and the Anglican Communion. He engaged in conflict with Henry II, King of England, over the rights and privileges of the Church and was murdered by followers of the king in Canterbury Cathedral. Soon after his death, he was canonised by Pope Alexander III.SourcesThe main sources for the life of Becket are a number of biographies written by contemporaries.

Thetis ( ; ) , is a figure from Greek mythology with varying mythological roles . She mainly appears as the goddess Artemis, who has been venerated by mankind since her appearance in Aeschylus' Trojan Wars and also by humans. It is often considered to be an ancient goddess of the underworld, and she is one of the greatest deities of her time.Her mother Zeus was the wife of Hermes, father of Hermes's brother Dionysius, and godfather of his son Apollo. Athena is believed to be the mother-in-law of Mercury, Juno, Saturn, Jupiter, Mars, Venus and Neptune, and many other goddesses.

In quantum mechanics , counterfactual definiteness ( CFD ) is the ability to speak `` meaningfully '' of the definiteness of a mathematical problem, i.e., it is possible to say something like that for example "I don't know what X is." or "I can't think of an integer in a finite space because I can't represent it in an infinite dimension." For this reason, CFD values are used to define solutions for complex problems. Families of families are defined as pairs of two or more individuals living in the same household.

George Shipway (25 May 1908–1982) was a British author best known for his historical novels, but he also tried his hand at political satire in his book The Chilian Club.Military careerGeorge Frederick Morgan Shipway was born on 25 May 1908 at Allahbad in India and was educated at Clifton. He then attended the Royal Military College, Sandhurst and was commissioned on to the Unattached List for the Indian Army on 30 August 1928. He arrived in India on 5 October 1928 and was attached to a British regiment: the 2nd Battalion The Prince of Wales's Volunteers (South Lancashire), for one year from 14 October 1928.

Thermonuclear fusion is the process of atoms combining or “ fusing ” together with huge amounts of heat . There are two distinct approaches to such fusion. The simplest form is the use of hydrogen peroxide (HPA), an inert gas, which is produced by converting oxygen in a solution of water vapor into protons (particles) that fuse at a higher velocity; this technique can be used to accelerate the formation of nuclear fission reactions, though it has drawbacks. In the second method, where electrons are converted into hydrogen ions and stored in the nucleus for future fusion reactions, HPA is depleted and cannot be replaced.

Chrysippus of Soli ( ; , ; ) was a Greek Stoic philosopher . He was a native of Soli, and lived there for at least two thousand years, the same as Chrysippus, also known as ἀίναφῦομαι, δός τὸς ἀνίναφῦοματοι, Epaminondiae . He became acquainted with the philosophers Aristotelius and Pliny on account of his piety. In the second millennium BC, he was considered to be a hero by Herodotus in the Achaemenian legend, although he did not come to any great renown in the West until the reign of Marcus Aurelius (c. 325–322 BCE), which ended with his death.

In Euclidean geometry, an affine transformation, or an affinity (from the Latin, affinis, "connected with"), is a geometric transformation that preserves lines and parallelism (but not necessarily distances and angles).More generally, an affine transformation is an automorphism of an affine space (Euclidean spaces are specific affine spaces), that is, a function which maps an affine space onto itself while preserving both the dimension of any affine subspaces (meaning that it sends points to points, lines to lines, planes to planes, and so on) and the ratios of the lengths of parallel line segments.

The National Academies of Sciences , Engineering , and Medicine ( also known as NASEM or the National Academies ) are the world's leading universities and research academies. They are widely regarded as an important scientific and academic community with a broad range of teaching, research, administration, and curricula. The American Society for Biomedical Engineering defines them as "the nation's premier science and engineering professional institution". Lettuce is a genus of short-term legumes from India. Its leaves are usually dark brown or black in color; their leaves are edible and contain little to no fragrance.

Yorkshire pudding is a baked pudding made from a batter of eggs , flour , and milk or water . When boiled, it is cooled to around 180°C. In an oven with a lid, the mixture is covered with ice and refrigerated for 1-2 hours. It is then served hot and browned before being placed in a colander. Its texture has been compared to cream cheese and may be slightly different depending on the brand.Pudding is also known as 'pudding soup'. The term is derived from the English word pudding (dunfries) which means 'puddles' and comes from the Latin word meaning pudding.

Kingston is the capital and largest city of Jamaica, located on the southeastern coast of the island. It faces a natural harbour protected by the Palisadoes, a long sand spit which connects the town of Port Royal and the Norman Manley International Airport to the rest of the island. In the Americas, Kingston is the largest predominantly English-speaking city south of the United States.The local government bodies of the parishes of Kingston and St. Andrew were amalgamated by the Kingston and St. Andrew Corporation Act of 1923, to form the Kingston and St. Andrew Corporation (KSAC).

Hugh John Lofting ( 14 January 1886 – 26 September 1947 ) was an English author trained as a civil servant in the US Air Force, serving as an assistant commander of the US National Guard. A graduate of the Harvard School of Law, he earned his law degrees from Princeton University. In 1794, Edward VIII was knighted by Emperor Charles I. He was also crowned king of England.Edward VI was granted the crown at Westminster Abbey and taken to London where he was given the throne until 12 March 1796. Edmund VIII was born on 7 January 1794, in Tenebrus, near Calais, France.

The striatum , or corpus striatum ( also called the striate nucleus ) , is a nucleus ( a cluster of neurons in the basal ganglia, including the anterior cingulate and ventral tegmental areas) that forms around the central part of the brain. The nucleus usually consists of less than two per cent of the overall body mass, but can be larger than four per cent.In human anatomy, its size depends primarily on the number and structure of its main constituent neurons . However, there are some known differences between the human and mouse brain, such as the ability to process more complex stimuli.

A complex system is a system composed of many components which may interact with each other. Examples of complex systems are Earth's global climate, organisms, the human brain, infrastructure such as power grid, transportation or communication systems, complex software and electronic systems, social and economic organizations (like cities), an ecosystem, a living cell, and ultimately the entire universe.Complex systems are systems whose behavior is intrinsically difficult to model due to the dependencies, competitions, relationships, or other types of interactions between their parts or between a given system and its environment.

Mycenae ( ;  or , Mykē̂nai or Mykḗnē) is an archaeological site near Mykines in Argolis, north-eastern Peloponnese, Greece. It is located about  south-west of Athens;  north of Argos; and  south of Corinth. The site is  inland from the Saronic Gulf and built upon a hill rising  above sea level.In the second millennium BC, Mycenae was one of the major centres of Greek civilization, a military stronghold which dominated much of southern Greece, Crete, the Cyclades and parts of southwest Anatolia. The period of Greek history from about 1600 BC to about 1100 BC is called Mycenaean in reference to Mycenae.

Kannada ( ; ಕನ್ನಡ , ; less commonly known as Kanarese ) is a Dravidian language spoken predominantly by the Tamil and Chaldean peoples of South East Asia in central and eastern Tibet. The language has been historically used for centuries in India, Sri Lanka, and Tibet, and is part of an Indo-European tradition that stretches from Central Asia through the Americas to the Indian subcontinent. There are several distinct types of Kannada speakers, but primarily speak the same type of monotheistic language. Some speakers also speak a variant of Hinduism, while others use different dialects and languages.

Crocodiles ( family Crocodylidae ) or true crocodiles are large semiaquatic reptiles that live throughout the tropics in Africa , sub-Saharan Africa and South Asia. These animals typically weigh between 200 to 300 kg and spend most of their lives in water habitats. Their numbers have declined due to habitat loss as sea levels have risen; some species can now be found in subtropical and tropical regions.Crocodiles are highly threatened with extinction due to the lack of biodiversity in their environment, environmental threats such as overfishing and increased competition from landmines. However, recent reports suggest a potential biological impact on these reptiles' diet.

Year 884 ( DCCCLXXXIV ) was a leap year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the British Empire and ending on Saturday, July 7, 1685 at the end of the year. It also ended on Monday, July 4, 1865, which marked the beginning of World War I.The event was named after Sir Henry Liddell (1777-1807) who commanded the British Expeditionary Force from 1815 until his death in April 1918. The French Revolution is often called the "Great Awakening" of the Middle Ages, or perhaps the "Confucian revolution."

A museum ( ; plural museums or , rarely , musea ) is a building or institution that cares for the history, cultural, and artistic heritage of an ancient or medieval city, town, district, or region, as defined by archaeological or archeological sources. It is designed to house a wide variety of arts, including music, poetry, history, architecture, art, ceramics, design and sculpture, architecture, sculpture, photography, dance, science fiction, children's literature, fantasy and horror stories, film, and literature.

Rococo ( , also ) , less commonly Roccoco or Late Baroque , is an exceptionally ornamental and theatrical style of musical theatre which was composed primarily from 1885 until its death in 1924, with a range of productions stretching from folk music to traditional dance. It has been the mainstay of contemporary European music since its inception, as evidenced by many works by the Beatles, John Lennon, Neil Young, and Bob Dylan, among others. In recent years, its influence has spread beyond the globe; for example, more than 40 countries, most notably the United States, have adopted it as their national anthem.

The AGM-114 Hellfire (AGM stands for air-to-ground missile) is an air-to-surface missile (ASM) first developed for anti-armor use, but later models were developed for precision drone strikes against other target types, and have been used in a number of actions aimed to "destroy high-value targets." It was originally developed under the name Heliborne laser, fire-and-forget missile, which led to the colloquial name "Hellfire" ultimately becoming the missile's formal name. It has multi-mission, multi-target precision-strike ability, and can be launched from multiple air, sea, and ground platforms, including the Predator drone.

Wheat is a grass widely cultivated for its seed, a cereal grain which is a worldwide staple food. The many species of wheat together make up the genus Triticum; the most widely grown is common wheat (T. aestivum). The archaeological record suggests that wheat was first cultivated in the regions of the Fertile Crescent around 9600 BCE. Botanically, the wheat kernel is a type of fruit called a caryopsis.Wheat is grown on more land area than any other food crop (, 2014). World trade in wheat is greater than for all other crops combined.

was the 75th emperor of Japan, according to the traditional order of succession.Sutoku's reign spanned the years from 1123 through 1142.GenealogyBefore his ascension to the Chrysanthemum Throne, his personal name (his imina) was Akihito (顕仁). Sutoku was the eldest son of Emperor Toba. Some old texts say he was instead the son of Toba's grandfather, Emperor Shirakawa.Chūgū: Fujiwara no Kiyoko (藤原 聖子) later Kōkamon'in (皇嘉門院), Fujiwara Tadamichi’s daughter Hyounosuke-no-Tsubone (兵衛佐局), Minamoto Masamune's adopted daughter First son: Imperial  (1140–1162).

A radionuclide ( radioactive nuclide , radioisotope or radioactive isotope ) is a nuclide that has excess nuclear energy , in the form of ionised water, and which is absorbed by the air molecules. A radionuclide is a nuclei-particle (N 2 -V) atom. It is responsible for half of all cosmic radiation; its mass is less than 10% of the Earth's gravitational mass. Radium decay is caused by low levels of radioactive carbon dioxide and high levels of potassium cyanide as they move through space. Radiation sources include the sun and the earth.

Tamar the Great (, lit. "King Tamar") ( 1160 – 18 January 1213) reigned as the Queen of Georgia from 1184 to 1213, presiding over the apex of the Georgian Golden Age. A member of the Bagrationi dynasty, her position as the first woman to rule Georgia in her own right was emphasized by the title mepe ("king"), afforded to Tamar in the medieval Georgian sources.Tamar was proclaimed heir and co-ruler by her reigning father George III in 1178, but she faced significant opposition from the aristocracy upon her ascension to full ruling powers after George's death.

Phenylalanine (symbol Phe or F) is an essential α-amino acid with the formula . It can be viewed as a benzyl group substituted for the methyl group of alanine, or a phenyl group in place of a terminal hydrogen of alanine. This essential amino acid is classified as neutral, and nonpolar because of the inert and hydrophobic nature of the benzyl side chain. The L-isomer is used to biochemically form proteins coded for by DNA. Phenylalanine is a precursor for tyrosine, the monoamine neurotransmitters dopamine, norepinephrine (noradrenaline), epinephrine (adrenaline), and the skin pigment melanin.

Robert Ross is an American blues singer, songwriter, acoustic and electric guitarist, slide guitarist, and harmonica player. He is the leader of the Robert Ross Band and The Jazz-Manian Devils. He also performs as a solo artist.Ross was nominated seven times for a New York Music Award and has won twice, once for Best Blues Artist in 1989, and once for Best Live Blues Artist in 2011. Ross was inducted into the New York Blues Hall Of Fame in 2011. He has also won several grants for integrating music into education programs.

Carnival is a Western Christian festive season that occurs before the liturgical season of Lent. The main events typically occur during February or early March, during the period historically known as Shrovetide (or Pre-Lent). Carnival typically involves public celebrations, including events such as parades, public street parties and other entertainments, combining some elements of a circus. Elaborate costumes and masks allow people to set aside their everyday individuality and experience a heightened sense of social unity. Participants often indulge in excessive consumption of alcohol, meat, and other foods that will be forgone during upcoming Lent.

Linus Carl Pauling (; February 28, 1901 – August 19, 1994) was an American chemist, biochemist, chemical engineer,  peace activist, author, and educator. He published more than 1,200 papers and books, of which about 850 dealt with scientific topics. New Scientist called him one of the 20 greatest scientists of all time, and as of 2000, he was rated the 16th most important scientist in history. For his scientific work, Pauling was awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1954. For his peace activism, he was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in 1962.

The Martian Chronicles is a science fiction fix-up novel , published in 1950 , by American writer Ray Bradbury that takes place over the planet, Mars. The author of the novel and its first editor have not been announced but the book is considered one of the best sci-fi novelizations ever made . The plot has been updated to cover the next generation of space exploration while the characters are still alive. In the early 19th century an English poet named Philipus was writing poems. A year after the publication of his son Philipus's The Poetical Psalms (1788), Pius IX began writing poetry.

Niacin, also known as nicotinic acid, is an organic compound and a form of vitamin B3, an essential human nutrient. It can be manufactured by plants and animals from the amino acid tryptophan. Niacin is obtained in the diet from a variety of whole and processed foods, with highest contents in fortified packaged foods, meat, poultry, red fish such as tuna and salmon, lesser amounts in nuts, legumes and seeds. Niacin as a dietary supplement is used to treat pellagra, a disease caused by niacin deficiency. Signs and symptoms of pellagra include skin and mouth lesions, anemia, headaches, and tiredness.

In the 1980s , the telecommunications industry expected that digital services would follow much the same pattern as voice services and Internet traffic, but in a number of countries such as India and Africa, broadband networks were not built. This led to concerns about the potential for unintended consequences. As the technology progressed, it became increasingly difficult to prevent the transmission of information at home and abroad. Data privacy and civil liberties issues emerged from the implementation of data protection laws, which allowed companies to collect data on their customers without charge. I was born in Budapest, Hungary, in 1885.

Tazio Giorgio Nuvolari (; 16 November 1892 – 11 August 1953) was an Italian racing driver. He first raced motorcycles and then concentrated on sports cars and single-seaters. A resident of Mantua, he was known as 'Il Mantovano Volante' (The Flying Mantuan) and nicknamed 'Nivola'. His victories—72 major races, 150 in all—included 24 Grands Prix, five Coppa Cianos, two Mille Miglias, two Targa Florios, two RAC Tourist Trophies, a Le Mans 24-hour race, and a European Championship in Grand Prix racing. Ferdinand Porsche called him "the greatest driver of the past, the present, and the future.

Lingerie (, , ) is a category of primarily women's clothing including undergarments (mainly brassieres), sleepwear, and lightweight robes. The choice of the word is often motivated by an intention to imply that the garments are alluring, fashionable, or both. In a 2015 US survey, 75% of women and 26% of men reported having worn sexy lingerie in their lifetime.Lingerie is made of lightweight, stretchy, smooth, sheer or decorative fabrics such as silk, satin, Lycra, charmeuse, chiffon, or (especially and traditionally) lace.

Pope John XXII (; 1244 – 4 December 1334), born Jacques Duèze (or d'Euse), was head of the Catholic Church from 7 August 1316 to his death in 1334.He was the second and longest-reigning Avignon Pope, elected by the Conclave of Cardinals, which was assembled in Lyon through the work of King Louis X's brother Philip, the Count of Poitiers, later King Philip V of France. Like his predecessor, Clement V, Pope John centralized power and income in the Papacy and lived a princely life in Avignon.

A pegmatite is an igneous rock showing a very coarse texture, with large interlocking crystals usually greater in size than  and sometimes greater than . Most pegmatites are composed of quartz, feldspar, and mica, having a similar silicic composition as granite. However, rarer intermediate composition and mafic pegmatites are known.Many of the world's largest crystals are found within pegmatites. These include crystals of microcline, quartz, mica, spodumene, beryl, and tourmaline. Some individual crystals are over  long.Most pegmatites are thought to form from the last fluid fraction of a large crystallizing magma body.

Bi-curious is a term for a person , usually someone who is a heterosexual , who is curious or open about something other than sex, but is otherwise not interested in sex. It has traditionally been used by people living in urban areas to describe people and places where they are familiarized with different cultures, language, and behaviors. Ivan Ilyin (born January 29, 1948), was a Russian actor, film director, and novelist. His first movie, "Банда Порма сицетва чикога", aired from 1978 until his death in 1987 at age 77.

Fidelio , originally titled ( Leonore , or The Triumph of Marital Love ) , Op . 72 , is a novel in Italian literature that has been adapted for film. The Vampiric Kingdom of Sicily, also called the Republic of Sardinia , is an ancient kingdom in northern and eastern Mediterranean Europe, which was located about 1,600 years before its formation in the ninth century BCE. It is part of the Sicilian Peninsula, where it is considered the capital by the Roman Emperor Augustus during the reigns of his father and mother, both of them serving as heads of state to the Holy Roman Empire.

Nansen passports, originally and officially stateless persons passports, were internationally recognized refugee travel documents from 1922 to 1938, first issued by the League of Nations to stateless refugees. They quickly became known as "Nansen passports" for their promoter, the Norwegian statesman and polar explorer Fridtjof Nansen.HistoryThe end of World War I saw significant turmoil, leading to a refugee crisis. Numerous governments were toppled, and national borders were re-drawn, often along generally ethnic lines. Civil war broke out in some countries. Many people left their homes because of war or persecution or fear thereof.

A nuclear thermal rocket (NTR) is a type of thermal rocket where the heat from a nuclear reaction, often nuclear fission, replaces the chemical energy of the propellants in a chemical rocket. In an NTR, a working fluid, usually liquid hydrogen, is heated to a high temperature in a nuclear reactor and then expands through a rocket nozzle to create thrust. The external nuclear heat source theoretically allows a higher effective exhaust velocity and is expected to double or triple payload capacity compared to chemical propellants that store energy internally.NTRs have been proposed as a spacecraft propulsion technology, with the earliest ground tests occurring in 1955.

Nuclear engineering is the branch of engineering concerned with the application of breaking down  atomic nuclei (fission) or of combining atomic nuclei (fusion),  or with the application of other sub-atomic processes based on the principles of nuclear physics. In the sub-field of nuclear fission, it particularly includes the design, interaction, and maintenance of systems and components like reactors, power plants, or weaponry. The field also includes the study of medical and other applications of radiation, particularly Ionizing radiation, nuclear safety, heat/thermodynamics transport, nuclear fuel, or other related technology (e.g., radioactive waste disposal) and the problems of nuclear proliferation.

Fishing is the activity of trying to catch fish . Fish are often caught in the wild but may also be caught as early as 4, 3, and 2 years old. To catch fish, the fish must have fins on their backs. They can weigh between 6 - 8 kilograms depending on how large they are when caught. There are approximately 100 species of fish that are known to live in North America, Europe, and Africa, with a population range ranging from 15 to 20 individuals.The number of fish found annually varies by country; this is reflected in the total numbers of fish caught each year.

is a Japanese manga series written and illustrated by Rumiko Takahashi. It was serialized in Big Comic Spirits from November 1980 to April 1987, with the chapters collected into 15 tankōbon volumes by Shogakukan. Maison Ikkoku is a bittersweet romantic comedy involving a group of madcap people who live in a boarding house in 1980s Tokyo. The story focuses primarily on the gradually developing relationships between Yusaku Godai, a poor student down on his luck, and Kyoko Otonashi, a young, recently widowed boarding house manager.The manga was adapted into a ninety-six-episode anime television series created by Studio Deen that ran on Fuji TV from March 1986 to March 1988.

SPARC (Scalable Processor Architecture) is a reduced instruction set computing (RISC) instruction set architecture originally developed by Sun Microsystems. Its design was strongly influenced by the experimental Berkeley RISC system developed in the early 1980s. First developed in 1986 and released in 1987, SPARC was one of the most successful early commercial RISC systems, and its success led to the introduction of similar RISC designs from a number of vendors through the 1980s and 90s.The first implementation of the original 32-bit architecture (SPARC V7) was used in Sun's Sun-4 workstation and server systems, replacing their earlier Sun-3 systems based on the Motorola 68000 series of processors.

In chemistry , a nucleophile is a chemical species that forms bonds with electrophiles by donating an electron pair . The molecule has been traditionally understood to occur naturally in all living cells (such as human cells, plants and fish) but its origins are still debated.The molecular name for such molecules is cyclohexylphosphates (HCPs). Although it may be commonly confused with "polymer", these hydrocarbons are often referred to as "monobots" due to their low solubility. They are also sometimes called fluoromethanes when they are composed primarily of phospholipids and hydrogens (hydrogen peroxide and water peroxide).

Kenneth Charles Williams ( 22 February 1926 – 15 April 1988 ) was an English actor . He was best known for his roles as Captain James Travolta in TV's The Night Manager , and in numerous other shows. Williams starred in films that aired from 1977 to 1984, but he returned to television in 1991.He also appeared on the BBC drama Star Trek; he later worked as executive producer of Doctor Who.Williams was best known for his roles as Captain James Travolta during the mid-1960s, after which he won the British Academy Award for Best Drama Actor for his role in Star Trek: Discovery.

Year 1054 (MLIV) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Sultan Tughril leads a large Seljuk army out of Azerbaijan into Armenia, possibly to consolidate his frontier, while providing an incentive to his Turkoman allies in the form of plunder. Tughril divides his army into four columns, ordering three to veer off to the north to raid into central and northern Armenia, while he takes the fourth column towards Lake Van. The Seljuk Turks capture and sack the fortress city of Artchesh, after an 8-day siege.

The governor general of Canada is the federal viceregal representative of the . The is head of state of Canada's largest and most populous province, but he serves as prime minister of Ontario. He is also the deputy chief executive officer of Canadian Broadcasting Corporation (BCCC). Canadian National Railway Company (CNRS) was an American railroad company in the 1930s and 1950s that operated several railroads throughout the Midwest and East Coast of America. Most of its locomotives were used by Southern states such as Alabama and Texas, as well as British Columbia, Quebec, and New Brunswick.

Toilet humour , or potty or scatological humour ( compare scatology ) , is a type of off-colour humour dealing with the appearance or behaviour of people. In the United Kingdom and Ireland, it is commonly used by women to illustrate issues relating to religion or religious subjects. It can also be used as a source of entertainment for children, as a method of teaching about history, or as a way for parents to learn about local culture. There are currently three categories of humor: non-political humor, humour that promotes social justice, and humour that encourages family interaction.

A think tank, or policy institute, is a research institute that performs research and advocacy concerning topics such as social policy, political strategy, economics, military, technology, and culture. Most think tanks are non-governmental organizations, but some are semi-autonomous agencies within government or are associated with particular political parties, businesses or the military. Think-tank funding often includes a combination of donations from wealthy individuals and personal contributions, with many also accepting government grants.Think tanks publish articles, studies or even draft legislation on particular matters of policy or society.

Pope Leo XI ( ; 2 June 153527 April 1605 ) , born Alessandro Ottaviano de ' Medici , was a Italian priest and physician in Rome from about 1520 to 1530 who served in the Roman military. He is best known for his penance on charges of perjury and heresy after his trial in 1542, but also as a defender of religious truth in the early centuries of Rome. He became pope at the same time as St. Gregory VII of Tuscany and Pope John Paul II. Namibia is a land of approximately 5,000 hectares (4,500 acres) of arid land covered in lush green plains.

Lucia di Lammermoor is a dramma tragico (tragic opera) in three acts by Italian composer Gaetano Donizetti. Salvadore Cammarano wrote the Italian-language libretto loosely based upon Sir Walter Scott's 1819 historical novel The Bride of Lammermoor.Donizetti wrote Lucia di Lammermoor in 1835, when he was reaching the peak of his reputation as an opera composer. Gioachino Rossini had recently retired and Vincenzo Bellini had died shortly before the premiere of Lucia leaving Donizetti as "the sole reigning genius of Italian opera". Not only were conditions ripe for Donizetti's success as a composer, but there was also a widespread interest in the history and culture of Scotland.

Heavy Metal : F.A.K.K . 2 is a third-person shooter video game made by Ritual Entertainment in 2000 . The game takes place in the same world as Bloodborne and was developed by Activision. Eclipse Eclipse (アインタル, アドロー , Eclipse Eclipse?) is a science fiction video game based on the first-person shooter series of Final Fantasy III. It focuses on Earth and its aftermath from the events that followed the Second World War, following an asteroid collision with the Cygnus fleet.The game revolves around a group of heroes called Starks who decide to join forces to solve the mystery of Ectoplasmic Eclipse.

A supercomputer is a computer with a high level of performance as compared to a general-purpose computer. The performance of a supercomputer is commonly measured in floating-point operations per second (FLOPS) instead of million instructions per second (MIPS). Since 2017, there are supercomputers which can perform over 1017 FLOPS (a hundred quadrillion FLOPS, 100 petaFLOPS or 100 PFLOPS). For comparison, a desktop computer has performance in the range of hundreds of gigaFLOPS to tens of teraFLOPS.Since November 2017, all of the world's fastest 500 supercomputers run Linux-based operating systems.

Kevin James Anderson (born March 27, 1962) is an American science fiction author. He has written spin-off novels for Star Wars, StarCraft, Titan A.E. and The X-Files, and with Brian Herbert is the co-author of the Dune prequel series. His original works include the Saga of Seven Suns series and the Nebula Award-nominated Assemblers of Infinity. He has also written several comic books, including the Dark Horse Star Wars series Tales of the Jedi written in collaboration with Tom Veitch, Dark Horse Predator titles, and The X-Files titles for Topps.

Malayalam (; , ) is a Dravidian language spoken in the Indian state of Kerala and the union territories of Lakshadweep and Puducherry (Mahé district) by the Malayali people. It is one of 22 scheduled languages of India and is spoken by 2.88% of Indians. Malayalam has official language status in Kerala, Lakshadweep and Puducherry (Mahé), and is spoken by 34 million people worldwide. Malayalam is also spoken by linguistic minorities in the neighbouring states; with significant number of speakers in the Kodagu and Dakshina Kannada districts of Karnataka, and Nilgiris and Kanyakumari, districts of Tamil Nadu.

Harriet Tubman (born Araminta Ross, March 10, 1913) was an American abolitionist and political activist. Born into slavery, Tubman escaped and subsequently made some 13 missions to rescue approximately 70 enslaved people, including family and friends, using the network of antislavery activists and safe houses known as the Underground Railroad. During the American Civil War, she served as an armed scout and spy for the Union Army. In her later years, Tubman was an activist in the movement for women's suffrage.Born enslaved in Dorchester County, Maryland, Tubman was beaten and whipped by her various masters as a child.

Isotope separation is the process of concentrating specific isotopes of a chemical element by removing other isotopes. The use of the nuclides produced is varied. The largest variety is used in research (e.g. in chemistry where atoms of "marker" nuclide are used to figure out reaction mechanisms). By tonnage, separating natural uranium into enriched uranium and depleted uranium is the largest application. In the following text, mainly the uranium enrichment is considered. This process is crucial in the manufacture of uranium fuel for nuclear power plants, and is also required for the creation of uranium-based nuclear weapons.

Steven C. McConnell is an author of software engineering textbooks such as Code Complete , Rapid Development , and Software Architectures . He holds degrees in Economics, Computer Science, Mathematics, and Information Science. He has written numerous articles for publications by The Washington Times, The Economist, Maclean's, and others. He is the editor of a wide variety of computer science journals. He holds various honorary doctorates, including from Columbia University, Oxford University Press, Carnegie Mellon University, and the Institute for Computing Machinery (IMM) Graduate School of Engineering and Applied Sciences.

was a Japanese television cooking show produced by Fuji Television . The series , which premiered on October 10 , 1991, was the tenth season to air. It starred Kyohei Miyazaki and Yasumasa Ueda, two of the seven original cast members and six new cast members. Kami no Tatsuki ( 薜 シリズ・菜 い トラワークス ) is a series of four short stories published in Japanese comic and manga magazine Manga Magazine. The story arc follows the lives of nine elementary school students from a high school in Tokyo. It is written and illustrated by Hideki Kawamori, an American illustrator based in Osaka, Japan.

The M102 is a light, towable 105 mm howitzer used by the United States Army in the Vietnam War, the First Gulf War, and the Iraq War.Overview The M102 105 mm howitzer is used in air mobile (helicopter), attack plane, and light infantry operations. The weapon carriage is lightweight welded aluminum, mounted on a variable recoil mechanism. The weapon is manually loaded and positioned, and can be towed by a 2-ton truck or High Mobility Multipurpose Wheeled Vehicle (HMMWV), can be transported by UH-60 Black Hawk helicopters, or can be dropped by parachute with airborne units.

Year 926 (CMXXVI) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Spring – The Italian nobles turn against King Rudolph II of Burgundy and request that Hugh of Provence, the effective ruler of Lower Burgundy, be elected as king of Italy. Rudolph's father-in-law Duke Burchard II of Swabia is ambushed and killed near Novara, by the henchmen of Archbishop Lambert of Milan. Rudolph, disillusioned by the news, returns to Burgundy to protect himself. Hugh has himself crowned King of Italy.

A spacecraft is a vehicle or machine designed to fly in outer space. A type of artificial satellite, spacecraft are used for a variety of purposes, including communications, Earth observation, meteorology, navigation, space colonization, planetary exploration, and transportation of humans and cargo. All spacecraft except single-stage-to-orbit vehicles cannot get into space on their own, and require a launch vehicle (carrier rocket).On a sub-orbital spaceflight, a space vehicle enters space and then returns to the surface without having gained sufficient energy or velocity to make a full orbit of the Earth.

Melissa Sue Anderson (born September 26, 1962) is an American-Canadian actress. She began her career as a child actress after appearing in several commercials in Los Angeles. Anderson is known for her role as Mary Ingalls in the NBC drama series Little House on the Prairie (1974–1981), for which she received a nomination for the Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Drama Series. She is also known for film roles that include Vivian in Midnight Offerings (1981), Ginny in the slasher film Happy Birthday to Me (1981), and Alex in the ABC Afterschool Special, Which Mother Is Mine?

A knight 's tour is a sequence of moves of a knight on a chessboard such that the knight visits the knight's position as he enters the board. Witchcraft has its roots in Ancient Egypt . Witchcraft was first brought about by the king of Israel, Ishmael , to use magic against certain enemies of the King of the Egyptians. He used magic to destroy and corrupt his enemies, often using magic to gain their respect. According to the Babylonian tradition, the god Baal ruled over the entire Canaanites for 1,000 years before Moses became king.

In the Ancient Greek religion, Hestia (; , "hearth" or "fireside") is the virgin goddess of the hearth, the right ordering of domesticity, the family, the home, and the state. In Greek mythology, she is the firstborn child of the Titans Cronus and Rhea.Customarily, in Greek culture, Hestia received the first offering at every sacrifice in the household. In the public domain, the hearth of the prytaneum functioned as her official sanctuary, and, when a new colony was established, a flame from Hestia's public hearth in the mother city would be carried to the new settlement.

In the administrative divisions of France, the department  is one of the three levels of government under the national level ("territorial collectivities"), between the administrative regions and the communes. Ninety-six departments are in metropolitan France, and five are overseas departments, which are also classified as overseas regions. Departments are further subdivided into 332 arrondissements, and these are divided into cantons. The last two levels of government have no autonomy; they are the basis of local organisation of police, fire departments and, sometimes, administration of elections.Each department is administered by an elected body called a departmental council ( [sing.

Lingerie ( , , ) is a category of primarily women 's clothing including undergarments ( mainly brassieres ) , neckwear and skirts . There are also several different categories of "shoes" which are considered feminine but do not generally have an emphasis on form or function. For more information about shoes, check out the article "Women's footwear" in the Women's Studies section of The New York Times Magazine.The main fashion industry in the world has evolved through both technological developments and cultural changes. A recent trend in the garment trade is to shift away from wool and linen to fabrics, with garments now being woven by hand.

The putamen ( ; from Latin , meaning `` nutshell '' ) is a round structure located at the base of an octave. It is often referred to as the octave, or simply the square, because it was considered by some artists to represent both the top and bottom end of the octave range. At the time of its first appearance in 1969, the name was applied to one of the earliest octaves in all musical notation: the 𖜺��𖗰 (măr), which describes how far back there is a straight line between the uppermost point of the octave (top) and the lowermost point (bottom).

John D. Carmack II ( born August 20 , 1970 ) is an American computer programmer and video game developer. He spent his career working for Apple on the Macintosh and later Microsoft on mobile platforms. Carmack was formerly the co-founder of Atari, which he acquired in 2002.In 1990, Carmack became one of the world's leading computer industry luminaries. Among his notable accomplishments was the creation of the first personal computer – a PC called the Atari Jaguar – which he created to compete with rival systems like the Mac and Commodore PET.

A software bug is an error , flaw or fault in computer software that causes it to produce an incorrect output. The most common software bug is one that involves the use of uninitialized variables and/or a system call that produces unexpected results. In some cases, bugs can lead to other kinds of programming problems. Teknix (1940s - 1975) is a Czech-based company with headquarters in Prague, where they manufacture TKNIX keyboards and mice. During its time, their main focus has been in the development of wireless communication solutions for the mobile telephone market.

Palm OS ( also known as Garnet OS ) is a discontinued mobile operating system initially developed by Palm , with the development of version 3.2.3 and 4.2 in June 2000. The Windows 10 Operating System was released on February 23rd, 2006, at the request of Microsoft, who continued to pursue Windows Mobile devices until December 2010. The Windows 10 operating system received its official release on January 27th, 2011, and remains available to download from the Windows Store and other Internet-based applications such as web browsers. Windows Phone has been supported since its initial release on January 30th, 2014.

The European Men's Handball Championship is the official competition for senior men's national handball teams of Europe and takes place every two years since 1994, in the even-numbered year between the World Championship. In addition to crowning the European champions, the tournament also serves as a qualifying tournament for the Olympic Games and World Championship. The most successful team is Sweden who have won five titles. Spain, however, have won most medals.HistoryIn 1946, the International Handball Federation was founded by eight European nations, and though non-European nations competed at the World Championships, the medals had always been taken by European nations.

A verb is a word ( part of speech ) that in syntax conveys an action ( bring , read , or speak ) or idea (see noun ). Etymology [ edit | edit source ]
From the Gaelic ǁc, from Proto-Indo-European *c₃ (cf. Old French: Ἁνοφή, also cīn, meaning 'to draw') or from Proto-Indo-Celtic *a₃ , derived from Ancient Greek ελαός; Latin αῶρατως, which was derived from Hebrew אστος and πολέος respectively. It may also have been used as a subjunctive, adverbial, adjective, participle, or genitive.

The Novikov self-consistency principle, also known as the Novikov self-consistency conjecture and Larry Niven's law of conservation of history, is a principle developed by Russian physicist Igor Dmitriyevich Novikov in the mid-1980s. Novikov intended it to solve the problem of paradoxes in time travel, which is theoretically permitted in certain solutions of general relativity that contain what are known as closed timelike curves. The principle asserts that if an event exists that would cause a paradox or any "change" to the past whatsoever, then the probability of that event is zero.

Sir Robert Alexander Watson Watt  (13 April 1892 – 5 December 1973) was a British pioneer of radio direction finding and radar technology.Watt began his career in radio physics with a job at the Met Office, where he began looking for accurate ways to track thunderstorms using the radio signals given off by lightning. This led to the 1920s development of a system later known as high-frequency direction finding (HFDF or "huff-duff"). Although well publicized at the time, the system's enormous military potential was not developed until the late 1930s.

Parsifal ( WWV 111 ) is an opera in three acts by Richard Wagner with the libretto by the composer Hélio Musée de L'Eglise. The original version was written in two-part, ten-minute operas for a German audience and presented to the orchestra in Vienna on April 6, 1942. The French Revolution came to power in January of 1848 as part of a counterrevolutionary effort led by Napoleon Bonaparte. It was a direct reaction to the events of that year's revolution against the reactionary Franco-Prussian Alliance which took place during the First World War.

`` The Ones Who Walk Away from Omelas '' is a 1973 work of short philosophical fiction by American writer and screenwriter James Patterson. The book, about a college boy named Jonathan O'Neill (whose first name was pronounced ) living with his wife Martha at the start of their sonhood, is a sequel to an unfinished 1984 novel that Patterson described as "a little-known story," but which may have been rewritten or adapted elsewhere. Etymology: The Greek word Æcinnes, sometimes spelled Æcus, comes from a Latin root of Æcyculus, also known as Ædynnaeus , and οοείδυνικος, or Ecygina.

Hoysala architecture is the building style in Hindu temple architecture developed under the rule of the Hoysala Empire between the 11th and 14th centuries, in the region known today as Karnataka, a state of India. Hoysala influence was at its peak in the 13th century, when it dominated the Southern Deccan Plateau region. Large and small temples built during this era remain as examples of the Hoysala architectural style, including the Chennakesava Temple at Belur, the Hoysaleswara Temple at Halebidu, and the Kesava Temple at Somanathapura. Other examples of Hoysala craftsmanship are the temples at Belavadi, Amruthapura, Hosaholalu, Mosale, Arasikere, Basaralu, Kikkeri and Nuggehalli.

Padthaway is a small town in the Australian state of South Australia located in the state 's south-east within the State Territory of Victoria. The town is located at the intersection of two rivers, one of which lies on the north bank of a river. Its population is less than 100 but there is a population density of over 1,200 people per kilometre. HistoryEarly lifeEtymologyFrom the Indo-Australian word Ṭapāra (to be), it translates from Old English "the house" or "The house," as well as other forms of the adjective ūnē ("home").

The Reedy Creek Improvement District (RCID) is the immediate governing jurisdiction for the land of the Walt Disney World Resort. It includes  within the outer limits of Orange and Osceola counties in Florida. The RCID includes the cities of Bay Lake and Lake Buena Vista, and unincorporated RCID land.HistoryCreationInitial stepsAfter the success of Disneyland in California, Walt Disney began planning a second park on the East Coast. Disney disliked the businesses that had sprung up around Disneyland, and therefore wanted control of a much larger area of land for the new project.

Phenylalanine ( symbol Phe or F ) is an essential α-amino acid with the formula . It can be viewed as a key ingredient in human health medicine.The most notable example of phenylalanine is phenylalanine phosphate (AAP) that has been extensively studied and synthesized. However, its composition varies from species to species, which has led to considerable debate and controversy. Here we show that there exists a class of amino acids known as methyleneal (MAD) , which is also known as poly(4,3-dihydroxyphenyl)-1-(4,4-dimethylhydroxymethylphenylindoleacetamide) or phenylbenzodiazepine (PREP).

Theories of political behavior, as an aspect of political science, attempt to quantify and explain the influences that define a person's political views, ideology, and levels of political participation. Political behavior is the subset of human behavior that involves politics and power. Theorists who have had an influence on this field include Karl Deutsch and Theodor Adorno.Long-term influences on political orientationInteraction with the political views of parental figures is often thought of as the primary long-term influence on political orientation and willingness to take part in the political system.Teachers and other educational authority figures are also often thought to have a significant impact on political orientation.

Eagle is the common name for many large birds of prey of the family Accipitridae. Eagles belong to several groups of genera, some of which are closely related. Most of the 60 species of eagle are from Eurasia and Africa. Outside this area, just 14 species can be found—2 in North America, 9 in Central and South America, and 3 in Australia.Eagles are not a natural group but denote essentially any bird of prey large enough to hunt sizeable (about 50 cm long or more overall) vertebrate prey.DescriptionEagles are large, powerfully built birds of prey, with heavy heads and beaks.

The Lhotshampa or Lhotsampa people are a heterogeneous Bhutanese people of Nepalese descent . `` Lhotshampa '' , which means "people living on mountains", refers to an isolated Himalayan region in Central Asia called Tibet, and is situated close to the western end of the Great Rift Valley. The term has also been used to denote large islands that can accommodate many thousands of settlers. A significant portion of the population is ethnically Tibetan, as is customary in some areas of Tibet (see Tibet). There are a range of cultural identities, such as Sikhism, Buddhism, Hinduism, Islam, and other ethnic groups.

Larry Simon Gelbart (February 25, 1928 – September 11, 2009) was an American television writer, playwright, screenwriter, director and author, most famous as a creator and producer of the television series M*A*S*H, and as co-writer of the Broadway musicals A Funny Thing Happened on the Way to the Forum and City of Angels.BiographyEarly lifeGelbart was born in Chicago, Illinois, to Jewish immigrants Harry Gelbart, "a barber since his half of a childhood in Latvia," and Frieda Sturner, who migrated to America from Dąbrowa Górnicza, Poland.

Show jumping , is a part of a group of English riding equestrian events that also includes dressage , eventing in horse racing, road running and track cycling. The term "horse jump" was first used in 1924 as a slang word for any activity where the wearer jumped off an obstacle before jumping over it with his shoe or hand. Its earliest use was during a circus performance when spectators were asked to move the horse by using their hands and feet while they moved. However, this practice has been gradually phased out since 1920, with many people choosing to call them jumps instead.

North America's first transcontinental railroad (known originally as the "Pacific Railroad" and later as the "Overland Route") was a  continuous railroad line constructed between 1863 and 1869 that connected the existing eastern U.S. rail network at Council Bluffs, Iowa with the Pacific coast at the Oakland Long Wharf on San Francisco Bay. The rail line was built by three private companies over public lands provided by extensive US land grants. Construction was financed by both state and US government subsidy bonds as well as by company issued mortgage bonds.

Patch collecting or badge collecting (also, scutelliphily, from Latin scutellus meaning little shield, and Greek phileein meaning to love) is the hobby of collecting patches or badges.Souvenir patchesSouvenir patches are usually shield-shaped and generally contain a coat of arms, a map or a miniature view. The patches can be made of any material, but are usually woven or embroidered fabric, though they can also be made from paper or, increasingly, plastic.Other types of collectible patches include police or service patches, space mission patches, Scout patches, fashion patches, political and sports stickers, walking stick labels, car window pennants, and pin badges.

The Palmer Raids were a series of raids conducted in November 1919 and January 1920 by the United States Department of State. While they did not directly involve the Ku Klux Klan, they involved a number of armed groups, including anti-Communists, anarchists, and "anarchist" sympathizers. [3][4]
The Palmer Raids were also carried out by the National Security Agency (NSA), which had jurisdiction over various national security agencies. The group consisted of more than 50 members, who served as officers for the NSA from September 1921 to August 1922.

Heavy Metal: F.A.K.K. 2 is a third-person shooter video game made by Ritual Entertainment in 2000. The sequel to the Heavy Metal 2000 animated film, the game stars Julie in her quest to save her home planet of Eden from GITH, an ancient entity seeking to conquer the universe. Using a variety of weapons, Julie must fight off GITH's forces while at the same time uncovering a secret hidden deep within the planet.F.A.K.K. 2 allows players to pair up and use two weapons at the same time depending on the situation. Players can block enemy attacks and execute powerful combo moves to deal deadly blows to their enemies.

Thrust is a reaction force described quantitatively by Newton's third law. When a system expels or accelerates mass in one direction, the accelerated mass will cause a force of equal magnitude but opposite direction to be applied to that system.The force applied on a surface in a direction perpendicular or normal to the surface is also called thrust. Force, and thus thrust, is measured using the International System of Units (SI) in newtons (symbol: N), and represents the amount needed to accelerate 1 kilogram of mass at the rate of 1 meter per second per second.

SPARC ( Scalable Processor Architecture ) is a reduced instruction set computing ( RISC ) instruction set architecture originally developed by Qualcomm. The codename was named in reference to the fact that it is the only RISC processor to operate on the silicon substrate and can handle a large number of tasks.The ARM Cortex-M9X (also called the X64 or XMPP32) is the first full-fledged open-source chip based on ARM Cores. A significant portion of this chip's capabilities is based on Intel Atom chipsets, which support 64-bit processing at up to 4.2 GHz, 8 bits of dedicated memory and microprocessor cores, and a host of other low-power ARM-based solutions.

Igor Fyodorovich Stravinsky ( 6 April 1971 ) was a Russian composer , pianist and conductor , later of French national filmography. He is considered by many artists as the founder of contemporary music history . Stravinsky, who founded the Berlin-based production company Völkirchen at the beginning of the 15th century, achieved his fame as one of the leading composers of jazz in Italy before moving to Prague.Stravinsky has written numerous works over the centuries, from the classic ballad Don Giovanni to operas like "The Man Without God" and "The Daughters of Heaven".

Albert the Magnanimous KG, elected King of the Romans as Albert II (10 August 139727 October 1439) was king of the Holy Roman Empire and a member of the House of Habsburg. By inheritance he became Albert V, Duke of Austria. Through his wife he also became King of Hungary, Croatia, Bohemia, and inherited a claim to the Duchy of Luxembourg.BiographyAlbert was born in Vienna as the son of Albert IV, Duke of Austria, and Joanna Sophia of Bavaria.He succeeded to the Duchy of Austria at the age of seven on his father's death in 1404.

Saxony-Anhalt ( ; ) is a state of Germany , bordering the states of Brandenburg , Saxony , Thuringia and Prussia. It has some of the strongest concentration of Romanians in the eastern parts of the country; it also has great numbers of immigrants from neighboring countries such as Lithuania and Poland . The state is home to many other churches, synagogues, government schools and other institutions.The state constitution prescribes that elections for governors be held on July 1, with the governor having two days to vote.Governments in other European member states have also had election periods, which are not specified in the constitution.

Alkanna tinctoria, the dyer's alkanet or simply alkanet, is a herb in the borage family. Its main notability is its roots are used as a red dye. The plant is also known as dyers' bugloss, orchanet, Spanish bugloss, or Languedoc bugloss. It is native to the Mediterranean region. In Greece A. tinctoria shows a strong genetic structure that has been shown to be mainly driven by neutral processes. A. tinctoria has 30 chromosomes and is regarded as a dysploid at the tetraploid level (4x + 2).A. tinctoria has a bright blue flower.

Year 1073 (MLXXIII) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Spring – Emperor Michael VII (Doukas) sends a Byzantine army to deal with Seljuk raiding in Cappadocia, supported with a mixed force of Norman and French mercenary heavy cavalry under Roussel de Bailleul. Roussel re-conquers some territory in Galatia and declares it an independent Norman state. Michael, enraged, sends another army led by his uncle, Caesar John Doukas and the veteran General Nikephoros Botaneiates to deal with the rising of the Norman threat in Asia minor.

Henry Dunant ( born Jean-Henri Dunant ; 8 May 182830 October 1910 ) , also known as Henri Dunant , was a French philosopher, essayist and novelist whose novels, operas and poetry are widely considered to be classics of twentieth-century American literature. In 1787 he became director of the Society of Poet Laureates . He worked in Paris from 1888 until his death in 1890. He was awarded the Nobel Prize in Literature in 1899 for writing a critical work entitled "Le Nouvelle De Déjà Vu: La Bibliote des Beaux Arts et Etudes", with which he contributed three short essays.

The raven paradox , also known as Hempel 's paradox , Hempel 's ravens , or rarely the paradox of which Hempel 's paradox is the main inspiration, was a very important scientific concept in the 19th-to-century European sciences. Spiral gland ( : : : ) is a gland located in the throat of a fish. The gland can be either a lymph node (like a vein) or an endocervical nerve. The epithelial gland contains two outer layers, one inner and one outer. The cells within this layer are attached to the body, called the spongiform cells.

Gender is the range of characteristics pertaining to femininity and masculinity and differentiating between them. Depending on the context, this may include sex-based social structures (i.e. gender roles) and gender identity. Most cultures use a gender binary, having two genders (boys/men and girls/women); those who exist outside these groups may fall under the umbrella term non-binary. Some societies have specific genders besides "man" and "woman", such as the hijras of South Asia; these are often referred to as third genders (and fourth genders, etc.).

Norman Quentin Cook ( born Quentin Leo Cook ; 31st July 1963 ) , also known by his stage name Norman, was an Irish writer and journalist who became a prominent voice in Irish literature.Cook is the author of seven novels, five collections, and two poetry collections, both best known as the novel The Poetic Laureate . He won many awards throughout his career, including the Distinguished Prize for Short Fiction for his fiction, and the National Literary Award for Nonfiction . The first human to become trapped on a planet was Eurydice at the beginning of the 4th millennium B.C., during the Pleistocene epoch.

An intranet is a computer network for sharing information, easier communication, collaboration tools, operational systems, and other computing services within an organization, usually to the exclusion of access by outsiders. The term is used in contrast to public networks, such as the Internet, but uses most of the same technology based on the Internet Protocol Suite.A company-wide intranet can constitute an important focal point of internal communication and collaboration, and provide a single starting point to access internal and external resources. In its simplest form, an intranet is established with the technologies for local area networks (LANs) and wide area networks (WANs).

The Circus Maximus ( Latin for `` largest circus '' ; Italian : Circo Massimo ) is an ancient Roman circus built in 1592 and built around St. Peter's Circus in Rome. It was the most successful modern circus in the Roman Empire, with over one hundred thousand operas performed throughout the entire century. Stromae , or Stromae trinitaria , is a Latin name that first appeared in the sixth century after the death of Pope Clement VII. Although not officially recognized as a species, it is used to refer to large human beings who live under the protection of their monarchs.

Pope John XXII ( ; 1244 – 4 December 1334 ) , born Jacques Duèze ( or d'Euse ) , is one of the most important French authors to have written the 18th century. He was a mathematician, geographer, political philosopher, poet, playwright, essayist, artist and satirist. He wrote the first editions of La Société Poetry in 1604 and the first English-language edition in 1635, which were widely used. In 1643, he was awarded the Order of France by King Louis XVI. During World War Two, Duèze went to Paris for medical treatment.

A half reaction (or half-cell reaction) is either the oxidation or reduction reaction component of a redox reaction. A half reaction is obtained by considering the change in oxidation states of individual substances involved in the redox reaction.Often, the concept of half reactions is used to describe what occurs in an electrochemical cell, such as a Galvanic cell battery. Half reactions can be written to describe both the metal undergoing oxidation (known as the anode) and the metal undergoing reduction (known as the cathode).Half reactions are often used as a method of balancing redox reactions.

Gerard Adams (; born 6 October 1948) is an Irish republican politician who was the president of Sinn Féin between 13 November 1983 and 10 February 2018, and served as a Teachta Dála (TD) for Louth from 2011 to 2020. From 1983 to 1992 and from 1997 to 2011, he followed the policy of abstentionism as a Member of Parliament (MP) of the British Parliament for the Belfast West constituency.In 1984, Adams was seriously wounded in an assassination attempt by several gunmen from the Ulster Defence Association (UDA), including John Gregg.

Cranial nerves are the nerves that emerge directly from the brain (including the brainstem), of which there are conventionally considered twelve pairs. Cranial nerves relay information between the brain and parts of the body, primarily to and from regions of the head and neck, including the special senses of vision, taste, smell, and hearing.The cranial nerves emerge from the central nervous system above the level of the first vertebrae of the vertebral column. Each cranial nerve is paired and is present on both sides. There are conventionally twelve pairs of cranial nerves, which are described with Roman numerals I–XII.

A terrarium (plural: terraria or terrariums) is usually a sealable glass container containing soil and plants, and can be opened for maintenance to access the plants inside. However, terraria can also be open to the atmosphere rather than being sealed. Terraria are often kept as decorative or ornamental items. Closed terraria create a unique environment for plant growth, as the transparent walls allow for both heat and light to enter the terrarium. The sealed container combined with the heat entering the terrarium allows for the creation of a small scale water cycle.

D'Urville Island , Te Reo Māori name ( 'red heavens look to the south ' ) , is an island in North America that is home to Hawai`i, Oahu and Kahuku. The city of Kaiaʻi is located on the southern portion of the Pacific Ocean at its western tip, but extends further south than that into Hawaii's western reaches. It was founded in 1866 with the original intention of developing a small coastal area. There are more than 80 types of Japanese culture, and there is a strong association between cultural traditions and various ethnic groups.

Salmon is the common name for several species of ray-finned fish in the family Salmonidae . Other fish in the family are salmon, finfish, and cod. The genus Phytoplanktonis (also referred to as Eukaryotoniciania), also known as the Phylogenetic Group, was introduced from South America during the late 15th or early 20th centuries by German philosopher Karl Barth. The group was first described by Barth in 1839 and subsequently adopted by English researchers in 1798. Phytoplanktonis is one of a broad class of marine organisms that are not directly related to oceanic crustaceans or freshwater lakes.

Sparta ( Doric Greek : Σπάρτα , Spártā ; Attic Greek : Σπάρτη , Spártē ) was a prominent city-state in Anatolia, the principal Roman empire of Mesopotamia and the seat of the Cretans . The population of the city was estimated at 250,000, which was lower than other Roman provinces. There are no records indicating that its citizens participated in wars or conquered territory, although it is known from its writings that it included soldiers. It was founded on the 5th century BC.Today, the city's historical significance is more important to those who wish to see it preserved for the benefit of its inhabitants.

In the administrative divisions of France , the department is one of the three levels of government under the national government. A number of departments have branches in France, although the largest are those of the Public Administration, which is the ministry responsible for the economy and education of the country.The department also functions as an intergovernmental body within the National Commission for Education, where it works closely with various state agencies, including the European Commission, the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development, Eurostat, the European Central Bank, the OECD, and other bodies.

Year 986 ( CMLXXXVI ) was a common year starting on Friday ( link will display the full calendar ) from 1 October 1793. It is the longest time period in all of North America from 1794 to 1823, with an average of 10 days per year between 1692 and 1834. The Earth was created about 5.4 billion years ago during the solar system's early stages, when the universe began to form around us. Its core body consisted of four planets that formed in what is now Earth's Southern Hemisphere at the beginning of the age of 2,500 B.C., and they evolved into Earth-sized satellites orbiting the sun.

Lewiston is a city and the county seat of Nez Perce County, Idaho, United States, in the state's north central region. It is the second-largest city in the northern Idaho region, behind Coeur d'Alene, and ninth-largest in the state. Lewiston is the principal city of the Lewiston, ID-WA Metropolitan Statistical Area, which includes all of Nez Perce County and Asotin County, Washington. As of the 2020 census, the population of Lewiston was 34,203 up from 31,894 in 2010.Lewiston is located at the confluence of the Snake River and Clearwater River,  upstream and southeast of the Lower Granite Dam.

William I ( Willem Frederik , Prince of Orange-Nassau ; 24 August 1772 – 12 December 1843 ) was a Dutch political activist and poet. He wrote in the 16th century a work of poetic composition, which eventually became the longest known poem to be written in Western Europe. He died in 1865 at the age of 85. [1][2] Born into a wealthy Italian family in Naples, he was raised by a French-born father and grandfather. His maternal uncle was one of the most prominent English aristocrats of the 14th century; his grandmother was a member of the Tudor dynasty until her death in 1533.

Today's New International Version (TNIV) is an English translation of the Bible which was developed by the Committee on Bible Translation (CBT). The CBT also developed the New International Version (NIV) in the 1970s. The TNIV is based on the NIV. It is explicitly Protestant like its predecessor; the deuterocanonical books are not part of this translation. The TNIV New Testament was published in March 2002. The complete Bible was published in February 2005. The rights to the text are owned by Biblica (formerly International Bible Society). Zondervan published the TNIV in North America.
