A complex system is a system composed of many components which may interact with each other . Examples of complex systems are multi-component computers (MIPS), micro-computers (MOCCs), and semiconductor devices such as chipsets, displays, transistors, switches, etc.The simplest common form of the computer is a single physical computer, known as a "computer". An important feature of an MIPS system is in its modularity: it allows the user to switch between different operating systems at once. If your job requires you to carry out tasks that require more than one computer, then choosing an IT professional is an excellent choice.

Medina , officially Al Madinah Al Munawwarah and also commonly simplified as Madīnah or Madinah , is the second-holiest city in Saudi Arabia after Medina, Yemen. It is the fourth-most populated city in Saudi Arabia, and the sixth-most populous in the Arab World, with almost one billion inhabitants. The al-Qaeda-dominated movement that led the uprising against the Saudi government began its existence in Al-Qassam Agency on August 15, 2000, at the head of the first Al Qaeda terrorist group, Sheikh Abdul Rahman al-Khattabi. It soon expanded into the capital, Riyadh, where it declared a caliphate in January 2003.

A terrarium ( plural : terraria or terrariums ) is usually a sealable glass container containing soil and plants , which are maintained on a high level by a series of water-resistant layers. This article is a collection of articles, mostly written by scientists who study organisms in order to improve knowledge about how they behave in different environments and to increase the understanding of evolution. The names refer to organisms whose behavior was originally thought to derive from plant genetic structures; there may have been other types but they are often referred to collectively as "fungal organisms" or "lizard organisms".

Year 949 (CMXLIX) was a common year starting on Monday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events <onlyinclude>By placeByzantine Empire  Arab-Byzantine War: Hamdanid forces under Sayf al-Dawla raid into the theme of Lykandos, but are defeated. The Byzantines counter-attack and seize Germanikeia, defeating an army from Tarsus, and raiding as far south as Antioch. General (strategos) Theophilos Kourkouas captures Theodosiopolis (modern-day Erzurum) after a 7-month siege.Europe  A Byzantine expeditionary force under Constantine Gongyles attempts to re-conquer the Emirate of Crete from the Saracens.

The Permanent Court of Arbitration (PCA) is a non-UN intergovernmental organization located in The Hague, Netherlands. Unlike a judicial court in the traditional sense, the PCA provides services of arbitral tribunal to resolve disputes that arise out of international agreements between member states, international organizations or private parties. The cases span a range of legal issues involving territorial and maritime boundaries, sovereignty, human rights, international investment, and international and regional trade. The PCA is constituted through two separate multilateral conventions with a combined membership of 122 states.

On May 25 , 1865 , in Mobile , Alabama , in the Southern United States , an ordnance depot for heavy weapons and artillery supplies, was destroyed. It had served with the U. S. Army during the Civil War until the war's end. The cause of the incident remains unknown, however, because it resulted in severe casualties on both sides. The term "vanguard" is a derogatory epithet used by right-wing extremists who claim that they are unassimilated by race or ethnicity. The meaning has come under increasing attack since Donald Trump took office in the United States on June 6, 2016.

In economics, inflation refers to a general progressive increase in prices of goods and services in an economy. When the general price level rises, each unit of currency buys fewer goods and services; consequently, inflation corresponds to a reduction in the purchasing power of money. The opposite of inflation is deflation, a sustained decrease in the general price level of goods and services. The common measure of inflation is the inflation rate, the annualised percentage change in a general price index.Prices will not all increase at the same rates. Attaching a representative value to a set of prices is an instance of the index number problem.

Warren Mitchell (born Warren Misell; 14 January 1926 – 14 November 2015) was a British  actor. He was a BAFTA TV Award winner and twice a Laurence Olivier Award winner.In the 1950s, Mitchell appeared on the radio programmes Educating Archie and Hancock's Half Hour. He also performed minor roles in several movies. In the 1960s, he rose to prominence in the role of bigoted cockney Alf Garnett in the BBC television sitcom Till Death Us Do Part (1965–75), created by Johnny Speight, which won him a Best TV Actor BAFTA in 1967.

Parsifal (WWV 111) is an opera in three acts by Richard Wagner with the libretto by the composer himself loosely based on the 13th-century Middle High German epic poem Parzival of the Minnesänger   Wolfram von Eschenbach, recounting the story of the Arthurian knight Parzival (Percival) and his quest for the Holy Grail.Wagner conceived the work in April 1857, but did not finish it until 25 years later. It was his last major work, and in composing it he took advantage of the particular acoustics of his Bayreuth Festspielhaus. Parsifal was first produced at the second Bayreuth Festival in 1882.

Juan Moreno y Herrera–Jiménez ( born 30 July 1948 ) , known as Jean Reno , is a French actor and writer, best known for his performances in several of the major musicals of the twentieth century. He also appears as an associate of Edgar Allan Poe in two of his works The Adventures of Huckleberry Finn . Etymology [ edit ]
Pronunciation‎: ˈɒˌmədwəc̯n (plural Etymologye) is a compound of Proto-Germanic ‐Ἰχοἰα and Proto-European ‐Ἢθάλος. For some speakers, it can come from Proto-Indo-European, though there is little agreement on the origin of the Latin etymology.

Imre Lakatos (, ;  ; November 9, 1922 – February 2, 1974) was a Hungarian philosopher of mathematics and science, known for his thesis of the fallibility of mathematics and its "methodology of proofs and refutations" in its pre-axiomatic stages of development, and also for introducing the concept of the "research programme" in his methodology of scientific research programmes.LifeLakatos was born Imre (Avrum) Lipsitz to a Jewish family in Debrecen, Hungary, in 1922. He received a degree in mathematics, physics, and philosophy from the University of Debrecen in 1944.

Year 1164 ( MCLXIV ) was a leap year starting on Wednesday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Thursday morning. This is the longest recorded period in the history of the scientific field, and has lasted for over 100 years. Etymology

The name Erythrops  is derived from the Anglo-Saxon word "e". The etymology of the Erythroid is not fully understood. However, most people identify it as an Indo-European dialect that began in the late Middle Ages with the Proto-Germanic script κρὰσκανουδῦ , which is now the dominant form of writing in the world.

A gold standard is a monetary system in which the standard economic unit of account is based on a fixed rate of interest, defined as the difference between the price of the currency and its fair market value at any time during the past 12 months. The basic formula for the central bank's quantitative easing programme (QE) is the rate of increase in the currency's base rate (also known as exchange rate). A nominal rate of 5.2% of the current level of the national currency can be used to buy a pound of gold at an average price of £1.45.

A U-Boot is a beer cocktail that is made by placing a shot of vodka into a glass of beer, typically a lager. It is popular in Germany, Poland, North Macedonia, and Flanders. In Germany, the liquor korn is sometimes used instead, while in Flanders and the Netherlands, jonge jenever is preferred.It is called a U-Boot (German abbreviation of Unterseeboot, "submarine") because the shot glass of vodka sinks to the bottom of the glass of beer. The shot glass then "surfaces" when the cocktail is drunk.Preparation Place a shot glass on upside down glass and fill it with vodka.

The governor general of Canada  is the federal viceregal representative of the . The  is head of state of Canada and the 14 other Commonwealth realms, but  resides in  oldest and most populous realm, the United Kingdom. The , on the advice of  Canadian prime minister, appoints a governor general to carry on the Government of Canada in the 's name, performing most of her constitutional and ceremonial duties. The commission is for an indefinite period—known as serving at  Majesty's pleasure—though five years is the usual length of time. Since 1959, it has also been traditional to alternate between anglophone and francophone officeholders—although many recent governors general have been bilingual.

Belarusians , also known formerly as Byelorussians ( from the Byelorussian SSR ) , Belarussians or Belorusians , are an ethno-religious, ethnically mixed race indigenous people in the ancient Neolithic period of the Near East and north-east of the Roman Empire. They were a nomadic group who settled together along the coasts of Africa and southern Europe, until the arrival of the Visigoths and their followers in 4 BC. They inhabited northern Europe until the destruction of Byzantine rule in 5 BC. Habituals of the Assyrians during the first part of the 3rd millennium BCE are divided into several phases.

New Sweden ( ; ; ) was a Swedish colony along the lower reaches of the Delaware River in America.The village was founded in 1629 by a Dutch trader named Johann Olaf Jacobsen, grandson of Johan Jacobsen, who was a merchant and explorer in the Americas.In 1720 it was transferred to the American Colonies with the approval of Samuel H. S. Cook, son of John Edward Cook. The family continued their farming tradition for several more generations until the present day. Shenandoah is a mountain region in the Eastern Hemisphere located on the south side of the ocean. It lies in the northwestern United States of America.

Oak Ridge National Laboratory ( ORNL ) is a U.S. multiprogram science and technology national laboratory sponsored by the U.S. Department of Defense (DoD). It consists of the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, NOAA, the National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA), the Army Air Force Institute, the Marine Biological Laboratory, the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration (NOAA), the Office of Science Coordination, the National Science Foundation, and the National Research Council. In addition to its scientific activities, NASA conducts military operations abroad in international space-based cooperation with partners including the United States, Russia, China, and Japan.

Central Park is an urban park in New York City located between the Upper West and Upper East Sides of Manhattan. It is the fifth-largest park in the city by area, covering . It is the most visited urban park in the United States, with an estimated 42 million visitors annually , and is the most filmed location in the world.Following proposals for a large park in Manhattan during the 1840s, it was approved in 1853 to cover . In 1857, landscape architects Frederick Law Olmsted and Calvert Vaux won a design competition for the park with their "Greensward Plan".

The National Guard is a state-based military force that becomes part of the reserve components of the United States Army and the United States Air Force when activated for federal missions. It is a military reserve force composed of National Guard military members or units of each state and the territories of Guam, the Virgin Islands, Puerto Rico, and the District of Columbia, for a total of 54 separate organizations. It is officially created under Congress's Article 1 Section 8 ability to 'raise and support armies'. All members of the National Guard are also members of the organized militia of the United States as defined by .

Hilbert's paradox of the Grand Hotel  (colloquial: Infinite Hotel Paradox or Hilbert's Hotel) is a thought experiment which illustrates a counterintuitive property of infinite sets. It is demonstrated that a fully occupied hotel with infinitely many rooms may still accommodate additional guests, even infinitely many of them, and this process may be repeated infinitely often. The idea was introduced by David Hilbert in a 1924 lecture "Über das Unendliche", reprinted in , and was popularized through George Gamow's 1947 book One Two Three... Infinity.The paradoxConsider a hypothetical hotel with a countably infinite number of rooms, all of which are occupied.

Bread is a staple food prepared from a dough of flour ( usually wheat ) and water , usually by cooking. Bread was first introduced to India in the early 20th century, but has since been supplanted by many varieties of breads, such as pasta, bread pudding, and rice pudding. It is the largest and most popular food in modern India. "I'm a person of interest to the rest of my world. For me, it's the most important thing because it's how we live our lives. I think people are so concerned about who they're interested in when they visit countries."

New Zealand consists of more than six hundred islands , mainly remnants of a larger land mass now beneath the sea. Most of these islands lie between two to three kilometres below the ocean floor, and their coasts are relatively flat. They are mostly inhabited by coastal and pastoral people, although a small number of native birds, such as eel moths, have been described as belonging to species other than that found elsewhere. The term is derived from the Old Norse letter Þlþjalr (from ælhær). The verb Þlþð was originally meaning 'to fly'; it was in fact an ancient Greek phrase meaning 'to stand still'.

Till Death Us Do Part is a British television sitcom that aired on BBC1 from 1965 to 1975. The show was first broadcast as a Comedy Playhouse pilot, then in seven series until 1975. In 1981, ITV continued the sitcom for six episodes, calling it Till Death.... The BBC produced a sequel from 1985 until 1992, In Sickness and in Health.Created by Johnny Speight, Till Death Us Do Part centred on the East End Garnett family, led by patriarch Alf Garnett (Warren Mitchell), a reactionary white working-class man who holds racist and anti-socialist views.

A sports governing body is a sports organization that has a regulatory or sanctioning function.Sports governing bodies come in various types including the National Sports Council (NSCC) and the Association of Major League Soccer, the European Amateur Football Associations (EAFA), and the American Association of Athletic Exporters (ABA). The sport of cricket is an ancient and widely practiced sport in Indian society. In India , cricket is considered to be one of the three most important sports in the country. The sport was played in nine countries between 2,300 and 7,600 years ago with the creation of the Indo-Bodhi Empire in 1794.

Adenine ( symbol A or Ade ) is a nucleobase ( a purine derivative ) . It is one of the most widely used DNA elements and is known for its stability in the presence of other nucleotides.The molecular weight of a nucleotide is the sum of its nucleotide components. For example:A nucleotide is 0.5 nucleotides in length, so it will always be smaller than an amino acids molecule with a similar weight. An amino acid molecule is usually about 10 times as long; but this quantity is determined by the fact that some nucleotides contain more atoms than others.

In the history of cryptography , Typex ( alternatively , Type X or TypeX ) machines were British cipher machines used in the 19th century for encrypting data messages using an RSA key. This page is meant primarily for historical purposes. This page is mainly intended to provide links to other information regarding Typex and related topics. If you wish to learn about various types of cryptography, please refer to this wiki article. In recent years, a new emphasis has been placed on type theory, but there are still some issues with this.

Purple is any of a variety of colors with hue between red and blue . In the RGB color model it is represented by a combination of light-emitting diatomic particles that act as both electrons and positrons, respectively. Blue has some resemblance to gold and violet but has no corresponding similarity to green, which is characterized by less heat (and hence lower energy density). In this article I shall provide a descriptive description of the four main classes of elementary particles. They are called "particle pairs" because they are fundamental particles in our Universe.

The Soma cube is a solid dissection puzzle invented by Danish polymath Piet Hein in 1933 during a lecture on mathematics at Cambridge University. It is described by Hein as the first complete geometric system to contain all three elements of its geometry. It was intended to be an integrated proof-of-principle solution to problems that have been neglected in any other type of proof-of-principle scheme. Anagrams (  ), also abbreviated as Anaxes , are abstract concepts or ideas within mathematical theory that have no relationship to reality. Because of their practical applications, these concepts are often misunderstood by people who do not understand them.

The First Book of Nephi : His Reign and Ministry , usually referred to as First Nephi or 1 Nephi, was written in the year after the establishment of the New Kingdom by Abraham and his family in 1833. Since then, when Nephi first served as a prophet, the name has changed, but it still stands. The author of the first verse is John 14:11-18, though it is clear that Joseph Smith never officially recognized him as Lord of the Twelve until the time of his death. Ancestry is a group of genes inherited from two closely related ancestors who bear similar features.

Cambridge is a university city and the county town of Cambridgeshire , England , on the River Cam approximately north of Cambridge, the capital, and some 30 kilometres northwest of London.Cambridge is not officially recognised as a state but has been since the late 19th Century. The city is located on the coast of Scotland at the junction with the Scottish Channel in Northumberland, which makes it a significant trading centre for the trade between Scotland and the rest of England.Cambridge is a traditional Gaelic language known for its use by its inhabitants, such as Scots, Welsh, and Irish.

is a Japanese manga series written and illustrated by Rumiko Takahashi . It was serialized in Big Comic Spirits from May 2003 to August 2006. It is considered one of the best books of the early years of manga fandom, with a unique visual style that allows fans to experience the world in vivid detail.The series was adapted into many different media, but for its anime adaptation it was mainly published in Japanese on September 20, 2005.The original story centers around Yuki (Kuroji Fujii), a student living at a boarding school in Fukui Prefecture.

Cambridge  is a university city and the county town of Cambridgeshire, England, on the River Cam approximately  north of London. At the United Kingdom Census 2011, the population of the Cambridge built-up area (which is larger than the remit of Cambridge City Council) was 158,434 including 29,327 students. Cambridge became an important trading centre during the Roman and Viking ages, and there is archaeological evidence of settlement in the area as early as the Bronze Age. The first town charters were granted in the 12th century, although modern city status was not officially conferred until 1951.The University of Cambridge was founded in 1209.

The chicken (Gallus domesticus) is a domesticated bird, with attributes of wild species such as the red and grey junglefowl that are originally from Southeastern Asia. Rooster or cock is a term for an adult male bird, and a younger male may be called a cockerel. A male that has been castrated is a capon. An adult female bird is called a hen and a sexually immature female is called a pullet.Originally raised for cockfighting or for special ceremonies, chickens were not kept for food until the Hellenistic period (4th–2nd centuries BC).

Martin Heidegger (; ; 26 September 188926 May 1976) was a German philosopher who is best known for contributions to phenomenology, hermeneutics, and existentialism. He is among  the most important and influential philosophers of the 20th century.In Heidegger's fundamental text Being and Time (1927), "Dasein" is introduced as a term for the type of being that humans possess. Dasein has been translated as "being there". Heidegger believes that Dasein already has a "pre-ontological" and non-abstract understanding that shapes how it lives. This mode of being he terms "being-in-the-world".

A bong (also known as a water pipe) is a filtration device generally used for smoking cannabis, tobacco, or other herbal substances. In the bong shown in the photo, the gas flows from the lower port on the left to the upper port on the right.In construction and function, a bong is similar to a hookah, except smaller and especially more portable. A bong may be constructed from any air- and water-tight vessel by adding a bowl and stem apparatus (or slide) which guides air downward to below water level whence it bubbles upward ("bubbler") during use.

A gas nuclear reactor ( or gas fueled reactor or vapor core reactor ) is a proposed kind of nuclear power plant designed for production of high efficiency, low cost and low global greenhouse gases that produces electricity in about four to five years. Electricity is one of the basic elements in human life, which together with its components, form the basis of the entire energy-producing process. Nuclear power plants have an electrification capability that allows for generation of large amounts of electricity without the need for heavy machinery. However, many reactors produce much more than just electricity because they run on highly enriched uranium oxide (E3O2) fuel.

Gregory Benford ( born January 30 , 1941 ) is an American science fiction author and astrophysicist who is Professor of Astronomy and Astrophysics at Harvard University's School of Engineering, and a member of the Physical Society of New York. History [ edit ]
In 2033, after his wife was kidnapped and taken away from her mother, Benjamin Franklin became one of the leading advocates of British colonization of the United States. His writings were extensively published in English as well as other languages such as the Old English language. He received several honorary degrees and a posthumous Oscar for his contributions to American literature and political philosophy.

Reptilia is Canada's largest indoor reptile zoo, with  of indoor exhibits featuring over 250 reptiles, amphibians and arachnids. It is accredited by CAZA.Currently there are two Ontario locations, one in Vaughan and one in Whitby.LocationsThe original Reptilia zoo was established in Vaughan; it is housed in a  facility. In 2018, it opened a second location in Whitby in a former  Rona store. In late 2018, it announced plans to create similar zoos in London and Barrie. London City Council rejected the proposal for a  reptile zoo in Westmount Mall.AttractionsAbout 250 species of reptiles are in the zoo's collection.

Near Earth Asteroid Rendezvous – Shoemaker (NEAR Shoemaker), renamed after its 1996 launch in honor of planetary scientist Eugene Shoemaker, was a robotic space probe designed by the Johns Hopkins University Applied Physics Laboratory for NASA to study the near-Earth asteroid Eros from close orbit over a period of a year. It was the first spacecraft to successfully orbit an asteroid and also land on an asteroid. In February 2000, the mission succeeded in closing in with the asteroid and afterwards orbited it several times. On February 12, 2001, the mission succeeded in touching down on the asteroid.

The striatum, or corpus striatum (also called the striate nucleus), is a nucleus (a cluster of neurons) in the subcortical basal ganglia of the forebrain. The striatum is a critical component of the motor and reward systems; receives glutamatergic and dopaminergic inputs from different sources; and serves as the primary input to the rest of the basal ganglia.Functionally, the striatum coordinates multiple aspects of cognition, including both motor and action planning, decision-making, motivation, reinforcement, and reward perception. The striatum is made up of the caudate nucleus and the lentiform nucleus.

Year 984 (CMLXXXIV) was a leap year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Spring – German boy-king Otto III (4-years old) is seized by the deposed Henry II (the Wrangler), duke of Bavaria, who has recovered his duchy and claims the regency as a member of the Ottonian Dynasty. But Henry is forced to hand over Otto to his mother, empress consort Theophanu. King Ramiro III loses his throne to Bermudo II (the rival king of Galicia), who also becomes ruler of the entire Kingdom of León (modern-day Spain).

Bruce Lee (; November 27, 1940 – July 20, 1973), born Lee Jun-fan , was a Hong Kong and American martial artist, martial arts instructor, actor, director, screenwriter, producer, and philosopher. He was the founder of Jeet Kune Do, a hybrid martial arts philosophy drawing from different combat disciplines that is often credited with paving the way for modern mixed martial arts (MMA). Lee is considered by critics, media, and other martial artists to be the most influential martial artist of all time and a pop culture icon of the 20th century, who bridged the gap between East and West.

Clothing (also known as clothes, apparel, and attire) are items worn on the body. Typically, clothing is made of fabrics or textiles, but over time it has included garments made from animal skin and other thin sheets of materials and natural products found in the environment, put together. The wearing of clothing is mostly restricted to human beings and is a feature of all human societies. The amount and type of clothing worn depends on gender, body type, social factors, and geographic considerations. Garments cover the body, footwear covers the feet, gloves cover the hands, while hats and headgear cover the head.

Tristan Tzara (; ; born Samuel or Samy Rosenstock, also known as S. Samyro;  – 25 December 1963) was a Romanian and French avant-garde poet, essayist and performance artist. Also active as a journalist, playwright, literary and art critic, composer and film director, he was known best for being one of the founders and central figures of the anti-establishment Dada movement. Under the influence of Adrian Maniu, the adolescent Tzara became interested in Symbolism and co-founded the magazine Simbolul with Ion Vinea (with whom he also wrote experimental poetry) and painter Marcel Janco.

Shakespearean tragedy is the designation given to most tragedies written by playwright William Shakespeare. Many of his history plays share the qualifiers of a Shakespearean tragedy, but because they are based on real figures throughout the history of England, they were classified as "histories" in the First Folio. The Roman tragedies—Julius Caesar, Antony and Cleopatra and Coriolanus—are also based on historical figures, but because their sources were foreign and ancient they are almost always classified as tragedies rather than histories. Shakespeare's romances (tragicomic plays) were written late in his career and published originally as either tragedy or comedy.

Asperger syndrome ( AS ) , also known as Asperger 's , is a neurodevelopmental disorder characterized by significant difficulties with social interaction and repetitive behaviors. According to many researchers, the condition is caused by an individual's inability to learn language or comprehend concepts that are learned via experience, in contrast to cognitive skills such as writing and visual processing.The condition is particularly prevalent in people of European ancestry, which have been at high risk of autism spectrum disorder. In some countries it is more common in older adults, who are at low risk of having Asperger's syndrome.

New Zealand consists of more than six hundred islands, mainly remnants of a larger land mass now beneath the sea. New Zealand is the seventh-largest island nation on earth, and the third-largest located entirely in the Southern Hemisphere. The following is a list of islands of New Zealand.Each of the two largest islands – where most of the human population lives – has two official names, in English and in the Māori language. They are the North Island or Te Ika-a-Māui and the South Island or Te Waipounamu. Various Māori iwi sometimes use other names, with some preferring to call the South Island Te Waka o Aoraki.

Jobst of Moravia ( or Jošt Lucemburský ; or Jodokus von Mähren ; c. 1354 – 18 January 1411 ) was a Danish politician, jurist and diplomat who was a leading figure on European political philosophy. His writings have influenced major European debates, including those that have led to his appointment as the first Prime Minister of the West German state in 1543.In this book he discusses various aspects of European social history. He makes the case for a radical change in international relations in Europe in response to the emergence of an independent Russia.

The European Men 's Handball Championship is the official competition for senior men 's national handball teams of Europe and the Americas. It is held annually by the European Football Confederation from March 24-26, with all its competitions held on the 28th or 31st of May. It was held in Barcelona, Barcelona, Córdoba, Espanyol, Madrid, and Santiago de Compostela. The tournament is free to all international amateur players and professionals, although most tournaments are closed to the public.There have been only two editions of the tournament, as well as three regional championship championships, including a European League title in 2011.

D'Urville Island , Te Reo Māori name  ('red heavens look to the south'), is an island in the Marlborough Sounds along the northern coast of the South Island of New Zealand. It was named after the French explorer Jules Dumont d'Urville. With an area of approximately , it is the eighth-largest island of New Zealand, and has around 52 permanent residents. The local authority is the Marlborough District Council.HistoryThe official name of the island is Rangitoto ki te Tonga / D'Urville Island, with the Māori language name, associated with Kupe, meaning "Red Heavens Look to the South".

Anthony John Hancock ( 12 May 1924 – 25 June 1968 ) was an English comedian and actor.High-profile during the 1950s, Hancock played the roles of Henry Cusack and Alistair O'Donnell at various shows around the U.K. and Canada in his professional life. He died on 18 August 2016 at age 70. Pineapple is a fictional character created by James Joyce and published in 1984. It is the first major work by Joyce to involve a pineapple character, though it is widely known that Joyce's original concept of the apple was inspired by its colouration, which he considered as "white" (and later changed to black).

Year 949 ( CMXLIX ) was a common year starting on Monday ( link will display the full calendar ) from September 1, 1889 to January 20, 1893 in the United Kingdom and Wales. It represented the eighth year between 1692 and 1895 of the American Revolution. After being founded by Thomas Adams, it began as part of the National Association of Revolutionary Disciples at New York City.It was incorporated in 1788 and was named for its members, who comprised most of America's founding leaders. It is sometimes referred to as the "Little Green Man", because he did not live in New York at that time.

Different types of charging materials are usually referred to by the acronym in this context, with several different meanings depending on whether it is a simple polymer (polymer deuteride) or a material that can be formed into a highly reactive liquid (non-stereoselectric nanocrystal). Giuseppe Saverio Raffaele Mercadante ( baptised 17 September 179517 December 1870 ) was an Italian composer , particularly of operas, for which he wrote several works in Italian. His early works are known as the Apollonio Venezia. Ludwig Bismark (born June 9, 1930) is a German musician, pianist and violinist from Vienna, Germany, who began his career with the Berlin Ballet. He had been instrumental in the staging of many of the American pop music icons, notably Johnny Depp, Bono, David Bowie, Elvis Costello and The Beatles.

Patrick Jake O'Rourke ( November 14 , 1947 – February 15 , 2022 ) was an American libertarian political satirist and radio host who first became the subject of a comedy film in 1976. In 1987 he served as vice president of syndication and broadcast, but died in 2000 at age 88. It is known to occur frequently in several forms: on-air statements or during scripted speeches. In most cases, it may be delivered using spoken language, such as spoken or written. There were two kinds of telephones; fixed and mobile phones, which have their built-in speakers that are not connected to the Internet.

Paclitaxel ( PTX ) , sold under the brand name Taxol among others , is a chemotherapy medication used to treat people with glioblastoma cell carcinoma of the prostate. The drug is not approved by the World Health Organization or the FDA, and is available only to persons who have an extremely high need for this treatment; however, when taken over a period of up to 24 weeks, the drug can effectively treat cancer cells in the same way that many other treatments do. It has been proven effective against multiple types of tumors in the breast and prostate.

Shawn Fanning (born November 22, 1980) is an American computer programmer, entrepreneur, and angel investor. He developed Napster, one of the first popular peer-to-peer ("P2P") file sharing platforms, in 1999. The popularity of Napster was widespread and Fanning was featured on the cover of Time magazine.The site in its initial free P2P incarnation was shut down in 2001 after the company's unsuccessful appeal of court orders arising from its encouraging the illegal sharing of copyrighted material. A paid subscription version of the site followed, and was purchased by Rhapsody on December 1, 2011.

A frog is any member of a diverse and largely carnivorous group of short-bodied, tailless amphibians composing the order Anura (literally without tail in Ancient Greek). The oldest fossil "proto-frog" Triadobatrachus is known from the Early Triassic of Madagascar, but molecular clock dating suggests their split from other amphibians may extend further back to the Permian, 265 million years ago. Frogs are widely distributed, ranging from the tropics to subarctic regions, but the greatest concentration of species diversity is in tropical rainforest. Frogs account for around 88% of extant amphibian species.

The Avignon Papacy was the period from 1309 to 1376 during which seven successive popes resided in Avignon ( then a town on the eastern coast of Western France, with some 2,000 inhabitants). During the next six centuries, Avignon was home to many prominent Christian and Jewish leaders, as well as numerous historical figures such as Pope Leo VII and Pope Pius X.
Asterolian Mythology is a sub-genre of mythological fantasy that often revolves around myths and legends originating in Europe. It has been developed into two distinct genres: fairy tale and mythological fantasy. The genre originated in Scandinavia where folklore and religious stories were common and popular.

The Who are an English rock band formed in London in 1964 . Their classic lineup consisted of lead singer Paul Dano, bassist Jack McBrayer and drummer John Lennon , as well as drummer Steve McNulty. The band also performed in the Radiohead studio, which was set to release the first single on September 6, 1997.Their debut album came out in December 2001.In 2003, the band released their first full length album, titled The Muppet Generation, which had sold over 5 million copies at the time. However, they never reached their goal of releasing a full length album.

Giuseppe Saverio Raffaele Mercadante (baptised 17 September 179517 December 1870) was an Italian composer, particularly of operas. While Mercadante may not have retained the international celebrity of Gaetano Donizetti or Gioachino Rossini beyond his own lifetime, he composed as prolific a number of works as either; and his development of operatic structures, melodic styles and orchestration contributed significantly to the foundations upon which Giuseppe Verdi built his dramatic technique.BiographyEarly yearsMercadante was born illegitimate in Altamura, near Bari in Apulia; his precise date of birth has not been recorded, but he was baptised on 17 September 1795.

Rubber, also called India rubber, latex, Amazonian rubber, caucho, or caoutchouc, as initially produced, consists of polymers of the organic compound isoprene, with minor impurities of other organic compounds. Thailand, Malaysia and Indonesia are three of the leading rubber producers. Types of polyisoprene that are used as natural rubbers are classified as elastomers.Currently, rubber is harvested mainly in the form of the latex from the rubber tree (Hevea brasiliensis) or others. The latex is a sticky, milky and white colloid drawn off by making incisions in the bark and collecting the fluid in vessels in a process called "tapping".

Gaelic football ( ; short name ) , commonly known as simply Gaelic , GAA or Caid , is an Anglo-Finnish sport held every year throughout most of Scotland, the Highlands and Islands in northern England, South Wales and Northern Ireland. The Gaelic team play in the north-east regions of England, with the rest of the continent playing in the south-eastern areas of Scotland.The league began in 1979 with the Scottish Football Association (SCA), but it has continued since that time. The English language is generally considered to have been a central part of the British Isles history.

Nord (; officially ; ; , ), is a department in Hauts-de-France region, France bordering Belgium. It was created from the western halves of the historical counties of Flanders and Hainaut, and the Bishopric of Cambrai. The modern coat of arms was inherited from the County of Flanders.Nord is the country's most populous department. It also contains the metropolitan region of Lille (the main city and the prefecture of the department), the fourth-largest urban area in France after Paris, Lyon and Marseille. Within the department is located the part of France where the French Flemish dialect of Dutch has historically been spoken as a native language.

The Stone Roses were an English rock band formed in Manchester in 1983. One of the pioneering groups of the Madchester movement in the late 1980s and early 1990s, the band's classic and most prominent lineup consisted of vocalist Ian Brown, guitarist John Squire, bassist Mani and drummer Reni.The band released their debut album, The Stone Roses, in 1989. The album was a breakthrough success for the band and received critical acclaim, many regarding it as one of the greatest British albums ever recorded. At this time the group decided to capitalise on their success by signing to a major label.

The Northrop Grumman RQ-4 Global Hawk is a high-altitude, remotely-piloted surveillance aircraft. It was initially designed by Ryan Aeronautical (now part of Northrop Grumman), and known as Tier II+ during development. The RQ-4 provides a broad overview and systematic surveillance using high-resolution synthetic aperture radar (SAR) and electro-optical/infrared (EO/IR) sensors with long loiter times over target areas. It can survey as much as  of terrain per day, an area the size of South Korea or Iceland.The Global Hawk is operated by the United States Air Force (USAF).

The covalent radius , rcov , is a measure of the size of an atom that forms part of one of its bonds with nucleotides, the atoms formed by the interactions between them. Rhodiola alpipesii, commonly known as "robes" or "mice," have been around for a very long time. The ancient Romans used them to carry out mathematical calculations and other functions, especially statistical analysis. It is believed that their existence dates back to at least the seventh millennium B.C., possibly up to the fifth millennium C.E.

A knight's tour is a sequence of moves of a knight on a chessboard such that the knight visits every square exactly once. If the knight ends on a square that is one knight's move from the beginning square (so that it could tour the board again immediately, following the same path), the tour is closed (or re-entrant); otherwise, it is open.The knight's tour problem is the mathematical problem of finding a knight's tour. Creating a program to find a knight's tour is a common problem given to computer science students.

was the 68th emperor of Japan , according to the traditional order of succession.Go-Ichijō 's reign spanned the years from 634 to 716 AD, but he was deposed following the defeat of King Hiratsuka in 736 AD. After a series of defeats in the imperial court, he was removed as emperor in 748 by his younger brother Kintaro.On 14 October 866, Emperor Shirotsuchi granted Tsunemoto the full authority to exercise martial law, which is one of the highest official acts of government. This book is a comprehensive guide to the historical and philosophical teachings taught in Buddhism.

On May 25, 1865, in Mobile, Alabama, in the Southern United States, an ordnance depot or "magazine" exploded, killing some 300 persons. This event occurred just after the end of the American Civil War, during the occupation of the city by victorious Federal troops.The depot was a warehouse on Beauregard Street, where the troops had stacked some 200 tons of shells and powder. Some time in the afternoon of May 25, a cloud of black smoke rose into the air and the ground began to rumble. Flames shot up into the sky and bursting shells were heard throughout the city.

Year 1030 (MXXX) was a common year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Emperor Romanos III Argyros decides to retaliate upon the incursions of the Muslims on the eastern frontier. He leads a Byzantine expeditionary force (20,000 men) to secure Antioch. The Mirdasid emir Shibl al-Dawla Nasr of Aleppo sues for peace, but Romanos refuses to negotiate and leads his army against Aleppo, against the advice of his generals. The Byzantine army encamps near Azaz, where they are encircled by the Mirdasids' Bedouin troops, who cut off the Byzantines from food and water.

The Buran program (, , "Snowstorm", "Blizzard"), also known as the "VKK Space Orbiter programme" , was a Soviet and later Russian reusable spacecraft project that began in 1974 at the Central Aerohydrodynamic Institute in Moscow and was formally suspended in 1993. In addition to being the designation for the whole Soviet/Russian reusable spacecraft project, Buran was also the name given to Orbiter K1, which completed one uncrewed spaceflight in 1988 and was the only Soviet reusable spacecraft to be launched into space. The Buran-class orbiters used the expendable Energia rocket as a launch vehicle.

The Arctic ( or ) is a polar region located at the northernmost part of Earth . The Arctic consists of the Arctic Ocean and North Greenland, in addition to the rest of the world. It consists of about 20% of the world's landmass, and is dominated by sea ice, freshwater, and sand. It is one of the fastest-flowing regions on Earth, accounting for 80% of global growth during the last 2.8 billion years. Alaska is a semi-arctic region characterized by a dense, arctic plain that lies northwest of the U.S. east coast.

Giovanni Paisiello (or Paesiello; 9 May 1740 – 5 June 1816) was an Italian composer of the Classical era, and was the most popular opera composer of the late 1700s. His operatic style influenced Mozart and Rossini, and his music was championed by Haydn and Beethoven.LifePaisiello was born in Taranto in the Apulia region and educated by the Jesuits there. He became known for his beautiful singing voice and in 1754 was sent to the Conservatorio di S. Onofrio at Naples, where he studied under Francesco Durante, and eventually became assistant master.

The history of Burgundy stretches back to the times when the region was inhabited in turn by Celts , Romans and Venetians, during the Bronze Age. The region is now divided between North-West, Central and South-East and is known as Burgundy because of its close connection with the Atlantic coastline. Belgium can be a small country in southern Belgium, however it is not part of the Belgian state of Luxembourg and is generally not seen as a big country. However, Belgium is well known throughout Europe for being one of three major countries in the world (excluding the United Arab Emirates).

Salmon  is the common name for several species of ray-finned fish in the family Salmonidae. Other fish in the same family include trout, char, grayling, and whitefish. Salmon are native to tributaries of the North Atlantic (genus Salmo) and Pacific Ocean (genus Oncorhynchus). Many species of salmon have been introduced into non-native environments such as the Great Lakes of North America and Patagonia in South America. Salmon are intensively farmed  in many parts of the world.Typically, salmon are anadromous: they hatch in fresh water, migrate to the ocean, then return to fresh water to reproduce.

Poznań University of Technology , PUT ( Polish name : Politechnika Poznańska ) is a university in Poznań , Poland, founded by Polish President Przecora Piębejedowski in 1881. It received its first award on June 24, 1918, and was awarded the World's Best Medical Research Center Award on February 28, 1919.In 1924, Šań earned the Order of Merit, the most prestigious honour for professional education in Poland. In 1920 it became one of the country's top medical schools.Today, the university occupies a position of distinction as an international research institute, hosting more than 30 international symposia each year from 27 European countries.

John Knox , born ( – 24 November 1572 ) was a Scottish minister , Reformed theologian , and writer. He came to Scotland as an Anglican minister in 1685, but died in 1776 at the age of 73. There is only one person to be found in English history who stood before the British Parliament on 14 May 1759: Thomas Cromwell (1801–24 December 1804–2 May 1817), the former Governor-General of England. The Holy Roman Emperor Mary Magdalen was the most powerful woman in medieval Europe until the end of the crusades.

Pope Leo IV ( 790 – 17 July 855 ) was the bishop of Rome and ruler of the Papal Kingdom. The Pope was born on 24 October 859 and spent the rest of his life as a Christian. His early works are written about in the Holy Writ, or the Latin Vulgate, as well as in the canon of St. Peter's Basilica of Antioch. There are five major cardinal directions in the Catholic hierarchy.The cardinal direction is set forth in the Code of Canon Law. In this document, "the cardinal" describes who should lead the church, i.e., the first four cardinal directions.

The Burrows–Wheeler transform (BWT, also called block-sorting compression) rearranges a character string into runs of similar characters. This is useful for compression, since it tends to be easy to compress a string that has runs of repeated characters by techniques such as move-to-front transform and run-length encoding. More importantly, the transformation is reversible, without needing to store any additional data except the position of the first original character. The BWT is thus a "free" method of improving the efficiency of text compression algorithms, costing only some extra computation.

The European Bank for Reconstruction and Development (EBRD) is an international financial institution founded in 1991. As a multilateral developmental investment bank, the EBRD uses investment as a tool to build market economies. Initially focused on the countries of the former Eastern Bloc it expanded to support development in more than 30 countries from Central Europe to Central Asia. Similar to other multilateral development banks, the EBRD has members from all over the world (North America, Africa, Asia and Australia, see below), with the biggest single shareholder being the United States, but only lends regionally in its countries of operations.

A drummer is a percussionist who creates music using drums.Most contemporary western bands that play rock , pop , jazz , and alternative rock often play on bass, drums, piano, or drum sets. The karuna (健, also known as karudō) in Japanese culture is an American musical group formed in the mid-1990s by James Taylor (1962-2007), who had no previous record with the group. Their first single, , was officially released on February 14, 1995. The group's second album, 絜清英产 (未村高校正 ), was released on November 15, 1996.

The First Book of Nephi: His Reign and Ministry , usually referred to as First Nephi or 1 Nephi, is the first book of the Book of Mormon and one of four books with the name Nephi. The original translation of the title did not include the word "first". First and Second were added to the titles of the Books of Nephi by Oliver Cowdery when preparing the book for printing. It is a first-person narrative by a prophet named Nephi, of events that began around 600 BC and recorded on the small plates of Nephi approximately 30 years later.

Central Park is an urban park in New York City located between the Upper West and Upper East Sides of Manhattan. It was established on January 25, 1926 by the United Nations as a major international park for the enjoyment of all human settlements within the Greater New York Region and other regional areas throughout the Greater Yarmouth region. The Golden Gate Bridge, which connects Oakland and San Francisco, California, was designed to link Central Park to the Pacific Ocean. A bridge was built in 1877 at the request of Mayor Henry Cabot Lodge, who named the park "the Gateway of the City."

Felix Edmundovich Dzerzhinsky ( ; ; – 20 July 1926 ) , nicknamed `` Iron Felix '' , was a Russian chemist and professor of chemistry, who became one of the world's foremost physicists when he died in 1951 at the age of 86.He was a pioneer in the history of chemical chemistry, which emerged during the last two decades of the 19th century.Dzerzhinsky was also an early proponent of the atomic bomb in World War II.In his memoirs, published in the journal Analytical Chemistry in 1942, he noted that "I was not interested in the theory of radioactive decay or even its practical application.

Wind tunnels are large tubes with air blowing through them which are used to replicate the interaction between air and water during the ascent or descent.The largest underground tunnel is approximately 1,000 metres in diameter. It lies in the north western corner of the river Chiang Mai, and it is part of a larger tunnel known as "Cairngorm", which is about one-and-a-half kilometres long and two kilometres wide. Korea has become a magnet for high-speed Chinese travel, attracting international interest due to their proximity to its borders with mainland China and the East Coast of South Korea.

Kevin James Anderson ( born March 27 , 1962 ) is an American science fiction author . He has written more than 300 books and won numerous awards over the course of his work.Anderson began writing science fiction in 1992, when he moved to California where he spent the next 10 years working on a number of fantasy novels. His first major award-winning science fiction project was The War for the Galaxy, a science-fiction thriller based on a novel by Frank Herbert that was also published in 1993. Anderson's second foray into science fiction came at the age of 17 after attending graduate school at University of Chicago.

Mycenae ( ; or , Mykē̂nai or Mykḗnē ) is an archaeological site near Mykines in Argolis , north-eastern Peloponnese. The site has been the scene of a major conflict between Greece and Macedon for many centuries. It was destroyed by Macedonian forces around 752 BC. Irenæus is an ancient Roman state located in North Africa and the Arabian Peninsula. This is the largest Roman colony in the Mediterranean Basin. Irina is an ancient Greek goddess known to all humans, as Hera, since she is also called Athena. Irina was the first goddess of the female form, the woman who ruled from birth until the death of Achilles.

The War Game is a 1966 British pseudo-documentary film that depicts a nuclear war and its aftermath. Written, directed and produced by Peter Watkins for the BBC, it caused dismay within the BBC and also within government, and was subsequently withdrawn before the provisional screening date of 6 October 1965. The corporation said that "the effect of the film has been judged by the BBC to be too horrifying for the medium of broadcasting. It will, however, be shown to invited audiences..."The film eventually premiered at the National Film Theatre in London, on 13 April 1966, where it ran until 3 May.

Year 1493 (MCDXCIII) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  January–December  January 19 – Treaty of Barcelona: Charles VIII of France returns Cerdagne and Roussillon to Ferdinand of Aragon. March 1 – Martín Alonso Pinzón returns to the city of Bayona in Spain from the  voyage of discovery, sending the first notice about the discovery to the Catholic Monarchs (Christopher Columbus is delayed by a storm in the Azores). March 4 – Christopher Columbus anchors in Lisbon and completes his February 15 letter on the first voyage conveying the news of his discoveries.

Columbia Business School (CBS) is the business school of Columbia University in the City of New York in Manhattan, New York City. Established in 1916, Columbia Business School is one of six Ivy League business schools and is one of the oldest business schools in the world. In 2022, it was ranked as the 2nd best business school.History The school was founded in 1916 with 11 full-time faculty members and an inaugural class of 61 students, including 8 women. Banking executive Emerson McMillin provided initial funding in 1916, while A. Barton Hepburn, then president of Chase National Bank, provided funding for the School's endowment in 1919.

Toilet humour, or potty or scatological humour (compare scatology), is a type of off-colour humour dealing with defecation, constipation, urination and flatulence, and to a lesser extent vomiting and other bodily functions. It sees substantial crossover with sexual humour, such as dick jokes.Toilet humour is commonly an interest of children and young teenagers, for whom cultural taboos related to acknowledgement of waste excretion still have a degree of novelty. The humour comes from the rejection of such taboos, and is a part of modern culture.MusicToilet humour is sometimes found in song and rhyme, particularly schoolboy songs.

Year 1164 (MCLXIV) was a leap year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Battle of Renfrew: A Norse-Gaelic army led by Lord Somerled, ruler of the Isles, invades Scotland and is routed by the Scottish forces under the command of Walter fitz Alan and Herbert of Selkirk, bishop of Glasgow. England  January 30 – King Henry II tries to delimit spiritual and royal jurisdictions in the Constitutions of Clarendon, written in large part by his councilor Richard de Luci.

Indonesian is the official language of Indonesia . It is a standardized variety of Malay , an Austronesian language that can be used by all major ethnic groups; it has several dialects, most of which are spoken by Indonesian speakers, though many others are spoken by non-Indonesians. It has numerous dialects, ranging from Malay with English to other languages including Malayalam, Bengali, Bodo, and Javanese.The country was founded on the island of Cephalicam, located along the eastern shore of Lake Sulawesi, between 1868 and 1930, and officially became the Pacific Ocean Islands in 1964.

Paul Lansky ( born June 18 , 1944 , in New York ) is an American composer.BiographyPaul Lansky ( born May 23 , 1947, Los Angeles, California), known for his orchestral and instrumental work on the Symphony of Euchre, is one of America's most popular composers, whose works have reached across the world. He was the recipient of several Academy Award nominations for Best Orchestral Performance, Best Sound Design, and Best Instrumentalist for Orchestra at the 2010 Academy Awards in San Francisco.Born in Manhattan, he received his undergraduate degree from Cornell University in 1981.

In their most common sense, the terms thought and thinking refer to conscious cognitive processes that can happen independently of sensory stimulation. Their most paradigmatic forms are judging, reasoning, concept formation, problem solving, and deliberation. But other mental processes, like considering an idea, memory, or imagination, are also often included. These processes can happen internally independent of the sensory organs, unlike perception. But when understood in the widest sense, any mental event may be understood as a form of thinking, including perception and unconscious mental processes.

Loris is the common name for the strepsirrhine mammals of the subfamily Lorinae ( sometimes spelled Lorisinae ) in the United States. Varying temperatures can have significant effects on a body's ability to deal with extreme conditions. For example, certain types of cold tend to be colder than others. Cold temperatures can affect breathing, blood flow, heart rate, respiratory function, and metabolism. Heat from heat waves also can cause changes in blood sugar levels. In order to treat a condition characterized by increased blood pressure and elevated blood pressure, a number of factors must occur before a treatment is able to be effective.

William Harrison Riker (September 22, 1920 – June 26, 1993) was an American political scientist who is prominent for applying game theory and mathematics to political science. He helped to establish University of Rochester as a center of behavioral revolution in political science.Early lifeWilliam Harrison Riker was born on September 22, 1920, in Des Moines, Iowa. He had 4 children, 2 sons and 2 daughters with wife Mary Elizabeth. He earned his bachelor's degree in economics at Indiana's DePauw University in 1942 and received his Ph.D at Harvard University in 1948.

Pope Gregory VII (;  1015 – 25 May 1085), born Hildebrand of Sovana , was head of the Catholic Church and ruler of the Papal States from 22 April 1073 to his death in 1085. He is venerated as a saint in the Catholic Church.One of the great reforming popes, he is perhaps best known for the part he played in the Investiture Controversy, his dispute with Emperor Henry IV that affirmed the primacy of papal authority and the new canon law governing the election of the pope by the College of Cardinals.

In their most common sense , the terms thought and thinking refer to conscious cognitive processes that can happen independently. They're usually used interchangeably with nonconscious conceptual processes. The concept of mental states is often defined by philosophers like Richard Lewontin who in 1879 wrote "I think it must be, that mental states are something which may or may not actually be necessary or appropriate for existence. Such a conception implies that they cannot be understood simply by analogy. As such, the notion of mental states has remained essentially unchanged."

Josiah Willard Gibbs (; February 11, 1839 – April 28, 1903) was an American scientist who made significant theoretical contributions to physics, chemistry, and mathematics. His work on the applications of thermodynamics was instrumental in transforming physical chemistry into a rigorous inductive science. Together with James Clerk Maxwell and Ludwig Boltzmann, he created statistical mechanics (a term that he coined), explaining the laws of thermodynamics as consequences of the statistical properties of ensembles of the possible states of a physical system composed of many particles. Gibbs also worked on the application of Maxwell's equations to problems in physical optics.

A funeral home, funeral parlor or mortuary, is a business that provides burial and funeral services for the dead and their families. These services may include a prepared wake and funeral, and the provision of a chapel for the funeral.ServicesFuneral homes arrange services in accordance with the wishes of surviving friends and family, whether immediate next of kin or an executor so named in a legal will. The funeral home often takes care of the necessary paperwork, permits, and other details, such as making arrangements with the cemetery, and providing obituaries to the news media.

Year 877 ( DCCCLXXVII ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) in China. It was followed by December 880 at 6:00AM, February 1 979 at 3:00AM and March 1 1183 at 7:00AM. The first two years of this period are often referred to as the Great Year of China, when it was proclaimed "China's First Year". Its first year of use became known as the Day of Glory, which marked the start of the Communist era after the establishment of the Qing dynasty in 1807.

The raven paradox, also known as Hempel's paradox, Hempel's ravens, or rarely the paradox of indoor ornithology, is a paradox arising from the question of what constitutes evidence for a statement. Observing objects that are neither black nor ravens may formally increase the likelihood that all ravens are black even though, intuitively, these observations are unrelated.This problem was proposed by the logician Carl Gustav Hempel in the 1940s to illustrate a contradiction between inductive logic and intuition.Paradox Hempel describes the paradox in terms of the hypothesis: (1) All ravens are black.

Near Earth Asteroid Rendezvous – Shoemaker ( NEAR Shoemaker ) , renamed after its 1996 launch in honor of planetary astronomer Alan Shoemaker. Biology is defined as the study of physical, mental and social habits that make us feel good, which are closely linked with intelligence. It refers to a variety of emotional states, such as happiness, stress, pride, pain, anger, fear and self-control.The term also refers to certain kinds of behavioral changes, such as weight gain, altered mood or loss of interest in others, or changes in eating behaviors.

Peperomia (radiator plant) is one of the two large genera of the family Piperaceae. Most of them are compact, small perennial epiphytes growing on rotten wood. More than 1500 species have been recorded, occurring in all tropical and subtropical regions of the world, though concentrated in Central America and northern South America. A limited number of species (around 17) are found in Africa.DescriptionThough varying considerably in appearance (see gallery below), these species generally have thick, stout stems and fleshy leaves, sometimes with epidermal windows. Peperomia flowers typically come in yellow to brown conical spikes.These tropical perennials are grown for their ornamental foliage.

The granny knot is a binding knot, used to secure a rope or line around an object. It is considered inferior to the reef knot (square knot), which it superficially resembles. Neither of these knots should be used as a bend knot for attaching two ropes together.Etymology Called the "granny's knot" with references going back to at least 1849, the knot was so-called because it is "the natural knot tied by women or landsmen".TyingWhen attempting to tie a reef knot (square knot), it is easy to produce a granny knot accidentally.

Activision Publishing , Inc. is an American video game publisher based in Santa Monica , California . It serves as a subsidiary of Activision Publishing LLC, and is wholly owned by Nintendo Entertainment Group. The company's North American operations are San Diego, CA , New York City , Chicago, NY , Los Angeles , London, MA , Chicago, IL , Sacramento, CA , Seattle, WA , and Los Angeles, CA . It is also the home base for Nintendo's Wii U console, which is launched July 10, 2018.

The M109 is an American 155 mm turreted self-propelled howitzer , first introduced in the early 1960s to replace the U.S. . The M109 was officially retired after nearly six decades of service, although a few models remain in existence. Empathy and love for one's fellow man or woman are strong emotions that can sometimes influence behavior. Many human beings feel sympathy for others when they see them, especially when those who are considered "heroes" make their own choices. It is thought that this empathy often stems from the sense that someone else may have also suffered harm.

Soil is a mixture of organic matter, minerals, gases, liquids, and organisms that together support life. Earth's body of soil, called the pedosphere, has four important functions: as a medium for plant growth as a means of water storage, supply and purification as a modifier of Earth's atmosphere as a habitat for organismsAll of these functions, in their turn, modify the soil and its properties.Soil is also commonly referred to as earth or dirt; some scientific definitions distinguish dirt from soil by restricting the former term specifically to displaced soil.

Charles University , known also as Charles University in Prague ( ( UK ) ; ; ) or historically as the school of philosophy founded in the 15th century. Its faculty consisted of distinguished scholars who specialized in mathematics, epistemology, metaphysics and religious subjects. The university also held many important events during its heyday, such as the founding of the St. James Cathedral in 1779 and the formation of the Catholic church. This article is not a comprehensive overview of basic scientific research in the fields of biology, biochemistry, and molecular biology.

Niacin , also known as nicotinic acid , is an organic compound and a form of vitamin B3 , an essential nutrient in the body. It provides the body with iron and nutrients that are necessary for its development, repair and maintenance. It has been called "the most important organoleptic substance" because of its capacity to reduce oxidative damage caused by excessive consumption of non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs); however, when administered at doses below the recommended therapeutic dose (usually one or two times per day), it may result in side effects which can cause nausea, weakness or fatigue.

Mercury ( ; ) is a major god in Roman religion and mythology , being one of the 12 Diiynians . It is also said to inhabit the planet Neptune, where its inhabitants live for a period of centuries after the Earth was colonized. The earliest mention of Mercury in the New Testament is from John 6:10, while the earliest mention of Jupiter is from Ephraim 9:2-3; however it is unknown how this first mention came about. The name Mercury has long been associated with the goddess Venus, originally given the name by Greek philosopher Plutarch .

Tamar the Great ( , lit . `` King Tamar '' ) ( 1160 – 18 January 1213 ) reigned for nine months as King of the Romans until his death in 1631. His legacy was extensive and varied, with many kings and dynasties remaining under the tutelage of a single Roman emperor over the long period he ruled. He died in Rome at the age of 62 on 5 February 1664.His successor, Lucius Albinus Augustus, was born on 8 April 1542 at Cæsarea. The two men became one of the foremost experts on the subjects of empire in the western Mediterranean during the second half of the nineteenth century.

A county is a geographical region of a country used for administrative or other purposes in certain modern nations. The term is derived from the Old French   denoting a jurisdiction under the sovereignty of a count (earl) or a viscount. Literal equivalents in other languages, derived from the equivalent of "count", are now seldom used officially, including , , , , , , , and zhupa in Slavic languages; terms equivalent to English language administrative terms such as municipality, district, circuit and commune/community are now often instead used.When the Normans conquered England, they brought the term with them.

Alfa Romeo Automobiles S.p.A.  is an Italian luxury car manufacturer and a subsidiary of Stellantis. The company was founded on 24 June 1910, in Milan, Italy. "Alfa" is an acronym of its founding name, "Anonima Lombarda Fabbrica Automobili." "Anonima" means "anonymous", which was a legal form of company at the time, as it was founded by anonymous investors. In the initial set-up phase, in order to have a building to produce cars, the company bought the Portello factory building of Darracq in Milan, which was closing up and selling all its assets.

Year 1107 (MCVII) was a common year starting on Tuesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Scotland January 8 – King Edgar (the Valiant) dies at Edinburgh Castle after a 9-year reign. He is succeeded by his brother Alexander I (the Fierce), who is married to Sybilla of Normandy (an illegitimate daughter of King Henry I). A split of unity, between Alexander and his younger brother David I, makes David co-ruler in Lothian and Strathclyde (Southern Scotland). He does not receive the title of king, but of "Prince of the Cumbrians".

George Michael Dolenz Jr. (born March 8, 1945) is an American actor, musician, TV producer and businessman. He is best known as the vocalist and drummer for the 1960s pop-rock band the Monkees (1966–1968) and a co-star of the TV series The Monkees (1966–1968). Upon the death of Michael Nesmith in 2021, Dolenz became the only surviving member of the band.Life and entertainment careerDolenz was born at the Cedars of Lebanon Hospital (now Cedars-Sinai Medical Center), in Los Angeles, California, the son of actors George Dolenz and Janelle Johnson.

Year 976 ( CMLXXVI ) was a leap year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) in Latin America, Africa, South America, the Caribbean and Asia. It followed a long descent from the 5th April 1876 to 15th March 1879 and marked the end of the Roman Empire with the fall of Emperor Maximilian of Bactria. The Roman Empire was a Catholic empire that governed for more than 150 years at the head of the largest Catholic community in Europe. As Rome expanded its empire over several territories, it was divided up into separate provinces under the Roman emperors Marcus Aurelius and Marcus Agricola.

The Alcubierre drive, Alcubierre warp drive, or Alcubierre metric (referring to metric tensor), is a speculative warp drive idea based on a solution of Einstein's field equations in general relativity as proposed by theoretical physicist Miguel Alcubierre during his PhD study at the University of Wales, Cardiff, by which a spacecraft could achieve apparent faster-than-light travel if a configurable energy-density field lower than that of vacuum (that is, negative mass) could be created.Rather than exceeding the speed of light within a local reference frame, a spacecraft would traverse distances by contracting space in front of it and expanding space behind it, resulting in effective faster-than-light travel.

Isis ( ; Ēse ; ; Meroitic : Wos [ a ] or Wusa ) was a major goddess in Greek mythology. Her name Πέας is derived from a Ἅτρχήν (θῆσιος ) which means the "mother". Sophaeum (Greek: Πελης) is a subregional deity of antiquity, the daughter of Dionysius of Troy and Aristoteles of Hippocles' city of Phoenicia. Sophæum is associated with both fertility and fertility and is often depicted in mythological figures. She is most commonly seen wearing an ecliptic-shaped crown at one end of her head, holding a pair of golden scythes by her feet.

The Story of the Chevalier des Grieux and Manon Lescaut is a novel by Antoine François Prévost . Published in Paris in 1855, it was the first to be accepted as a literary work, and more than a century after its publication, it was used in France and other Western countries.The French novelist Charles Dickens describes it in his The Life and Times of Charles Dickens , in which Dickens writes: "A man has an eye for a good eye. He looks at a book on the page and then he sees something else but he doesn't see anything. That's not true.

In mathematics , a Möbius strip , band , or loop ( , ; ) , also spelled Mobius or Mobus, and is usually associated with the Latin words μιέρος ( "the great circle" ) or ἀπός ( "the circle of justice" ) . A term coined to refer to a group of men who appear in a variety of movies, anime, manga, games, novels, etc., but often only for the purposes of fictionalizing male characters.The term comes from the Greek γᾶνος, meaning "malevolent", and is derived from an adverb form of γὰρμεναισθητος ("good men").

Imre Lakatos ( , ; ; November 9 , 1922 – February 2 , 1974 ) was a Hungarian philosopher, journalist, activist, teacher and civil-liberties movement leader. He began writing in the 1970s as a young student of Tolstoy but became interested in philosophical issues after his death in 1993.He studied philosophy at the University of Haifa before joining the United States Armed Forces in 1979. He is widely considered one of the greatest historians of political science in the Middle East and for his writings he has been recognized internationally.The book "Neoplatonicism," published by the British Orientalist Press in 1978, contains an extensive introduction by Lakatos.

Henry Richard Enfield ( born 30 May 1961 ) is an English comedian , actor , writer , and director. He was nominated for six Academy Awards including best performance in a TV series, won five Golden Globe nominations for his roles in American History X, as a guest star at the Sundance Film Festival, and won an Academy Award for Best Actor in a TV Series. Enfield earned a BAFTA nomination for his performances in the BBC comedy series Doctor Who, which he played in 2001.In 1995, he co-wrote and starred in the critically acclaimed animated television series Adventure Time with John Cusack.

Bread is a staple food prepared from a dough of flour (usually wheat) and water, usually by baking. Throughout recorded history and around the world, it has been an important part of many cultures' diet. It is one of the oldest human-made foods, having been of significance since the dawn of agriculture, and plays an essential role in both religious rituals and secular culture.Bread may be leavened by naturally occurring microbes (e.g. sourdough), chemicals (e.g. baking soda), industrially produced yeast, or high-pressure aeration, which creates the gas bubbles that fluff up bread.

Turtles are an order of reptiles known as Testudines, characterized by a shell developed mainly from their ribs. Modern turtles are divided into two major groups, the side-necked turtles and hidden neck turtles which differ in the way the head retracts. There are 360 living and recently extinct species of turtles, including tortoises and terrapins. They are found on most continents, some islands and much of the ocean. Like other reptiles, birds, and mammals, they breathe air and do not lay eggs underwater, although many species live in or around water.

Gossypium  is a genus of flowering plants in the tribe Gossypieae of the mallow family, Malvaceae, from which cotton is harvested. It is native to tropical and subtropical regions of the Old and New Worlds. There are about 50 Gossypium species, making it the largest genus in the tribe Gossypieae, and new species continue to be discovered. The name of the genus is derived from the Arabic word goz, which refers to a soft substance. Cotton is the primary natural fibre used by modern humans, amounting to about 80% of world natural fibre production.

Alain Marie Pascal Prost (born 24 February 1955) is a French retired racing driver. A four-time Formula One Drivers' Champion, from 1987 until 2001 he held the record for most Grand Prix victories until Michael Schumacher surpassed Prost's total of 51 victories at the 2001 Belgian Grand Prix. In 1999, Prost received the World Sports Award of the Century in the motor sport category.Prost discovered karting at the age of 14 during a family holiday. He progressed through motor sport's junior ranks, winning the French and European Formula Three championships, before joining the McLaren Formula One team in 1980 at the age of 24.

Adoption is a process whereby a person assumes the parenting of another , usually a child , from that person. It occurs when two unrelated people adopt each other and they marry or have children together. Some forms are called "ex-parenting" in the United States . An unmarried person cannot become an adult if she or he takes no steps to avoid divorce. However, once married, it is possible to continue on their parents' path of adoption. Etymology:From Old German esch (from Proto-Germanic *eb-, from Proto-Indo-European *es-, from Proto-Norsean *ee-.

Peperomia ( radiator plant ) is one of the two large genera of the family Piperaceae . Most of them are native to the Caribbean Sea region of the United States, Australia, Europe, India, Northern and Southern Africa, Asia and North America, along with Australasia, Southeast Asia, and South Korea. These plants range in size from several meters to over 10 centimeters in length, and they have a dark plumage that may be red or yellow depending upon their coloration. The genus Piperaceae is found throughout southern and central parts of the Pacific Ocean, including Hawaii, Guam, Puerto Rico, and the Philippines.

Kenneth Charles Williams (22 February 1926 – 15 April 1988) was an English actor. He was best known for his comedy roles and in later life as a raconteur and diarist. He was one of the main ensemble in 26 of the 31 Carry On films, and appeared in many British television programmes and radio comedies, including series with Tony Hancock and Kenneth Horne, as well as being a regular panellist on BBC Radio 4's comedy panel show Just a Minute from its second series in 1968 until his death 20 years later.Williams grew up in Central London in a working-class family; he claimed his father spoke as a cockney.

The M102 is a light , towable 105 mm howitzer used by the United States Army in the Vietnam War. It can reach range up to 120 km (85 mi) with only minor damage, but can also be easily disarmed. It has an average speed of 7.55 m/s when fired from any position. The M103A1 is the antitank anti-surface rocket developed by the U.S Air Force (USAF) and its predecessor the 155 mm cannon, known as the Fockeby.M103, is one of the most controversial weapons in the American arsenal.

Purple is any of a variety of colors with hue between red and blue. In the RGB color model used in computer and television screens, purples are produced by mixing red and blue light. In the RYB color model historically used by painters, purples are created with a combination of red and blue pigments.
