In the CMYK color model used in printing, purples are made by combining magenta pigment with either cyan pigment, black pigment, or both.Purple has long been associated with royalty, originally because Tyrian purple dye, made from crushed shells, was extremely expensive in antiquity.

Hex is a two player abstract strategy board game in which players attempt to connect opposite sides of a hexagonal board. Hexes are divided into four squares, each numbered 4. The square is arranged on the edge of the board with a diagonal line extending downward from the center and down toward the end of the board. Players move through the hexagonal space by pressing either a left or right key. Each player selects his/her number of hexes that will result in the victory of their opponent. While players can move about the hexagon at various speeds, only the most powerful moves are possible.

A verb  is a word (part of speech) that in syntax conveys an action (bring, read, walk, run, learn), an occurrence (happen, become), or a state of being (be, exist, stand). In the usual description of English, the basic form, with or without the particle to, is the infinitive. In many languages, verbs are inflected (modified in form) to encode tense, aspect, mood, and voice. A verb may also agree with the person, gender or number of some of its arguments, such as its subject, or object.

The Magic Flute (German: , ), K. 620, is an opera in two acts by Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart to a German libretto by Emanuel Schikaneder. The work is in the form of a Singspiel, a popular form during the time it was written that included both singing and spoken dialogue. The work premiered on 30 September 1791 at Schikaneder's theatre, the Freihaus-Theater auf der Wieden in Vienna, just two months before the composer's premature death. Still a staple of the opera repertory, its popularity was reflected by two immediate sequels, Peter Winter's Das Labyrinth oder Der Kampf mit den Elementen.

A political prisoner is someone imprisoned for their political activity . The political offense is not always the official reason, but it may be considered in some cases. Political prisoners are a group of individuals or organizations whose membership and affiliations are governed by special rules concerning their political activities. They operate as political groups within countries such as Afghanistan, Albania, Central African Republic, Egypt, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Tajikistan, Sudan, South Sudan, and Uzbekistan. Members are expected to take responsibility for executing their political crimes, including those which they have been convicted of.

The Hippocratic Oath is an oath of ethics historically taken by physicians . It is one of the most widely-held beliefs in ancient Greece, as it holds that any individual who is capable of achieving a certain level of medical knowledge is qualified to teach and perform clinical medicine. For the past few months, I've written a blogpost about my thoughts on some of the major philosophical changes in modern philosophy, which has led me to re-evaluate why they're so hard to understand. I'll briefly present some of what I'm thinking about in that vein.

Flavius Odoacer ( ; – 493 AD ) , also spelled Odovacer or Odovacar , was a soldier and statesman who served with the Italian resistance during the Battle of Sicily, which led to the outbreak of the Italian occupation of Sicily in the Second Crusade. He was born on 8 November 1864 in Lonsdale, Middlesex county, Kent. He later studied at Leinster University and Oxford University.After graduating from Oxford University he went on to attend the Royal Military College for Arms and Swords in London where he was called into service as a swordsman and swordsman-for-hire.

Footwear refers to garments worn on the feet , which typically serves the purpose of protection against adversities of the wearer.The term includes a wide variety of styles of accessories, footwear, gaiters, trimmeries, dressmakers, and personal protective equipment (PPI) . The most commonly known style is t-shirt, which is made up of two different designs in three sizes ranging from the standard 5 inch (2/3″) to the mini 4.5 inch (4/6″). A short skirt or jacket may also be added, but only as long as the wearer does not carry a bra.

In the history of cryptography, Typex (alternatively, Type X or TypeX) machines were British cipher machines used from 1937. It was an adaptation of the commercial German Enigma with a number of enhancements that greatly increased its security. The cipher machine (and its many revisions) was used until the mid-1950s when other more modern military encryption systems came into use.DescriptionLike Enigma, Typex was a rotor machine. Typex came in a number of variations, but all contained five rotors, as opposed to three or four in the Enigma.

KFC (also known as Kentucky Fried Chicken) is an American fast food restaurant chain headquartered in Louisville, Kentucky that specializes in fried chicken. It is the world's second-largest restaurant chain (as measured by sales) after McDonald's, with 22,621 locations globally in 150 countries . The chain is a subsidiary of Yum! Brands, a restaurant company that also owns the Pizza Hut, Taco Bell and WingStreet chains.KFC was founded by Colonel Harland Sanders, an entrepreneur who began selling fried chicken from his roadside restaurant in Corbin, Kentucky during the Great Depression.

An anti-tank guided missile ( ATGM ) , anti-tank missile , anti-tank guided weapon ( ATGW ) or anti-armor guided missile ( ATGM ) has been developed and marketed as a highly versatile ballistic missile. In its early days, there was considerable debate over whether or not a missile that could be deployed from the U.S.-based Ballistic Missile Defense System (BMD) was capable of killing an enemy air force with ease, but several countries still wanted to deploy them at the time.In 2007, a group of experts formed the Joint Air-Ground Combat Squadron (JAMSC), whose first operational role was to provide guidance to the U.S.-based AASM.

In combinatorics and in experimental design , a Latin square is an n × n array filled with n different values. The N matrix represents the set of integer integers that comprise a given array. This matrix is then constructed using the following form:
N x Y = (n − 2*x) ; if n is zero, y is equal to 1; otherwise -n is equal to zero. Each value of the matrix is associated with a unique element called its index. The first element is the root of all elements, and the second is any element within that index.

George Catlett Marshall Jr.  (December 31, 1880 – October 16, 1959) was an American army officer and statesman. He rose through the United States Army to become Chief of Staff under Presidents Franklin D. Roosevelt and Harry S. Truman, then served as Secretary of State and Secretary of Defense under Truman. Winston Churchill lauded Marshall as the "organizer of victory" for his leadership of the Allied victory in World War II. After the war, he spent a frustrating year trying and failing to avoid the impending civil war in China.

Genus ( plural genera ) is a taxonomic rank used in the biological classification of living and fossil organisms as belonging to a specific family, etymologically speaking, that includes many species of vertebrate, mammal, plant, and animal. The genus comprises over 80 genera from the genera Ptolemae to Vermicula, together with a few rare families of genera Coccidioides and Sphenogonium. It is composed of 19 distinct genera, ranging in size from about one thousand to approximately one hundred times larger than the other four genera, most of which share common ancestors. Genes belong to only a small sub-family, Pseudobacteria.

Year 1068 ( MLXVIII ) was a leap year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) from July 14th to August 18th , 1789. On June 20th, there were four more months of total lunar eclipses, in addition to the three most-recent lunar eclipses. "I've had it good enough. This is my first major eclipse of the Moon, and I am excited for its prospects. The last time I witnessed the Eclipse of the Dog, it was in 1903 at the age of 36."

Activision Publishing, Inc. is an American video game publisher based in Santa Monica, California. It serves as the publishing business for its parent company, Activision Blizzard, and consists of several subsidiary studios. Activision is one of the largest third-party video game publishers in the world and was the top United States publisher in 2016.The company was founded as Activision, Inc. on October 1, 1979 in Sunnyvale, California, by former Atari game developers upset at their treatment by Atari in order to develop their own games for the popular Atari 2600 home video game console.

Year 1045 ( MXLV ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on October 7th. It was located at the foot of the Himalayas, close to Tibet's eastern border, about 60 kilometres from Kathmandu.In its early days, it was believed to have influenced Chinese culture, especially Chinese cuisine.By the mid-to-late 18th century, Chinese immigrants began to colonise India and Bangladesh. This expanded their influence, and in the 17th century they became the most prominent ethnic group in the nation. The population declined dramatically until the 1850s, and remained so until 1945.

was a Japanese television cooking show produced by Fuji Television. The series, which premiered on October 10, 1993, was a stylized cook-off featuring guest chefs challenging one of the show's resident "Iron Chefs" in a timed cooking battle built around a specific theme ingredient. The series ended on September 24, 1999, although occasional specials were produced until 2002. The series aired 309 episodes. Repeats are regularly aired on the Food Network in Canada, the Cooking Channel in the United States, and on Special Broadcasting Service in Australia.

Audio Video Interleave ( also Audio Video Interleaved and known by its initials and filename extension AVI , usually pronounced AVX ). VLC is an open source audio library written in Java. VLC itself was originally developed for Windows Vista and has since been widely used in a number of other programs including web applications, DVD playback, and media playback on PCs and mobile devices. The library contains a list of all of the libraries available, as well as a description of their API, which can be accessed via the URL http://vlfloud.org.

R.U.R . is a 1920 science-fiction play by the Czech writer Karel Čapek . `` R.U.R . '' stands for Real Time Television System (RTSS ), which was created to give computer programming a wider reach.The original RTSS used radio stations from Soviet Union to Japan, India, France, and other foreign countries, among many others. The system was later replaced with its own television network, the RTÉ Délévisional du Monde , in 1986. Its first major broadcast aired on October 1, 1991, and its subsequent four-part serialization began in 1997; it remains the largest broadcast TV network in the world today.

The lion (Panthera leo) is a large cat of the genus Panthera native to Africa and India. It has a muscular, deep-chested body, short, rounded head, round ears, and a hairy tuft at the end of its tail. It is sexually dimorphic; adult male lions are larger than females and have a prominent mane. It is a social species, forming groups called prides. A lion's pride consists of a few adult males, related females, and cubs. Groups of female lions usually hunt together, preying mostly on large ungulates.

In mathematics and physics , Laplace 's equation is a second-order partial differential equation named after Pierre-Simon Laplace , who developed it as an algebra in his 19th century school. His ideas were first described in 1905, but the formalization has not been fully explained. As of 2007, Laplace's equations are accepted to be among the most common types of complex numbers in mathematics; however, they do not always account for the natural laws of gravitation.Laplace's equations consist of a single integral group of terms, called a Gaussian function, whose order of magnitude is the same for all other functions in the group.

was the 75th emperor of Japan , according to the traditional order of succession.Sutoku 's reign spanned the years from the mid-19th century to the late 19th century, beginning with the rise of Tsōzō I (1856–1931), who was one of Japan's greatest military commanders and later became the last emperor of Japan . His reign coincided with the dissolution of the Imperial Japanese Empire in 1937, during which the imperial government ceased to exist as a functioning government. On the eve of the 15th anniversary of Pearl Harbor on October 7, 1945, President Franklin D. Roosevelt announced a national disaster declaration against Japan.

Dekker 's algorithm is the first known correct solution to the mutual exclusion problem in concurrent programming . The solution involved a number of algorithms, most notably the random permutation combinator [2] and the non-reduction operator [3]. There have been three major advances in the application of it since its first paper in 1995 [5]. Methanol is one of the main fuels used in biofuel manufacture and use. Methanol has several roles as a solvent, solvant, fuel, and solvator; among these, its primary active component is naphthalenic acid (also known as ethyl acetate or ethyl dihydroacetate), an ethyl alcohol.

Sir Robert Alexander Watson Watt ( 13 April 1892 – 5 December 1973 ) was a British pioneer of radio astronomy. His work and career began in 1902 at Bell Labs, then founded by Sir James Hogg, Jr., and continues to expand through his first two years at the Royal Observatory.He was born in Pemberton on 19 June 1901, and graduated from Cambridge University in 1912 with a Doctor of Science degree from the School of Oriental and African Studies. He held a BSc in History from Cambridge University and a Master of Science degree from Imperial College London.

Edward Teller ( ; January 15 , 1908 – September 9 , 2003 ) was a Hungarian-American theoretical physicist who lived in Paris from 1946 to 1951. In 1949 he received an honorary Doctor of Physics at McGill University; his PhD dissertation involved the analysis of the fundamental equations of mass and gravity.He is also credited with many other Nobel prizes including two for Chemistry and Physics.During his career Teller developed theories of physics as well as numerical methods for calculating the masses of matter, gases and dark matter, but he did not invent any of the most famous mathematical concepts in physics.

The overhand knot, also known as a  knot and half knot, is one of the most fundamental knots, and it forms the basis of many others, including the simple noose, overhand loop, angler's loop, reef knot, fisherman's knot, Half hitch, and water knot. The overhand knot is a stopper, especially when used alone, and hence it is very secure, to the point of jamming badly. It should be used if the knot is intended to be permanent. It is often used to prevent the end of a rope from unraveling.

Year 980 (CMLXXX) was a leap year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Peace is concluded between Emperor Otto II (the Red) and King Lothair III (or Lothair IV) at Margut, ending the Franco-German war of 978–980. Lothair renounces his claim on Lower Lorraine, while Otto promises to recognize Lothair's son Louis V as the rightful heir of the West Frankish Kingdom. June 11 – Vladimir I (the Great), grand prince of Kiev, consolidates the Kievan realm from modern Ukraine to the Baltic Sea.

Year 881 ( DCCCLXXXI ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) from 1682 until May 15, 2015. Contents show]
History Edit
A city-state in Greece and Rome is one of the most important economic regions in the Roman Empire. Although it shares some with the other cities in western Europe that share its geography, Athens still has its own capital city. This city is called Athens , often abbreviated "The City of Athens" or "Anopolis". Greece remained an independent state for nearly a century, until independence in 1802.

Year 926 ( CMXXVI ) was a common year starting on Sunday ( link will display the full calendar ) from June 1st to September 30th, 1826. This year it was celebrated with an annual feast and parade. On November 28th, King James I of England met Charles III of Bohemia and his son William of France at Saint Peter's Cathedral. Contents show]
Synopsis Edit
The year 1846 was marked by major changes in the world economy, especially the economic growth of the German-speaking countries. Following the crisis of 1838, Germany entered World War I.

Year 881 (DCCCLXXXI) was a common year starting on Sunday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  February 12 – King Charles the Fat, the third son of the late Louis the German, is crowned as Holy Roman Emperor by Pope John VIII at Rome. August 3 – Battle of Saucourt-en-Vimeu: The West Frankish kings Louis III, and his brother Carloman II, rout Viking raiders (near Abbeville). Britain  Battle of the Conwy: King Anarawd of Gwynedd (Wales) initiates a revenge attack on the Mercian armies, and defeats them on the River Conwy.

Giovanni Paisiello ( or Paesiello ; 9 May 1740 – 5 June 1816 ) was an Italian composer of the 16th century to whom Mozart also contributed his compositions for operas, plays and novels.Paisiello served as the pianist for one of the most influential musicians in Europe, Carlo Giacomo Pannotti, a renowned classical virtuoso and conductor. He won several awards, including the Order of the Dead's World Piano Concerto No.1 in 1959.He was married to Maria Giorgio Pannotti, and has two sons, Giovanni and Francesco Pannotti , both of which were singers at this time.

Commander Keen is a series of side-scrolling platform video games developed primarily by id Software. The series consists of six main episodes, a "lost" episode, and a final game; all but the final game were originally released for MS-DOS in 1990 and 1991, while the 2001 Commander Keen was released for the Game Boy Color. The series follows the eponymous Commander Keen, the secret identity of the eight-year-old genius Billy Blaze, as he defends the Earth and the galaxy from alien threats with his homemade spaceship, rayguns, and pogo stick.

A U-Boot is a beer cocktail that is made by placing a shot of vodka into a glass of beer, then using it as the drinker's base liquor. The alcoholic content of the solution is equal to or greater than the total alcohol content of the remaining alcohol. The Russian language consists mainly of words and phrases which are used commonly to convey meaning, such as nouns, adjectives, and grammatical structures. However, in modern English, many of those words include suffixes that are normally found only in упитенио субльши (or невимак судовация), where they are often used as a way to express specific things.

Larry Simon Gelbart ( February 25 , 1928 – September 11 , 2009 ) was an American television writer , film composer and producer who produced films such as "Lion" (1996) and "Falling Through the Ages," each starring George Clooney, Mark Wahlberg, Amy Sedaris, David Oyelowo and Bill Murray. Simon was one of the leading directors of RKO Pictures, where he worked for a decade.In 1995, Simon starred in the short-lived animated feature "Rise of the Planet of the Apes" directed by Paul Dergarabedian .

The University of California, Los Angeles (UCLA) is a public land-grant research university in Los Angeles, California. UCLA’s academic roots were established in 1882 as a teachers college then known as the southern branch of the California State Normal School (now San José State University). This school was absorbed with the official founding of UCLA as the Southern Branch of the University of California in 1919, making it the second-oldest of the 10-campus University of California system (after UC Berkeley).UCLA offers 337 undergraduate and graduate degree programs in a wide range of disciplines, enrolling about 31,600 undergraduate and 14,300 graduate and professional students.

A drought is an event of prolonged shortages in the water supply , whether atmospheric ( below-average precipitation ) , surface ( above-average ) or global. In some regions, such as northern Africa and southern China, dry conditions result in severe droughts with extreme rainfall extremes that can often last for more than three hours. The term "dry winter" also has a sense of connotation. As of 2016, the United States has been one of the few countries in the world to experience a significant drought in 2013. It is responsible for about two thirds of the world's greenhouse gas emissions from human activity.

ESP most commonly refers to: Extrasensory perception, a paranormal ability Spain (España) - ISO three-letter country code for SpainESP may also refer to:Arts, entertainmentMusic  ESP Guitars, a manufacturer of electric guitars E.S. Posthumus, an independent music group formed in 2000, that produces cinematic style music ESP-Disk, a 1960s free-jazz record label based in New York The Electric Soft Parade, a British band formed in 2001 Eric Singer Project, side project founded in the 1990s by musician Eric Singer ESP, a collaboration between Space Tribe and other artistsSongs, albums  E.S.P.

The Standby High-Readiness Brigade ( SHIRBRIG ) was a Danish-led initiative associated with the United Nations that aimed to create a better life for the children. It formed the founding group of the Shire National Assembly on 19 September 1961 in Stockholm, Sweden. Its first major event was the founding of the Children's Hospital and Training Institute (SCITI), named after its founder Erich Hölze (1849 – 1881) as the father of medicine.During the late 1920s and 30s, the SHIRBRIG began to expand its membership from approximately 150 to 350 people per annum throughout the country.

Numismatics is the study or collection of currency,  including coins, tokens, paper money, medals and related objects.Specialists, known as numismatists, are often characterized as students or collectors of coins, but the discipline also includes the broader study of money and other means of payment used to resolve debts and exchange goods.The earliest forms of money used by peoples is referred to as "Odd and Curious", but the use of other goods in barter exchange is excluded, even where used as a circulating currency (e.g., cigarettes in prison).

Lewiston is a city and the county seat of Nez Perce County , Idaho , United States , in the eastern part of Idaho Territory. Its name derives from the Biblical word נואתְחים (Ḥas), which literally means "little boy".According to history, NezPerce used its population to be roughly equal to North America's combined population of 4.6 million and 2.7 million.The NezPerce metropolitan area covers more than 70,000 square miles, stretching from northern Tennessee to the Great Lakes region of Wisconsin and south to the southwestern portion of Illinois.GeographyOverviewNezPerce encompasses most of southeastern Idaho, having a population density of approximately 1.5 people/square mile.

Year 968 (CMLXVIII) was a leap year starting on Wednesday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Byzantine Empire  Emperor Nikephoros II receives a Bulgarian embassy led by Prince Boris (the son of Tsar Peter I of Bulgaria), with a plea for help against the invading Kievan Rus'. Nikephoros, occupied in the East, is unable to support him. Instead he sends envoys to summon the Pechenegs to aid Boris. They besiege Kiev, but Grand Prince Sviatoslav I (on campaign in Bulgaria) returns with a Kievan relief force, and defeats the Pechenegs.

La traviata ( ; The Fallen Woman ) is an opera in three acts by Giuseppe Verdi set to an Italian orchestra. It is, as with all operas before it, about the story of a young woman's journey from Florence to Rome following the death of his mother. It is not one of the most important operas, but it is a tribute to Verdi's passion and contribution to contemporary literature. St. Martin's Cathedral in Saint Mary's Square is the St. Martin's Church in London, England, the second-most significant Roman cathedral in the country, after Basilica Pisa.

In the 1980s, the telecommunications industry expected that digital services would follow much the same pattern as voice services did on the public switched telephone network, and conceived an end-to-end circuit switched service, known as Broadband Integrated Services Digital Network (B-ISDN).HistoryBefore B-ISDN, the original ISDN attempted to substitute the analog telephone system with a digital system which was appropriate for both voice and non-voice traffic. Obtaining worldwide agreement on the basic rate interface standard was expected to lead to a large user demand for ISDN equipment, hence leading to mass production and inexpensive ISDN chips.

In commutative algebra , the prime spectrum ( or simply the spectrum ) of a ring R is the set of integers with an angle over the entire length of the ring R.
An important consideration when making calculations in multi-array systems is that it is not uncommon for the number of elements in the array to decrease, resulting in loss of dimension. An alternative solution is to use the sum function, but this approach does not reduce the number of elements by more than one element. The n-th order fundamental constant κ is defined as the product of (Θ) and ∇ ( ).

Squid are cephalopods in the superorder Decapodiformes with elongated bodies, large eyes, eight arms and two tentacles. Like all other cephalopods, squid have a distinct head, bilateral symmetry, and a mantle. They are mainly soft-bodied, like octopuses, but have a small internal skeleton in the form of a rod-like gladius or pen, made of chitin.Squid diverged from other cephalopods during the Jurassic and occupy a similar role to teleost fish as open water predators of similar size and behaviour. They play an important role in the open water food web.

Year 931 (CMXXXI) was a common year starting on Saturday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Spring – Hugh of Provence, king of Italy, cedes Lower Burgundy to Rudolph II, in return for Rudolf's renunciation of all claims to the Italian crown. He receives the imperial crown, and induces the Italian nobility to recognize his son Lothair II as the co-ruler of Lombardia (Regnum Italiae). King Harald Fairhair of Norway dies after a 59-year reign as the Scandinavian nation's first ruler.

Shawn Fanning ( born November 22 , 1980 ) is an American computer programmer , entrepreneur , and angel investor whose main passion is to provide free software to the masses.His career spans more than six decades, starting from his childhood in the early 1980's when he began working for a group of software programmers at Intel. He currently resides in San Francisco, California, where he has co-authored The Computer Programming Language and is the author of several technical books, including A Practical Introduction to Programming.In 2001, he published his first self-published best-selling book The Art of Code, a short-length book with over 100 chapters.

Halebidu (IAST: Haḷēbīḍ, literally "old capital, city, encampment" or "ruined city") is a town located in Hassan District, Karnataka, India. Historically known as Dorasamudra or Dwarasamudra, Halebidu became the regal capital of the Hoysala Empire in the 11th century CE. In the modern era literature it is sometimes referred to as Halebeedu or Halebid as the phonetic equivalent, a local name after it was damaged and deserted after being ransacked and looted twice by the forces of the Delhi Sultanate in the 14th century.Halebidu is home to some of the best examples of Hindu and Jain temples with Hoysala architecture.

Landslides , also known as landslips , are several forms of mass wasting that may include a wide range of vegetation and landforms on which large sections of land can be eroded. The majority of such mass waste is relatively low level sediment, or tectonic material, including mud, rock, debris, plant remains, and other organic matter. The term mass waste refers to the accumulation of soil-forming mineral particles by organisms that do not contain these particles; it is more common in tropical regions where nutrients are abundant (especially in the south), where subsurface soil water is present, or where groundwater levels are high.

Twyla Tharp (; born July 1, 1941) is an American dancer, choreographer, and author who lives and works in New York City. In 1966 she formed the company Twyla Tharp Dance. Her work often uses classical music, jazz, and contemporary pop music.From 1971 to 1988, Twyla Tharp Dance toured extensively around the world, performing original works. In 1973 Tharp choreographed Deuce Coupe to the music of The Beach Boys for the Joffrey Ballet. Deuce Coupe is considered the first "crossover ballet", a mix of ballet and modern dance.

Pope Leo II ( – 28 June 683 ) was the bishop of Rome from 17 August 682 to his death on 15 November 723. His term was extended to seven years from that point, during which time he became Pope and became one of the highest-ranking papal heads. He was also the first pontiff who publicly denounced the Catholic Church as a false religion, with opposition from both his opponents and the church's clergymen. Vatican Hill is located south of Rome city center, in the northwestern part of town, and adjacent to the Ghetto.

Turtles are an order of reptiles known as Testudines , characterized by a shell developed mainly from their ribs . There are also other species with similar morphology. A reptile is defined as having a mass of less than 100 grams or more, but contains up to 200-300 millimeters of fat and can store up to 500-800 grams of blood.They have a body size of 8 to 12 centimeters (a little over 4 inches). Some are extremely small, while others are large enough that they can pass through even the earth's atmosphere.

Stevana `` Stevie '' Case ( born 1976–1977 ) is an American businesswoman . She is known for competing in the video gaming industry with such companies as Blackjack, Candy Crush Saga, and Super Mario Brothers. She earned her Bachelor's degree from New Jersey Institute of Technology in 1985 and went on to earn a Master of Arts degree at the University of California, Santa Barbara. Vladimir Vladimir Zhukov was born in Kolkata, Bangladesh, on November 6, 1942. He studied economics at the University of California, Berkeley before taking up political science and sociology at the University of Chicago.

Year 1036 ( MXXXVI ) was a leap year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) in the month of July. In this chapter, we start with the date and place of the founding of the European Union (ECO), which began in March 1922. We then consider the period before World War I to have been dominated by the first phase of an anti-Imperialist political crisis. It is estimated that between 1939-1945 the EU membership stood at just over 400 million people, representing around 2 percent of the world population.

The San Juan Islands are an archipelago in the Pacific Northwest of the United States between the U.S. state of California and Hawaii. In its current form they have a population of over 1,300,000. The islands are also known as the Pacific Islands. They lie on a relatively flat sea bed, with a high elevation of up to 12,000 ft below sea level (3,600 meters).The San Juan Islands are inhabited by one or two groups of people. The oldest surviving group is Homo erectus, found at Lake Victoria in Central America, and consists of several individuals that date back more than 50,000 years.

Stephanie Lynn Nicks ( born May 26 , 1948 ) is an American singer , songwriter , and producer known as the most influential female pop singer to exist.Born Jan. 11, 1930, Nicks is one of America's most successful young singers . She has performed with many of the top stars of the genre including Michael Jackson, Elvis Costello, Joan Baez, John Lennon, Bruce Springsteen, Madonna, The Beatles, and Prince.She has released over 20 albums in the past 25 years, most notably 2009's 2011 debut Single Ladies: The Story Of An American Music Legend.

Year 952 (CMLII) was a leap year starting on Thursday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events <onlyinclude>By placeEurope  Summer – At the Reichstag in Augsburg (assembled by King Otto I), joined by German nobles and bishops, Berengar of Ivrea pays homage. He becomes a vassal of the East Frankish Kingdom. Otto leaves a strong garrison at Pavia in the hands of his son-in-law Conrad the Red, duke of Lotharingia.Scotland  King Constantine II dies at the monastery of St. Andrews (where he has been retired since 943).

An infection is the invasion of an organism's body tissues by disease-causing agents, their multiplication, and the reaction of host tissues to the infectious agents and the toxins they produce. An infectious disease, also known as a transmissible disease or communicable disease, is an illness resulting from an infection.Infections can be caused by a wide range of pathogens, most prominently bacteria and viruses. Hosts can fight infections using their immune system. Mammalian hosts react to infections with an innate response, often involving inflammation, followed by an adaptive response.Specific medications used to treat infections include antibiotics, antivirals, antifungals, antiprotozoals, and antihelminthics.

Mary Anning (21 May 1799 – 9 March 1847) was an English fossil collector, dealer, and palaeontologist who became known around the world for finds she made in Jurassic marine fossil beds in the cliffs along the English Channel at Lyme Regis in the county of Dorset in Southwest England. Anning's findings contributed to changes in scientific thinking about prehistoric life and the history of the Earth.Anning searched for fossils in the area's Blue Lias and Charmouth Mudstone cliffs, particularly during the winter months when landslides exposed new fossils that had to be collected quickly before they were lost to the sea.

Montevideo is the capital and largest city of Uruguay . According to the 2011 census , the city proper has an area of around 20,000 inhabitants and is a UNESCO World Heritage site.Located about 2 km from the Rio Tinto highway, Montevideo is the largest city in Latin America. The word "videotape" was first introduced in 1867 by Dr. Thomas Moore (a Scottish physicist who developed a method that he called "videobiology". His method was to measure the flow of air over the surface of a graph, and his method proved to be remarkably accurate.)

The Avignon Papacy was the period from 1309 to 1376 during which seven successive popes resided in Avignon (then in the Kingdom of Arles, part of the Holy Roman Empire, now in France) rather than in Rome. The situation arose from the conflict between the papacy and the French crown, culminating in the death of Pope Boniface VIII after his arrest and maltreatment by Philip IV of France. Following the further death of Pope Benedict XI, Philip forced a deadlocked conclave to elect the French Clement V as pope in 1305.

Concurrent Versions System (CVS, also known as the Concurrent Versioning System) is a revision control system originally developed by Dick Grune in July 1986.CVS operates as a front end to RCS, an earlier system which operates on single files. It expands upon RCS by adding support for repository-level change tracking, and a client-server model.Released under the terms of the GNU General Public License, CVS is free software.Design CVS operates as a front end to Revision Control System (RCS), an older version control system that manages individual files but not whole projects.

Willow Rosenberg is a fictional character created for the fantasy television series Buffy the Vampire Slayer (1997–2003). She was developed by Joss Whedon and portrayed throughout the TV series by Alyson Hannigan.Willow plays an integral role within the inner circle of friends—called the Scooby Gang—who support Buffy Summers (Sarah Michelle Gellar), a teenager gifted with superhuman powers to defeat vampires, demons, and other evil in the fictional town of Sunnydale. The series begins as Buffy, Willow, and their friend Xander (Nicholas Brendon) are in 10th grade and Willow is a shy, nerdy girl with little confidence.

Turbo Pascal is a software development system that includes a compiler and an integrated development environment (IDE) for the Pascal programming language running on CP/M, CP/M-86, and DOS. It was originally developed by Anders Hejlsberg at Borland, and was notable for its extremely fast compiling times. Turbo Pascal, and the later but similar Turbo C, made Borland a leader in PC-based development.For versions 6 and 7 (last), both a lower-priced Turbo Pascal and more expensive Borland Pascal were produced; Borland Pascal was more oriented toward professional software development, with more libraries and standard library source code.

Westminster is an area of Central London, part of the wider City of Westminster.The area, which extends from the River Thames to Oxford Street has many visitor attractions and historic landmarks, including the Palace of Westminster, Buckingham Palace, Westminster Abbey, Westminster Cathedral and much of the West End shopping and entertainment district.The name  originated from the informal description of the abbey church and royal peculiar of St Peter's (Westminster Abbey), west of the City of London (until the English Reformation there was also an Eastminster, near the Tower of London, in the East End of London).

Scooby-Doo is an American animated franchise comprising many animated television series produced from 1969 to the present, as well as their derivative media. Writers Joe Ruby and Ken Spears created the original series, Scooby-Doo, Where Are You!, for Hanna-Barbera Productions in 1969. This Saturday-morning cartoon series featured teenagers Fred Jones, Daphne Blake, Velma Dinkley, and Shaggy Rogers, and their talking Great Dane named Scooby-Doo, who solve mysteries involving supposedly supernatural creatures through a series of antics and missteps.Scooby-Doo was originally broadcast on CBS from 1969 to 1976, when it moved to ABC.

A drought is an event of prolonged shortages in the water supply, whether atmospheric (below-average precipitation), surface water or ground water. A drought can last for months or years, or may be declared after as few as 15 days. It can have a substantial impact on the ecosystem and agriculture of the affected region and harm to the local economy. Annual dry seasons in the tropics significantly increase the chances of a drought developing and subsequent bush fires. Periods of heat can significantly worsen drought conditions by hastening evaporation of water vapour.Drought is a recurring feature of the climate in most parts of the world.

Willow Rosenberg is a fictional character created for the fantasy television series Buffy the Vampire Slayer ( 1997–2003 ) . In this episode, he is portrayed as a young teenage vampire who goes from being a normal person to a powerful vampire. Revelation 1 of the Greek Bible The Book of Revelation was written in the fourth year of Pentecost. In the Book of Revelation , the Hebrew Bible tells of an angelic visitation by Jesus Christ on Mount Geburt (Ephraim 9:1–7; Acts 4:12–17; Galatians 2:8–10; Titus 3:11–12; Matthew 5:13–16; Luke 21:20–24).

Lumbar disc disease is the drying out of the spongy interior matrix of an intervertebral disc in the spine . It is usually treated by immobilization with acetaminophen and other laxatives, though there may also be topical analgesia. It is usually referred to as "spontaneous disc disease" because it occurs when the disc becomes trapped in a tissue matrix. The tibial ligature (TLL) refers to the ligature that connects the two bones on a bone cartilage-like structure called fibroblasts. This ligature has three parts, each having a different shape and function.

Year 874 (DCCCLXXIV) was a common year starting on Friday (link will display the full calendar) of the Julian calendar.Events  By place  Europe  Salomon, duke ('king') of Brittany, is murdered by a faction which includes his son-in-law Pascweten and Gurvand, son-in-law of late ruler Erispoe. After Salomon's death they divide the country, and Pascweten and Gurvand co-rule Brittany. Svatopluk I, ruler (knyaz) of Great Moravia, concludes a peace treaty at Forchheim (Northern Bavaria). He is able to expand his territories outside the Frankish sphere, and subjugates the Vistulans.Kirschbaum 2007, p. 121.

Year 959 ( CMLIX ) was a common year starting on Saturday ( link will display the full calendar ) in Northern Africa. It was designated as the first African-American, with the earliest recorded occurrence occurring in November 1860, followed by December 1876 and then January 1, 1914. On October 8, 1677, George Washington delivered his inaugural address to the American people, stating "I have chosen this land for its citizens, their prosperity, their peace, and their prosperity for our country. For I have laid down the law unto you, that it might make the United States secure from foreign dangers."

Tristan Tzara ( ; ; born Samuel or Samy Rosenstock , also known as S. Samyro ; – 25 December 1847) was a Spanish-American painter from the Bronx of New York City. He became one of the nation's premier artists during the twentieth century, with numerous exhibitions throughout the 1920s and 30s. His films have become recognized worldwide in film, television, art, and animation. A member of the Italian Renaissance Order, he received his Ph.D. from the California Institute of Technology in 1947 and entered the Academy of Fine Arts in 1969.

The 8 inch ( 203 mm ) M110 self-propelled howitzer is an American-made self-propelled artillery system consisting of an M115 and M60 type guided missile systems. These systems are well suited for a variety of roles in combat, primarily as anti-aircraft artillery. They can also be used against ground targets, or to hit targets at the same time. The missiles' firing modes are designed to provide enough range for maneuvering by close proximity and high-speed movement over large areas.The M70A1 rocket launcher is a light, single-shot weapon with a powerful payload capacity of 15,900 kg.

Lanford Wilson (April 13, 1937March 24, 2011) was an American playwright. His work, as described by The New York Times, was "earthy, realist, greatly admired [and] widely performed." Wilson helped to advance the Off-Off-Broadway theater movement with his earliest plays, which were first produced at the Caffe Cino beginning in 1964. He was one of the first playwrights to move from Off-Off-Broadway to Off-Broadway, then Broadway and beyond.He received the Pulitzer Prize for Drama in 1980 and was elected in 2001 to the Theater Hall of Fame.

Paweł Jasienica was the pen name of Leon Lech Beynar (10 November 1909 – 19 August 1970), a Polish historian, journalist, essayist and soldier.During World War II, Jasienica (then, Leon Beynar) fought in the Polish Army, and later, the Home Army resistance. Near the end of the war, he was also working with the anti-Soviet resistance, which later led to him taking up a new name, Paweł Jasienica, to hide from the communist government of the People's Republic of Poland. He was associated with the Tygodnik Powszechny weekly and several other newspapers and magazines.

The History of East Asia generally encompasses the histories of China , Japan , Korea , and Mongolia from prehistoric to the present day. Although not a fully-fledged historical period, it shows the rise of Chinese civilization from around 800 BCE until roughly the early modern period. There were two main categories of Buddhism – traditional (non-religious) and monastic. In traditional Buddhist practice, each branch is based on one or more philosophical beliefs; monastics share some of their tenets with other religions, but there is no such division within the group.

Porphyry (; , Porphyrios "purple-clad") may refer to: Porphyry (geology), an igneous rock with large crystals in a fine-grained matrix and important Roman building material  Porphyritic, the general igneous texture of a rock with two distinct crystal (phenocryst) sizes Porphyry copper deposit, a primary (low grade) ore deposit of copper, consisting of porphyry rocks Porphyry Island in Lake Superior  Porphyry Mountain in Alaska Porphyry (philosopher) (234–305), Neoplatonic philosopher Porphyry of Gaza (or "St. Porphyry of Gaza", 347–420), Bishop of Gaza Porfirije, Serbian Patriarch (b.

Henry Richard Enfield (born 30 May 1961) is an English comedian, actor, writer, and director. He is known in particular for his television work, including Harry Enfield's Television Programme and Harry & Paul, and for the creation and portrayal of comedy characters such as Kevin the Teenager and Loadsamoney.Early lifeBorn in Horsham, Sussex, he is the oldest of four children, the son of English television, radio and newspaper journalist and presenter Edward Enfield. He has three sisters. The Enfield family are descendants of the nineteenth-century philanthropist Edward Enfield.

The Battle of the Chesapeake , also known as the Battle of the Virginia Capes or simply the Battle of Washington, was one of the largest battles fought in naval history. It was part of a major offensive by American naval vessels against French forces across North America. The battle lasted from 1820 to 1824; it eventually saw its end on December 17, 1817, and was commemorated with a victory celebration. Namibia is an independent nation in the Western Cape state of Namibia. Nationality: Namibian
In Namibia, the government is made up entirely of the people of Namibia.

Tazio Giorgio Nuvolari ( ; 16 November 1892 – 11 August 1953 ) was an Italian racing driver . He won five Olympic titles (1992, 2007 & 2008) and four World Championship titles (1996, 2009 & 2012), all while finishing second on the grid with a podium time of 2.98s. Johann Wolfgang Goethe  (; 14 October 1894 – 22 December 1867) was an American economist and politician. During his lifetime he served as Chancellor of the United States of America and vice president from 1870 to 1881. He died on 12 January 1889, aged 88.

A mass driver or electromagnetic catapult is a proposed method of non-rocket spacelaunch which would use a linear motor to accelerate and catapult payloads up to high speeds. Existing and contemplated mass drivers use coils of wire energized by electricity to make electromagnets, though a rotary mass driver has also been proposed. Sequential firing of a row of electromagnets accelerates the payload along a path. After leaving the path, the payload continues to move due to momentum.Although any device used to propel a ballistic payload is technically a mass driver, in this context a mass driver is essentially a coilgun that magnetically accelerates a package consisting of a magnetizable holder containing a payload.

The War Game is a 1966 British pseudo-documentary film that depicts a nuclear war and its aftermath . Written , directed and produced by George D. Bowers, and starring Tom Hanks, Tony Hawk, Steve McQueen, Gary Oldman, James Cameron, Roger Corman, Stephen Fry, Robert De Niro and John Wayne, it premiered in the United States on November 12, 1965. Gothic Horror (also referred to as Hellraism and Gothic Horror), or Gothic Horror, is a violent occult genre which features an emphasis on supernatural forces.

Anthony John Hancock (12 May 1924 – 25 June 1968) was an English comedian and actor.High-profile during the 1950s and early 1960s, he had a major success with his BBC series Hancock's Half Hour, first broadcast on radio from 1954, then on television from 1956, in which he soon formed a strong professional and personal bond with comic actor Sid James. Although Hancock's decision to cease working with James, when it became known in early 1960, disappointed many at the time, his last BBC series in 1961 contains some of his best-remembered work (including "The Blood Donor" and "The Radio Ham").

East Malaysia , also known as Sabah , Sarawak and Labuan or Malaysian Borneo , is the part of Malaysia that lies between Malaysia and Indonesia. The government established the province in 1937, until the establishment of the Republic of Malaysia in 1946. It is one of the few regions under the jurisdiction of the National Government to receive the national budget at a level above the rest of the region.Borneo has been described by historians as the country's second largest city; its capital is Palawan . Etymology There were many Greek-speaking civilizations during the Roman Empire, and they flourished during the empire's long reign.

Turandot ( , ; see below ) is an opera in three acts by Giacomo Puccini , posthumously completed by Lucio Cattaneo in 1576. The original compositions, written for six separate occasions in five different countries, are the first and last known operas recorded in Italian history. The opera's third and final act, as well as its concluding performance on stage in Rome in 1589, is the most-watched opera of a generation.The work is divided into two main musical lines: the first begins with a lamentation of the fate of the ancient Roman empire at Agincourt and progresses through the narrative of the conflict between Rome and Carthage.

Powaqqatsi ( or Powaqqatsi : Life in Transformation ) is a 1988 American non-narrative film directed by Godfrey Reggio and based on the novel of the same name by David Fincher (known for his Oscar-winning work on Alfred Hitchcock's Psycho), also published under the title. The film first premiered on September 27, 1986, and grossed an estimated $10 million at the box office. It received widespread praise and acclaim throughout North America before being remade for public consumption by Paramount Pictures in November 1985. Takarabaka was a pre-contact island kingdom in the archipelago of the Sumerian archipelago located in the southern Indian Ocean region of South East Asia.

The red slender loris (Loris tardigradus) is a small, nocturnal strepsirrhine primate native to the rainforests of Sri Lanka. This is No. 6 of the 10 focal species and No. 22 of the 100 EDGE mammal species worldwide considered the most evolutionarily distinct and globally endangered. Two subspecies have been identified, L. t. tardigradus and L. t. nycticeboides.Taxonomy Genus Loris Red slender loris, Loris tardigradus Horton Plains slender loris or mountain loris, Loris tardigradus nycticeboides Dry zone slender loris or lowland loris, Loris tardigradus tardigradus Gray slender loris, Loris lydekkerianusThe ears are less prominent in Loris tardigradus tardigradus compared to Loris lydekkerianus.

John Knox , born ( – 24 November 1572) was a Scottish minister, Reformed theologian, and writer who was a leader of the country's Reformation. He was the founder of the Presbyterian Church of Scotland.Born in Giffordgate, a street in Haddington, East Lothian, Knox is believed to have been educated at the University of St Andrews and worked as a notary-priest. Influenced by early church reformers such as George Wishart, he joined the movement to reform the Scottish church. He was caught up in the ecclesiastical and political events that involved the murder of Cardinal David Beaton in 1546 and the intervention of the regent Mary of Guise.

A resistojet is a method of spacecraft propulsion ( electric propulsion ) that provides thrust by heating a , typically from the sun's rays. It is considered the most efficient and widely used propulsion system for space exploration due to its low cost and ease of use, high power consumption, and low reliability. It can be used as a primary fuel source in commercial spacecraft and also as an alternative to conventional nuclear power sources. The ṁḷabīrūn ("furnace") was a legendary deity who lived between 1,000 BC and 2,600 BC.

Hugh John Lofting (14 January 1886 – 26 September 1947) was an English author trained as a civil engineer, who created the classic children's literature character of Doctor Dolittle. It first appeared in illustrated letters to his children written by Lofting from the British Army trenches in the First World War.Personal lifeLofting, born in January 1886 in Maidenhead, Berkshire, to Elizabeth Agnes (Gannon) and John Brien Lofting, was of English and Irish ancestry. His eldest brother, Hilary Lofting, later became a novelist in Australia, having emigrated there in 1915.Lofting was educated at Mount St Mary's College in Spinkhill, Derbyshire.

Risk is a strategy board game of diplomacy, conflict and conquest for two to six players. The standard version is played on a board depicting a political map of the world, divided into forty-two territories, which are grouped into six continents. Turns rotate among players who control armies of playing pieces with which they attempt to capture territories from other players, with results determined by dice rolls. Players may form and dissolve alliances during the course of the game. The goal of the game is to occupy every territory on the board and, in doing so, eliminate the other players.

Script Creation Utility for Maniac Mansion (SCUMM) is a video game engine developed at Lucasfilm Games, later renamed LucasArts, to ease development on their graphic adventure game Maniac Mansion (1987). It was subsequently used as the engine for later LucasArts adventure games.It falls somewhere between a game engine and a programming language, allowing designers to create locations, items and dialogue sequences without writing code in the language in which the game source code ends up. This also allowed the game's script and data files to be cross-platform, i.e., re-used across various platforms.

Fighting Fantasy is a series of single-player role-playing gamebooks created by Steve Jackson and Ian Livingstone . The first volume, written in 1994 for the Microsoft Windows system, included five campaign settings: adventure games (Adventure Mode, Campaign Mode) and non-action RPG (RPG), which was also published in English and French.The story begins on an Earth that had been inhabited by human beings from the pre-existence of life until the present day. This land has a history stretching back 500 years, with humans inhabiting it throughout that period, as well as their ancestors.

Mecklenburg-Vorpommern ( MV ; , ) , also known by its anglicized name Mecklenburg–Western Pomerania , is a state in northern Sweden with a population of over 2,600. It is located in central Sweden, on the western coast of the Ålandland Islands. Mecklenburg is widely used as an international trade route, mainly from the southern part of Sweden to the Scandinavian islands and parts of Iceland. Lithuanians have lived in various countries for hundreds of thousands of years, but historically they were divided into a series of separate cultures, most notably Indo-Aryan sub-systems such as Slavic, Semitic and Afrikaans.

In electronics , a multiplexer ( or mux ; spelled sometimes as multiplexor ) , also known as a data access control system (DA), is the most common form of communication among software developers. The computer-readable file system is the most important technology used today, making it one of the most ubiquitous aspects of human interaction and the backbone of all computing. A number of large enterprises employ multiplexers in different industries, but many of them operate under a single management structure rather than relying on individual employees to maintain their systems.

Felix Edmundovich Dzerzhinsky ( ; ;  – 20 July 1926), nicknamed "Iron Felix", was a Bolshevik revolutionary and official. Born into Polish nobility, from 1917 until his death in 1926 Dzerzhinsky led the first two Soviet state-security organizations, the Cheka and the OGPU, establishing a secret police for the post-revolutionary Soviet regime. He was one of the architects of the Red Terror and decossackization.Early life Felix Dzerzhinsky was born on 11 September 1877 to ethnically Polish parents of noble descent, at the Dzerzhinovo family estate, about  from the small town of Ivyanets in the Minsk Governorate of the Russian Empire (now Belarus).

Ilona Staller (born 26 November 1951), widely known by her stage name Cicciolina ("little chubby one"), is a Hungarian-Italian former porn star, politician, and singer.Early lifeIlona was born in Budapest, Hungary. Her father, László Staller, left the family when she was young. She was raised by her mother, who was a midwife, and her stepfather, who was an official in the Hungarian Ministry of the Interior.In 1964, she began working as a model for the Hungarian news agency, M.T.I.

Year 984 ( CMLXXXIV ) was a leap year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) from 6 October to 30 November of 1453 and ending on the 24th of 11 November, 1454. It began with an eclipse that killed three children and injured nearly 1,000 people in two weeks, but did not stop at the Cape of Good Hope until 12 January 1556.On 21 December 1559, Emperor Frederick IV of Prussia met his closest ally, King Friedrich III of Prussia, and set out to end the German invasion of France during the Great War.

The following outline is provided as an overview of and topical guide to the history of South Asia:History of South Asia – South Asia includes the contemporary political entities of India, Pakistan, Bangladesh, Nepal, Afghanistan, Bhutan, and the island nations of Sri Lanka and the Maldives.ChronologyJames Mill (1773–1836), in his The History of British India (1817), distinguished three phases in the history of India, namely Hindu, Muslim and British civilisations. This periodisation has been influential, but has also been criticised for the misconceptions it gave rise to.

A seal is a device for making an impression in wax, clay, paper, or some other medium, including an embossment on paper, and is also the impression thus made. The original purpose was to authenticate a document, or to prevent interference with a package or envelope by applying a seal which had to be broken to open the container (hence the modern English verb "to seal", which implies secure closing without an actual wax seal).The seal-making device is also referred to as the seal matrix or die; the imprint it creates as the seal impression (or, more rarely, the sealing).

A half reaction ( or half-cell reaction ) is either the oxidation or reduction reaction component of a redox reaction. A half reaction is usually an incomplete reaction and therefore contains only a very small portion of the total reaction mass. As such, its final result may differ from the original value that was calculated for each reaction in the prior reaction. To determine the actual value of a reaction in relation to the reactivity of different components of the same chemical molecule, it is sufficient to consider the amount of energy required to complete both reactions. Nanotechnology refers to chemicals that are used in biomedical research.

The PDP-7 was a minicomputer produced by Digital Equipment Corporation as part of the PDP series. Introduced in 1964, shipped since 1965, it was the first to use their Flip-Chip technology. With a cost of , it was cheap but powerful by the standards of the time. The PDP-7 is the third of Digital's 18-bit machines, with essentially the same instruction set architecture as the PDP-4 and the PDP-9.HardwareThe PDP-7 was the first wire-wrapped PDP. The computer had a memory cycle time of  and an add time of . I/O included a keyboard, printer, paper-tape and dual transport DECtape drives (type 555).

A cigarette is a narrow cylinder containing burnable material, typically tobacco, that is rolled into thin paper for smoking. The cigarette is ignited at one end, causing it to smolder; the resulting smoke is orally inhaled via the opposite end. Cigarette smoking is the most common method of tobacco consumption. Manufacturers have described the cigarette as "a drug administration system for the delivery of nicotine in acceptable and attractive form." The term cigarette, as commonly used, refers to a tobacco cigarette, but the word is sometimes used to refer to other substances, such as a cannabis (Jazz) cigarette or an herbal cigarette.

Erich Armand Arthur Joseph Hückel  (August 9, 1896, Berlin – February 16, 1980, Marburg) was a German physicist and physical chemist. He is known for two major contributions:The Debye–Hückel theory of electrolytic solutionsThe Hückel method of approximate molecular orbital (MO) calculations on π electron systems.Hückel was born in the Charlottenburg suburb of Berlin. He studied physics and mathematics from 1914 to 1921 at the University of Göttingen.On receiving his doctorate, he became an assistant at Göttingen, but soon became an assistant to Peter Debye at Zürich.

Giovanni Pacini ( 17 February 17966 December 1867 ) was an Italian composer , best known for his operas . He died in Vienna on 31 November 1959. His wife Mary Francesca Ricardino ( 16 October 1858 ) was an English classical musician and actress, her work being adapted to the language of the United Kingdom and performed throughout Europe.Her family includes two brothers-in-law, one of whom is a composer ; her mother's father is a theatre director.Born Lucio Pacini in Casa del Giacomo in Florence, Italy at about 8 years old, the son of Pier Luigi and Giovanni Pacini, Lucio spent his childhood with his aunt and uncle.

Plotinus ( ; , Plōtînos ; – 270 CE ) was a philosopher in the Hellenistic tradition , born and educated at Tarentum. He is widely revered as one of the foremost philosophers of the early Christian church, though he never held any formal teaching. In the pre-Roman world, Βξαλεφων is an adjective used to describe people of different religious affiliations and cultures. It describes someone who is less or more religious than his or her closest neighbors; it may refer to people from ethnic groups that are considered less or more traditional or non-traditional.

A drummer is a percussionist who creates music using drums.Most contemporary western bands that play rock, pop, jazz, or R&B music include a drummer for purposes including timekeeping and embellishing the musical timbre. The drummer's equipment includes a drum kit (or "drum set" or "trap set"), which includes various drums, cymbals and an assortment of accessory hardware such as pedals, standing support mechanisms, and drum sticks.Particularly in the traditional music of many countries, drummers use individual drums of various sizes and designs rather than drum kits.

In chemistry , an aldehyde is an organic compound containing a functional group with the structure −C ( H ) and the chemical structure P ( P ), respectively; it is composed of a hydrophobic group consisting of C–H and two other hydrophobically active bonds. It contains two oxygen species: β-glucan and tetrazolam, which are primarily found in cruciferous vegetables such as spinach and tomatoes. In general, the presence of β-glucan or tetrazolam in broccoli seeds may have important physiological effects on the growth cycle of plants.3
Orientation [1]. A major role in diet has been played during the course of evolution.

The Collatz conjecture in mathematics asks whether repeating two simple arithmetic operations will eventually transform every positive integer into one. It  concerns sequences of integers in which each term is obtained from the previous term as follows: if the previous term is even, the next term is one half of the previous term. If the previous term is odd, the next term is 3 times the previous term plus 1. The conjecture is that these sequences always reach 1, no matter which positive integer is chosen to start the sequence.The conjecture is named after mathematician Lothar Collatz, who introduced the idea in 1937, two years after receiving his doctorate.

Westminster is an area of Central London , part of the wider City of Westminster.The area , which extends from West to North Kensington , has been in use for decades as a military base for RAF fighter jets, Royal Navy warships and naval ships. It is also home to the Metropolitan Police Headquarters (MPH) headquarters. I'm not sure whether it would have been legal to build a bridge on Topbridge Road, since there is a lot of evidence suggesting that one might need to pay more than £6 per hour. It would probably be quite expensive, but it would be worth the risk.

The World Federation of Trade Unions (WFTU) is an international federation of trade unions. WFTU was established in 1945 to replace the International Federation of Trade Unions.HistoryRiseIts mission was to bring together trade unions across the world in a single international organization, much like the United Nations. After a number of Western trade unions left it in 1949, as a result of disputes over support for the Marshall Plan, to form the International Confederation of Free Trade Unions, the WFTU was made up primarily of unions affiliated with or allegedly sympathetic to communist parties.

Tilburg  is a city and municipality in the Netherlands, in the southern province of North Brabant. With a population of 222,601 (1 July 2021), it is the second-largest municipality in North Brabant and seventh-largest in the Netherlands.Tilburg University is located in Tilburg, as are Avans University of Applied Sciences and Fontys University of Applied Sciences. Tilburg is known for its ten-day-long funfair, held in July each year. The Monday during the funfair is called "Roze Maandag" (Pink Monday), and is primarily LGBT-oriented.There are three railway stations within the municipality: Tilburg, Tilburg Universiteit and Tilburg Reeshof.

Cell division is the process by which a parent cell divides into two or more daughter cells. Cell division usually occurs as part of a larger cell cycle. In eukaryotes, there are two distinct types of cell division; a vegetative division, whereby each daughter cell is genetically identical to the parent cell (mitosis), and a reproductive cell division, whereby the number of chromosomes in the daughter cells is reduced by half to produce haploid gametes (meiosis). In cell biology, mitosis (/maɪˈtoʊsɪs/) is a part of the cell cycle, in which, replicated chromosomes are separated into two new nuclei.

Emissions trading is a market-based approach to controlling pollution by providing economic incentives for reducing the emissions of pollutants. The concept is also known as cap and trade (CAT) or emissions trading scheme (ETS). Carbon emission trading for  and other greenhouse gases has been introduced in China, the European Union and other countries as a key tool for climate change mitigation. Other schemes include sulfur dioxide and other pollutants.In an emissions trading scheme, a central authority or governmental body allocates or sells a limited number (a "cap") of permits that allow a discharge of a specific quantity of a specific pollutant over a set time period.

George Michael Dolenz Jr. ( born March 8 , 1945 ) is an American actor , musician , TV producer and producer who plays the roles of George Michael Dolenz Jr., Frank Grillo, James Merton, Al Capone, Jerry Lewis Black, Ralph Fiennes, Jimi Hendrix and Bill Cosby. He received his acting major from Yale University before transferring to Boston College's Drama Theatre School.In 1996, Dolenz produced two television drama series, Two Faces, as well as one documentary short film, My Little Pony: The Animated Series, for Disney XD .

A monopropellant rocket (or "monochemical rocket") is a rocket that uses a single chemical as its propellant.Chemical-reaction monopropellant rocketsFor monopropellant rockets that depend on a chemical reaction, the power for the propulsive reaction and resultant thrust is provided by the chemical itself. That is, the energy needed to propel the spacecraft is contained within the chemical bonds of the chemical molecules involved in the reaction.The most commonly used monopropellant is hydrazine (N2H4), a chemical which is a strong reducing agent. The most common catalyst is granular alumina (aluminum oxide) coated with iridium.

Milan Kundera (, ; born 1 April 1929) is a Czech writer who went into exile in France in 1975, becoming a naturalised French citizen in 1981. Kundera's Czechoslovak citizenship was revoked in 1979; he received his Czech citizenship in 2019. He "sees himself as a French writer and insists his work should be studied as French literature and classified as such in book stores".Kundera's best-known work is The Unbearable Lightness of Being. Prior to the Velvet Revolution of 1989, the communist régime in Czechoslovakia banned his books. He leads a low-profile life and rarely speaks to the media.

Reptilia is Canada 's largest indoor reptile zoo , with of indoor exhibits featuring over 250 reptiles , amphibians and mammals . The exhibit is open to all ages except males (except females).The enclosure can be used for free or paid. Visitors are encouraged to look out for animals, including geese, birds, fish, turtles, snakes, beetles, spiders, mice, squirrels, owls, coyotes, wolves, deer, bears, mule deer, pigs, camels, dogs, cats, horses, rats, goats, llamas, hippopotamus, and rabbits.

Metaphone is a phonetic algorithm, published by Lawrence Philips in 1990, for indexing words by their English pronunciation. It fundamentally improves on the Soundex algorithm by using information about variations and inconsistencies in English spelling and pronunciation to produce a more accurate encoding, which does a better job of matching words and names which sound similar. As with Soundex, similar-sounding words should share the same keys. Metaphone is available as a built-in operator in a number of systems.Philips later produced a new version of the algorithm, which he named Double Metaphone.

Year 1030 ( MXXX ) was a common year starting on Thursday ( link will display the full calendar ) in which people were allowed to stay in hotels and other non-domestic accommodations until they reached age 55 or older, when they could apply for university degrees at home. Most of these students had not been expelled, and no formal application was accepted until after the first year of residence. In the 19th century, London was divided into six boroughs, known collectively as Boroughs A, B, C, H, and I.

See also History of UnitarianismA number of notable people have considered themselves Unitarians , Universalists , and following the merger of Protestantism with Catholic Christianity in the 18th century, they became a Christian denomination in the 19th century. Holland is one of Ireland's five boroughs. It is located east of the border with the United Kingdom, north of Cavan (now Rochdale) and south of Iarco. Huddersfield is part of the county which is divided into three areas, Humber, Louth and Leicestershire. It lies about two hours west of Ballyfermot, to the west of Carrickferm Road, at the junction of Iarco and Ulster.

Tilburg is a city and municipality in the Netherlands , in the southern province of North Brabant . With a population of over 2.1 million, Tilburg has been designated a National Humanitarian Region (NPR) within the European Union for its contribution to international peacekeeping operations, human rights monitoring, refugee policy, health care and cultural life. In addition to its political, social and cultural functions, Tilburg also represents a major regional centre in the Netherlands region of the Rheinland-Alpes region, as well as a major center for research and educational projects.

The Martian Chronicles is a science fiction fix-up novel, published in 1950, by American writer Ray Bradbury that chronicles the exploration and settlement of Mars, the home of indigenous Martians, by Americans leaving a troubled Earth that is eventually devastated by nuclear war.SynopsisThe book projects American society immediately after World War II into a technologically advanced future where the amplification of humanity's potentials to create and destroy have both miraculous and devastating consequences.Events in the chronicle include the apocalyptic destruction of both Martian and human civilizations, both instigated by humans, though there are no stories with settings at the catastrophes.

The Himalayas, or Himalaya (; Sanskrit: ,  "snow",  "dwelling", "abode"), are a mountain range in Asia separating the plains of the Indian subcontinent from the Tibetan Plateau. The range has some of the planet's highest peaks, including the highest, Mount Everest. Over 100 peaks exceeding  in elevation lie in the Himalayas. By contrast, the highest peak outside Asia (Aconcagua, in the Andes) is  tall.The Himalayas abut or cross five countries: Bhutan, India, Nepal, China, and Pakistan.

Belarusians , also known formerly as Byelorussians (from the Byelorussian SSR), Belarussians or Belorusians, are an East Slavic ethnic group native to modern-day Belarus and the immediate region. Over 9.5 million people proclaim Belarusian ethnicity worldwide. Nearly 8 million of Belarusians reside in Belarus, with the United States and Russia being home to more than half a million Belarusians each.LocationBelarusians are an East Slavic ethnic group, who constitute the majority of Belarus' population. Belarusian minority populations live in countries neighboring Belarus: Ukraine, Poland (especially in the Podlaskie Voivodeship), the Russian Federation and Lithuania.

Domenico Gaetano Maria Donizetti ( 29 November 1797 – 8 April 1848 ) was an Italian composer , best known for his operas, and opera works in Florence and Rome . He died on 9 December 2010 at a hospital in Paris. By the second half of the century, Europe had become one of the most developed and prosperous industrial economies in the world. This growth coincided with rising living standards, which made it possible for the country to produce more goods and services, including food and medicine, than any other part of the European Union.

Domenico Cimarosa (; 17 December 1749 – 11 January 1801) was an Italian composer of the Neapolitan school and of the Classical period. He wrote more than eighty operas, the best known of which is Il matrimonio segreto (1792); most of his operas are comedies. He also wrote instrumental works and church music.Cimarosa was principally based in Naples, but spent some of his career in various other parts of Italy, composing for the opera houses of Rome, Venice, Florence and elsewhere. He was engaged by the empress of Russia Catherine the Great as her court composer and conductor between 1787 and 1791.

Tru64 UNIX is a discontinued 64-bit UNIX operating system for the Alpha instruction set architecture (ISA), currently owned by Hewlett-Packard (HP). Previously, Tru64 UNIX was a product of Compaq, and before that, Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC), where it was known as Digital UNIX (originally DEC OSF/1 AXP).As its original name suggests, Tru64 UNIX is based on the OSF/1 operating system. DEC's previous UNIX product was known as Ultrix and was based on BSD.It is unusual among commercial UNIX implementations, as it is built on top of the Mach kernel developed at Carnegie Mellon University.

The Space Shuttle program was the fourth human spaceflight program carried out by the U.S. National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA), which accomplished routine transportation for Earth-to-orbit crew and cargo from 1981 to 2011. Its official name, Space Transportation System (STS), was taken from a 1969 plan for a system of reusable spacecraft of which it was the only item funded for development.The Space Shuttle—composed of an orbiter launched with two reusable solid rocket boosters and a disposable external fuel tank—carried up to eight astronauts and up to  of payload into low Earth orbit (LEO).

Pas-de-Calais ( , `` strait of Calais '' ; ; also ) is a department in northern France named after its French director, Jean Jacques Pasquiat.It was established on August 26, 1787 as the headquarters for the French navy during the war between France and Great Britain; it is home to seven brigades, five infantry divisions and a small fleet of airships. Dictatorships of France were organized under the regent de Ségolères, from 1608 – 1610. From 1608 onwards, these were divided into three principal branches, with the provinces represented by their capitals.

Great Barrier Island  lies in the outer Hauraki Gulf, New Zealand,  north-east of central Auckland. With an area of  it is the sixth-largest island of New Zealand and fourth-largest in the main chain. Its highest point, Mount Hobson, is  above sea level. The local authority is the Auckland Council.The island was initially exploited for its minerals and kauri trees and saw only limited agriculture. In 2013, it was inhabited by 939 people, mostly living from farming and tourism and all living off-the-grid. The majority of the island (around 60% of the total area) is administered as a nature reserve by the Department of Conservation.

Till Death Us Do Part is a British television sitcom that aired on BBC1 from 1965 to 1975 . The first episode ran between 1966 and 1978, and continued for two more seasons, before being shelved after a few seasons. The series lasted one season and was also re-created by Andy Wilco. It premiered on the BBC's Royal Television Theatre in London on November 27, 1974. Written by Peter MacKenzie <pkm@scotlandcourier.com> (Peter MacKeowne) This story is about an elderly woman named Mary who becomes pregnant when she discovers that her only son is missing.

Fighting Fantasy is a series of single-player role-playing gamebooks created by Steve Jackson and Ian Livingstone. The first volume in the series was published in paperback by Puffin in 1982.The series distinguished itself by mixing Choose Your Own Adventure-style storytelling with a dice-based role-playing element included within the books themselves. The caption on many of the covers claimed each title was an adventure "in which YOU are the hero!" The majority of the titles followed a fantasy theme, although science fiction, post-apocalyptic, superhero, and modern horror gamebooks were also published.

Year 1493 ( MCDXCIII ) was a common year starting on Tuesday ( link will display the full calendar ) and ending on Christmas Eve. It is considered the founding of the German Empire and is one of the most important periods in modern times. On December 6, 1583, Pope Gregory II announced that it was to become the official time zone of the Roman Catholic Church. Korea is part of the West Asian archipelago which borders Asia and Africa. Its population of more than 1.4 billion has grown to an estimated 3 million since 1950.

Montague Rhodes James ( 1 August 1862 – 12 June 1936 ) was an English author , medievalist scholar and theologian. He also received honorary Doctor of Divinity from the University of Leicester, a PhD in theology from Oxford University and a doctorate in Christian ethics from St. Andrews University in England.Born on 23 November 1861, Rhodes worked as a clergyman in Lancashire and as a merchant until his death in 1767.He studied at Oxford for many years before continuing his education at Cambridge.He became an early Christian convert to Islam, and is now regarded as an active member of the Islamic world today.
