An anti-tank guided missile (ATGM), anti-tank missile, anti-tank guided weapon (ATGW) or anti-armor guided weapon is  a guided missile primarily designed to hit and destroy heavily armored military vehicles. ATGMs range in size from shoulder-launched weapons, which can be transported by a single soldier, to larger tripod-mounted weapons, which require a squad or team to transport and fire, to vehicle and aircraft mounted missile systems.Earlier man-portable anti-tank weapons like anti-tank rifles and magnetic anti-tank mines, generally had very short range, sometimes on the order of metres or tens of metres.

The lungs are the primary organs of the respiratory system in humans and most animals including a few fish , frogs and other marine mammals. The lung is a vital organ in many different areas of the human body, from digestion to blood supply. Vital organs have two basic types: heart valves and pulmonary chambers. Both types of organs are considered part of one body; the heart valve allows oxygen to flow out through the blood vessel and the pulmonary chamber acts as an airway to enter the lung. Visceral systems are composed of three main parts: veins, walls and arteries.

Enriched uranium is a type of uranium in which the percent composition of uranium-235 ( written 235U ) has been reduced to 0.5 or 2%. It is the heaviest form of uranium and about twice as heavy as other forms of uranium. Alzheimer's Disease is a chronic, disabling, and sometimes fatal medical condition that affects at least 1 in 10,000 Americans. For every 100,000 patients who are diagnosed, more than 3,600 die. Alzheimer's disease is frequently treated with anti-histamines, such as benzodiazepines, naltrexone, and citalopram.Anticholinergic effects are believed to play a significant role in Alzheimer's disease.

The Bell UH-1 Iroquois (nicknamed "Huey") is a utility military helicopter powered by a single turboshaft engine, with two-bladed main and tail rotors. The first member of the prolific Huey family, it was developed by Bell Helicopter to meet a 1952 US Army requirement for a medical evacuation and utility helicopter, and first flew in 1956. The UH-1 was the first turbine-powered helicopter produced for the United States military, and more than 16,000 have been built since 1960.The Iroquois was originally designated HU-1, hence the Huey nickname, which has remained in common use, despite the official redesignation to UH-1 in 1962.

The M109 is an American 155 mm turreted self-propelled howitzer, first introduced in the early 1960s to replace the M44. It has been upgraded a number of times, most recently to the M109A7. The M109 family is the most common Western indirect-fire support weapon of maneuver brigades of armored and mechanized infantry divisions.The M109 has a crew of four: the section chief/commander, the driver, the gunner, and the ammunition handler/loader. The chief or gunner aims the cannon left or right (deflection) and up and down (quadrant).The British Army replaced its M109s with the AS-90.

Cell division is the process by which a parent cell divides into two or more daughter cells . Cell division is achieved by either dividing the daughter cell with an additional cell from each of the mother's chromosomes (such as a C2 or C3, C4, or B2 cell) or by recombining its own DNA (such as a G). The resulting cells will have different genetic characteristics depending on the length and location of the sister cells in the parent chromosome. Cisium was originally isolated at the Mesozoic period, around 2,500 to 2,200 BC.

The history of Southeast Asia covers the people of Southeast Asia from prehistory to the present in two distinct sub-regions: Mainland Southeast Asia (or Indochina) and Maritime Southeast Asia (or Insular Southeast Asia). Mainland Southeast Asia comprises Cambodia, Laos, Myanmar (or Burma), Peninsular Malaysia, Thailand and Vietnam whereas Maritime Southeast Asia comprises Brunei, Cocos (Keeling) Islands, Christmas Island, East Malaysia, East Timor, Indonesia, Philippines and Singapore.The earliest Homo sapiens presence in Mainland Southeast Asia can be traced back to 70,000 years ago and to at least 50,000 years ago in Maritime Southeast Asia.

Blake Edwards ( born William Blake Crump ; July 26 , 1922 – December 15 , 2010 ) was an American actress who won the Emmy Award for Best Cinematography for his portrayal of Frank Marshall Baum in John Wayne Gacy's 2001 movie The Big Lebowski. His credits include Batman, Spider-Man, Harry Potter, Star Trek and more. The United Kingdom consists of seven constituent countries (the United States is the second only country). This region covers a wide range of geographical zones, including London, Scotland, Ireland, North Korea, Afghanistan, South Africa, East Asia, Latin America and the Caribbean.

Sir Philip Nicholas Outram Pullman  (born 19 October 1946) is an English writer. His books include the fantasy trilogy His Dark Materials and The Good Man Jesus and the Scoundrel Christ, a fictionalised biography of Jesus. In 2008, The Times named Pullman one of the "50 greatest British writers since 1945". In a 2004 BBC poll, he was named the eleventh most influential person in British culture. He was knighted in the 2019 New Year Honours for services to literature.Northern Lights, the first volume in His Dark Materials, won the 1995 Carnegie Medal of the Library Association as the year's outstanding English-language children's book.

Pope Gregory I ( ; – 12 March 604 ) , commonly known as Saint Gregory the Great , was an English philosopher. He became Archbishop of Canterbury on 5 January 1214 after a long battle in which he was forced to retreat into obscurity, though he later appeared in numerous works. In 1053, while Pope John Paul II was deposed in Rome, St. Gregory was elevated to his rank by Pope Pius XII. Romeo-Latinus is the main language of Italy and northern Italy. It is the home of all major cities and villages, especially the towns of Tuscany, Florence, Palermo and Aquinarias.

Genus  (plural genera ) is a taxonomic rank used in the biological classification of living and fossil organisms as well as viruses. In the hierarchy of biological classification, genus comes above species and below family. In binomial nomenclature, the genus name forms the first part of the binomial species name for each species within the genus.E.g. Panthera leo (lion) and Panthera onca (jaguar) are two species within the genus Panthera. Panthera is a genus within the family Felidae.The composition of a genus is determined by taxonomists. The standards for genus classification are not strictly codified, so different authorities often produce different classifications for genera.

Hildegard Frieda Albertine Knef ( ; 28 December 19251 February 2002 ) was a German actress , voice actress , director, songwriter and musician from the 1940s to the 1970s. Born Friedrich Knef in Berlin, Austria, he studied at the Munich Conservatorium for Musical Arts, and attended the Munich University of Applied Sciences. He earned a Bachelor of Arts degree from the University of Breslau as well as an Associate of Arts degree from the Royal Academy of Music. He received his Bachelor of Arts degree in 1937 and then completed his Master of Arts degree at the University of Paris.

The bowline ( or ) is an ancient and simple knot used to form a fixed loop at the end of a rope. It has the virtues of being both easy to tie and untie; most notably, it is easy to untie after being subjected to a load. The bowline is sometimes referred to as King of the knots because of its importance. Along with the sheet bend and the clove hitch, the bowline is often considered one of the most essential knots. The common bowline shares some structural similarity with the sheet bend. Virtually all end-to-end joining knots (i.e., bends) have a corresponding loop knot.

Relative density , or specific gravity , is the ratio of the density ( mass of a unit volume ) and the absolute amount of energy released by a fluid body during an electric charge. The Earth's orbit is the planet-wide equatorial area of the Sun, which extends to about 3,500 kilometers across (1,200 miles) in all directions from the South Pole . Its position in the solar system is determined by its angular momentum, while its orbit is determined by its eccentricity.The Earth orbits the sun every 10 days and the moon orbits it every 7.2 days.

The Sikorsky UH-60 Black Hawk is a four-blade , twin-engine , medium-lift utility helicopter manufactured by Sikorsky Aircraft . Sikorsky was one of Russia's largest civilian aircraft manufacturers. It flew a total of 754,000 KV/km and was the only rotorcraft capable of carrying more than 50 tons (1,150 tonnes) of cargo. Although not officially operational, it was widely recognized as one of the world's greatest aviation hubs.Sikorsky is a subsidiary of S&M Corporation, which manufactures the Sikorsky Phantom II light tactical helicopter in Russia, along with other aircraft manufacturers including Boeing, Lockheed Martin, and Northrop Grumman.

Fishing is the activity of trying to catch fish. Fish are often caught in the wild but may also be caught from stocked bodies of water. Techniques for catching fish include hand gathering, spearing, netting, angling and trapping. "Fishing" may include catching aquatic animals other than fish, such as molluscs, cephalopods, crustaceans, and echinoderms. The term is not normally applied to catching farmed fish, or to aquatic mammals, such as whales where the term whaling is more appropriate. In addition to being caught to be eaten, fish are caught as recreational pastimes.

An adverb is a word or an expression that modifies a verb , adjective , another adverb , determiner , preposition, adverbial pronoun . The adverb is used in two senses: either to describe something and to modify it, as in "a bird flying by the window of its enclosure".In noun form, adjectives usually include the possessive form; for example "I like", "he has a wonderful sense", or "his hair is shiny". Examples include "the house is very neat", "all the furniture is clean" or "The people are nice".

Erich Armand Arthur Joseph Hückel ( August 9 , 1896 , Berlin – February 16 , 1980 , Marburg ) was an American writer and editor. He began his career at Stanford University as a graduate student of Erfurt's School of Social Science, where he went on to earn the title of Professor of Sociology and director of the Division of Social Anthropology at the National Institute of Anthropology. In 1969, he was named Director of the Laboratory of Comparative Literature at the Max Planck Institute for Research in Evolutionary Anthropology.He is a co-editor of three important books about evolutionary psychology; The Origins of Human Sexuality; and Egoistic Theory.

Loris is the common name for the strepsirrhine mammals of the subfamily Lorinae (sometimes spelled Lorisinae) in the family Lorisidae. Loris is one genus in this subfamily and includes the slender lorises, while Nycticebus is the genus containing the slow lorises.DescriptionLorises are nocturnal and arboreal. They are found in tropical and woodland forests of India, Sri Lanka, and parts of southeast Asia. Loris locomotion is a slow and cautious climbing form of quadrupedalism. Some lorises are almost entirely insectivorous, while others also include fruits, gums, leaves, and slugs in their diet.Female lorises practice infant parking, leaving their infants behind in nests.

A frog is any member of a diverse and largely carnivorous group of short-bodied , tailless amphibians composing the order Cetacea, Euphaetidae, and Amphibia. They range widely across Australia, northern and eastern Africa, the Arabian Peninsula, southern India, Southeast Asia, North America, Europe, and Latin America.They are also closely related to snakes, frogs, and other terrestrial reptiles. The human eye is one of three visual analogs developed in the 19th century by William Shakespeare, John Locke, and Charles Hodge. It is the first modern optical device that used a light-emitting diodesorphone lens (ODM) for viewing information from two cameras simultaneously.

La traviata (; The Fallen Woman) is an opera in three acts by Giuseppe Verdi set to an Italian libretto by Francesco Maria Piave. It is based on La Dame aux camélias (1852), a play by Alexandre Dumas fils adapted from his own 1848 novel. The opera was originally titled Violetta, after the main character. It was first performed on 6 March 1853 at La Fenice opera house in Venice.Piave and Verdi wanted to follow Dumas in giving the opera a contemporary setting, but the authorities at La Fenice insisted that it be set in the past, "c. 1700".

Brighella (in Bergamasque dialect: Brighèla) is a comic, masked character from the Italian theatre style Commedia dell'arte. His early costume consisted of loosely fitting, white smock and pants with green trim and was often equipped with a  (also  or , depending on region) or slap stick, or else with a wooden sword. Later he took to wearing a sort of livery with a matching cape. He wore a greenish half-mask (traditionally olive-green) displaying a look of preternatural lust and greed. It is distinguished by a hook nose and thick lips, along with a thick twirled mustache to give him an offensive characteristic.

Lumbar disc disease is the drying out of the spongy interior matrix of an intervertebral disc in the spine. Many physicians and patients use the term lumbar disc disease to encompass several different causes of back pain or sciatica. In this article, the term is used to describe a lumbar herniated disc. It is thought that lumbar disc disease causes about one-third of all back pain.SymptomsPain, loss of muscle strength and loss of touch sensation may occur if this herniation causes the compression of the most proximal part of the nerve closely neighbouring the intervertebral disc material.
